diagnosis: AAA screening, see Abdominal aortic aneurysm screening
symptoms: Abdominal aortic aneurysm screening, also known as AAA screening, is a medical test used to detect an aneurysm in the abdominal aorta. Symptoms of an aneurysm include abdominal or back pain, feeling faint or dizzy, and a pulsating feeling in the abdomen.

Abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) is a condition where the aorta, the largest artery in the body, becomes abnormally large and weak. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, back pain, and a pulsating feeling in the stomach. In some cases, a person may also experience dizziness, nausea, and fatigue.

Abdominal aortic aneurysm is a ballooning of the aorta in the abdomen, which can cause pain in the abdomen, back, or legs. Other symptoms may include dizziness, sweating, and nausea. If the aneurysm becomes large enough, it can rupture, leading to severe abdominal pain and internal bleeding.

is used to check for an aneurysm in the abdominal aorta.

Abdominal aortic aneurysm screening is a test used to detect a bulging or weakened area in the abdominal aorta, which can be a sign of an aneurysm. Symptoms of an aneurysm may include abdominal pain, back pain, and loss of pulse in the legs.

is a medical procedure that ends a pregnancy.

Abortion is the termination of a pregnancy, usually performed by a doctor. It can involve either the removal of the fetus or the disruption of the uterine lining. Symptoms may include cramping, bleeding, and general discomfort.

es are pockets of infection that can form in many parts of the body

Abscesses are localized collections of pus that form due to infection. They are typically painful and can occur in many parts of the body, including the skin, mouth, throat, and lungs. Symptoms can include swelling, warmth, redness, and tenderness in the affected area.

is a skin condition characterized by areas of dark, velvety discoloration in body folds and creases

Acanthosis nigricans is a skin condition that causes dark, velvety patches of discoloration in areas such as the neck, armpits, groin, and other body folds and creases. It is usually seen in people who are overweight or have diabetes.

is a rare disorder of the esophagus.

Achalasia is a rare disorder of the esophagus that causes difficulty swallowing, chest pain, regurgitation, and weight loss. Symptoms can worsen over time, leading to serious complications such as aspiration pneumonia.

Acid and chemical burns are caused by contact with an acidic or basic solution. Symptoms include redness, pain, blisters, and tissue destruction. The affected area may also appear white or gray and may have a burning sensation. Long term effects may include scarring and disfigurement.

diagnosis: Acid reflux in babies, see Reflux in babies
symptoms: Acid reflux in babies is a condition where stomach acid flows back into the esophagus, causing discomfort and pain. Symptoms can include frequent spitting up, irritability, difficulty eating, and crying during or after feedings.

is an inflammatory skin condition that occurs when the oil glands (sebaceous glands) become clogged and infected.

Acne is a skin condition characterized by clogged and infected oil glands (sebaceous glands) which can lead to inflammation. Symptoms of acne can include redness, swelling, and the development of pus-filled bumps on the skin.

is a benign tumor that grows on the main (vestibulocochlear) nerve leading from your inner ear to your brain

Acoustic neuroma is a benign tumor that affects the vestibulocochlear nerve, which is the main nerve that connects the inner ear to the brain. Symptoms may include hearing loss, tinnitus, vertigo, and balance problems.

is a hormonal disorder that results from too much growth hormone being released in the body.

Acromegaly is a hormonal disorder caused by an excess of growth hormone in the body. Symptoms include enlarged hands and feet, thickening of the skin, increased sweating, joint pain, and fatigue. Other symptoms can include enlarged organs, vision problems, and changes in facial features.

are scaly patches of skin that form on sun-exposed areas, such as the face, scalp, hands, and arms.

Actinic keratoses are scaly patches of skin that appear on sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the face, scalp, hands, and arms. They are caused by long-term sun exposure and are considered pre-cancerous.

is a chronic granulomatous disease caused by a group of bacteria

Actinomycosis is a chronic bacterial infection that causes granulomas, or masses of inflamed tissue, to form in the body. It is caused by a group of bacteria known as actinomycetes, which are commonly found in the mouth, nose, throat, and gastrointestinal tract. Symptoms of actinomycosis include fever, fatigue, weight loss, night sweats, and pain in the infected area. It is often misdiagnosed as a tumor or abscess, and treatment typically involves antibiotics, surgery, or both.

is a form of ancient Chinese medicine in which thin needles are inserted into specific points of the body to treat a variety of conditions.

Acupuncture is an ancient Chinese medical practice in which thin needles are inserted into specific points of the body to treat a variety of health issues. It is believed that the needles stimulate different points of the body to help treat pain, as well as other physical, mental, and emotional ailments.

is an inflammation of the gallbladder that can cause severe abdominal pain.

Acute cholecystitis is an inflammation of the gallbladder that causes severe abdominal pain, usually on the right side of the abdomen below the ribs. It can also cause fever, nausea, and vomiting.

(AKI) is a sudden episode of kidney failure or kidney damage that happens within a few hours or a few days.

Acute kidney injury (AKI) is a sudden episode of kidney failure or kidney damage that can occur within a few hours or days. Symptoms include decreased urine output, swelling in the legs, ankles, and feet, fatigue, shortness of breath, and confusion.

Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia is a type of cancer that affects the white blood cells. Symptoms of this condition can include fatigue, pale skin, fever, bruising and bleeding easily, swollen lymph nodes, night sweats, and weight loss.

(AML)

Acute myeloid leukaemia (AML) is a type of cancer of the blood and bone marrow, where the body produces an abnormal number of immature white blood cells. Symptoms of AML include fatigue, shortness of breath, easy bruising, frequent infections, and pale skin.

is a sudden inflammation of the pancreas.

Acute pancreatitis is a sudden, severe inflammation of the pancreas, causing abdominal pain and other symptoms such as nausea, vomiting, and fever. It can be life-threatening if not treated promptly.

(ARDS) is a serious condition affecting the lungs.

ARDS is a serious condition that affects the lungs and causes difficulty breathing. Symptoms include severe shortness of breath, rapid breathing, low oxygen levels in the blood, and rapid heart rate. It can also cause fluid buildup in the lungs, which can lead to respiratory failure.

is a disorder in which the adrenal glands do not produce enough of certain hormones

Addison's disease is a disorder caused by the adrenal glands not producing enough of certain hormones. Symptoms include extreme fatigue, low blood pressure, muscle weakness, weight loss, darkening of the skin, and salt cravings.

is a surgical procedure to remove adenoids

Adenoidectomy is a surgical procedure that involves the removal of the adenoid glands. This procedure is used to treat enlarged adenoids, which can cause difficulty breathing through the nose, snoring, and recurrent ear infections.

cause the eyes to become increasingly cloudy and blurry.

Age-related cataracts cause vision to become cloudy and blurry and light to seem too bright or glaring. Objects may also appear less colorful than usual.

is a common eye condition and a leading cause of blindness in people over the age of 60.

Age-related macular degeneration (AMD) is a common eye condition and a leading cause of blindness among people over the age of 60. Symptoms of AMD include blurred vision, difficulty seeing objects clearly, and decreased central vision. People with AMD may also experience difficulty adapting to changes in light levels, trouble recognizing faces, and straight lines appearing wavy.

is an anxiety disorder characterized by feelings of fear and anxiety in situations

Agoraphobia is an anxiety disorder where the person feels intense fear and anxiety in certain situations, such as being in public places, being in open spaces, or being in unfamiliar environments. The person may also experience physical symptoms such as sweating, trembling, and feeling dizzy. They may also avoid certain activities and places in order to avoid the anxiety.

is a condition in which one or more air or gas bubbles enter a vein or artery and become trapped in the circulatory system.

Air or gas embolism is a condition in which air or gas bubbles enter the circulatory system and become trapped in the veins or arteries. This can cause blockages, leading to symptoms such as chest pain, shortness of breath, dizziness, and confusion.

is a rare, non-contagious, genetically inherited condition which is present from birth and characterized by the complete or partial absence of pigment in the skin, hair and eyes

Albinism is a genetic condition that is present from birth and is characterized by a lack of pigment in the skin, hair, and eyes. It is not contagious, and it is rare.

can lead to a variety of physical and psychological health problems.

Alcohol misuse can cause physical symptoms such as liver damage, nausea, and headaches. It can also lead to psychological issues such as depression, anxiety, and memory loss. Long-term misuse of alcohol can also increase the risk of developing cancer, heart disease, and other chronic illnesses.

is caused by drinking large amounts of alcohol in a short period of time

Alcohol poisoning is a serious and potentially life-threatening condition caused by drinking large amounts of alcohol in a short period of time. Symptoms can include confusion, vomiting, seizures, slow breathing, and decreased body temperature. In extreme cases, alcohol poisoning can cause coma, brain damage, and even death.

(ARLD)

Alcohol-related liver disease (ARLD) is caused by excessive drinking over a long period of time. Symptoms include jaundice, fatigue, nausea, abdominal pain, and loss of appetite. It can lead to serious health complications such as cirrhosis, liver failure, and even death.

Alcohol-related liver disease (ARLD) is caused by excessive drinking over a long period of time. Symptoms of ARLD include jaundice, fatigue, nausea, abdominal pain, and loss of appetite. In severe cases, it can lead to serious health complications such as cirrhosis, liver failure, and even death.

The Alexander Technique is a form of physical therapy that teaches people how to move and sit with better posture and coordination. It focuses on the relationship between the mind and body and how small changes in posture can lead to improved physical and mental wellbeing. Symptoms that can be addressed with the Alexander Technique include back pain, neck pain, and breathing problems. It can also help with posture, balance, coordination, and stress relief.

is an inherited disorder that affects the way the body breaks down and processes certain amino acids.

Alkaptonuria is an inherited disorder which causes an accumulation of a pigment called homogentisic acid in the body, leading to the darkening of connective tissues and urine. It can also cause joint pain, arthritis, and heart and kidney problems.

can cause sneezing, itchy nose, runny nose, and congestion.

Allergic rhinitis is a condition that can cause a range of symptoms, including sneezing, itchy nose, runny nose, and congestion. These symptoms are often triggered by allergens in the environment.

may cause sneezing, itchy eyes, and a runny nose.

Allergies can cause a range of symptoms including sneezing, itchy eyes, and a runny nose.

is a condition that can occur when people climb or travel to a high altitude too quickly.

Altitude sickness is a condition that can be caused by ascending to high altitudes too quickly. Symptoms can include headache, dizziness, fatigue, difficulty sleeping, loss of appetite and nausea.

Alzheimer's disease is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder that causes memory loss, confusion, and difficulty with daily activities. It is the most common form of dementia and typically worsens over time. Symptoms can include difficulty with communication, language, and problem-solving, as well as changes in behavior and personality.

Amblyopia (also known as lazy eye) is a vision disorder that affects one or both eyes, resulting in decreased vision. It is caused by abnormal visual development in childhood, often due to one eye being more dominant than the other, or due to strabismus (crossed eyes). Symptoms include blurred vision, difficulty judging distances, and difficulty seeing in 3D.

Amnesia is a memory disorder in which a person is unable to recall events or memories from their past. It can be caused by physical trauma, medical conditions, psychological trauma, or drug use. Symptoms may include difficulty forming new memories, difficulty recalling old memories, confusion, and disorientation. It can also cause a person to forget their identity, language, or other aspects of their life.

is a procedure used to diagnose genetic disorders in a fetus.

Amniocentesis is a procedure used to diagnose genetic disorders in a fetus. It involves taking a sample of the amniotic fluid that surrounds the fetus and testing it for genetic abnormalities. Symptoms of the procedure include abdominal discomfort, cramping, and a slight risk of miscarriage.

of the left leg was necessary due to a severe infection.

A severe infection in the left leg led to the need for amputation. Surgery was required to remove the leg in order to prevent the infection from spreading.

is a rare condition that affects the body's organs and tissues.

Amyloidosis is a rare condition where abnormal proteins, called amyloid, accumulate in the organs and tissues of the body. This can cause problems with the functioning of the organs and tissues and can lead to organ failure. Symptoms vary depending on which organs are affected, but may include fatigue, weight loss, and unexplained swelling.

can lead to serious long-term, even permanent, health problems.

Mismanagement of anabolic steroids can result in a variety of serious physical and mental health issues, including liver damage, heart disease, and fertility problems. It can also cause mental health issues such as depression, aggression, and addiction.

diagnosis: Anaemia (iron deficiency), see Iron deficiency anaemia
symptoms: Anaemia (iron deficiency) is a condition in which the body does not have enough healthy red blood cells, resulting in a decrease in the amount of oxygen that can be carried throughout the body. Symptoms of anaemia can include fatigue, weakness, pale skin, dizziness, headaches, chest pain, and difficulty concentrating.

diagnosis: Anaemia (vitamin B12 or folate deficiency), see Vitamin B12 or folate deficiency anaemia
symptoms: Vitamin B12 or folate deficiency anaemia is a condition in which the body does not have enough healthy red blood cells due to a lack of vitamin B12 or folate. Symptoms may include fatigue, paleness, shortness of breath, dizziness, headaches, and an enlarged spleen. In some cases, a person may also experience a sore tongue, difficulty concentrating, and a decreased appetite.

is a medical condition in which a person is unable to feel pain or other sensations.

Anaesthesia is a medical condition which causes a person to be unable to feel pain or other sensations. It can be caused by a variety of medications or techniques which block the transmission of signals from the nerves to the brain. Symptoms include numbness, lack of feeling, and loss of consciousness.

is a rare form of cancer that occurs in the anus.

Anal cancer is a form of cancer that affects the anus and is relatively rare. Symptoms of anal cancer can include pain, bleeding, itching, and changes in bowel habits.

is a tear in the lining of the anus

Anal fissure is a tear in the lining of the anus which can cause pain, itching, and bleeding. Symptoms can range from mild to severe depending on the severity of the tear. Common symptoms include burning and stinging pain during and after bowel movements, bright red blood on the toilet paper, and visible tears or cracks in the skin around the anus.

is a tunnel that develops between the end of the bowel and the skin near the anus (the opening where stool leaves the body).

Anal fistula is a tunnel-like structure that develops between the end of the bowel and the skin near the anus. It causes symptoms such as itching, pain, and discharge of pus or blood. It may also cause discomfort during bowel movements.

, bloating, and nausea

The symptoms described in the text include anal pain, bloating, and nausea. These symptoms could be indicative of an underlying digestive issue, such as irritable bowel syndrome, Crohn's disease, or an infection.

is a severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction.

Anaphylaxis is an extreme allergic reaction that can be life-threatening. Symptoms can include shortness of breath, swelling of the face, throat or tongue, dizziness, hives, and difficulty swallowing.

(AIS)

Androgen Insensitivity Syndrome (AIS) is a genetic disorder in which a person's cells do not respond to androgens, the male hormones that are responsible for male physical characteristics. Symptoms can include the presence of female genitalia, the absence of male genitalia, and infertility in those with a 46,XY karyotype. Other symptoms can include a lack of facial or body hair, poor muscular development, and a short stature.

diagnosis: Aneurysm (abdominal aortic), see Abdominal aortic aneurysm
symptoms: Abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) is a bulge in the wall of the aorta, the main artery that carries blood from the heart to the rest of the body. Symptoms of AAA can include abdominal or back pain, feeling faint, nausea, and loss of appetite. In some cases, there may be no symptoms until the aneurysm ruptures, which can be fatal.

A brain aneurysm is a bulge or ballooning in a blood vessel in the brain. It can leak or rupture, causing bleeding into the brain (hemorrhagic stroke). Symptoms may include a sudden and severe headache, nausea and vomiting, stiff neck, confusion, blurred or double vision, and loss of consciousness. In some cases, a brain aneurysm may not cause any symptoms.

Angelman syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects the nervous system. Symptoms include developmental delays, intellectual disability, seizures, sleep disturbances, jerky movements, difficulty speaking, and a happy demeanor.

is chest pain or discomfort that occurs when some part of the heart does not receive enough blood

Angina is a symptom of a heart condition in which chest pain or discomfort is experienced due to an insufficient supply of blood to the heart. It can be a sign of a heart attack or other heart issue. Symptoms may include tightness or pressure in the chest, shortness of breath, fatigue, and pain in the shoulder, arm, neck, or jaw.

is a condition that causes swelling of the face, lips, tongue, and/or throat.

Angioedema is a condition that causes sudden and severe swelling of the face, lips, tongue, and/or throat. Symptoms may include swelling of the face, lips, tongue, and/or throat, difficulty swallowing, difficulty breathing, and hives.

revealed a large aneurysm in the patient's left anterior descending artery.

The patient has a large aneurysm in the left anterior descending artery, which was revealed through angiography.

diagnosis: Angioplasty, see Coronary angioplasty and stent insertion
symptoms: Angioplasty is a procedure used to treat coronary artery disease. It involves inserting a small balloon-tipped catheter into an artery and inflating the balloon to widen the artery, allowing for improved blood flow. In some cases, a stent is also inserted to help keep the artery open. Symptoms of coronary artery disease may include chest pain, shortness of breath, and fatigue.

Animal and human bites cause pain, swelling, redness, and bruising at the site of the bite. They can also lead to infection, which can cause fever, chills, swollen lymph nodes, and pus. In some cases, animal or human bites can even lead to serious health problems, such as rabies.

Animal and human bites cause pain, swelling, redness, and bruising at the site of the bite. They can also lead to infection, with symptoms of fever, chills, swollen lymph nodes and pus. In severe cases, animal or human bites can cause serious health problems, such as rabies.
The patient is experiencing pain in their ankle. The pain is localized and is described as aching and throbbing. The pain worsens with activity and is relieved with rest.

is a type of arthritis that affects the spine.

Ankylosing spondylitis is a type of arthritis that affects the spine and causes inflammation, pain, and stiffness in the lower back and hips. It can also cause fatigue, loss of appetite, and difficulty sleeping. Over time, the inflammation can cause the spine to fuse, leading to a hunched posture.

is an eating disorder that affects a person's mental, physical, and emotional health

Anorexia nervosa is a serious mental health disorder characterized by an extreme restriction of food intake, leading to a number of physical and emotional symptoms. These symptoms include extreme weight loss, an intense fear of gaining weight, a distorted body image, and a preoccupation with food and body weight. Other physical symptoms include fatigue, low blood pressure, and irregular heart rate. Emotional symptoms can include depression, anxiety, and an inability to focus.

diagnosis: Anosmia, see Lost or changed sense of smell
symptoms: Anosmia is a condition in which a person has lost or changed their sense of smell. Symptoms of anosmia include an inability to smell or taste, a decreased appetite, and an inability to recognize odors.

are used to treat heartburn, a burning sensation in the chest or throat.

Heartburn is a burning sensation in the chest or throat which can be treated with antacids. It is often accompanied by a sour taste in the mouth, chest pain and difficulty swallowing.

are not working

The patient is not responding to treatment with antibiotics, indicating that the infection is not being treated effectively. Symptoms may include fever, fatigue, and other signs of infection.

are used to reduce the risk of stroke and other serious medical conditions.

Anticoagulant medicines are used to reduce the risk of stroke and other serious medical conditions by thinning the blood and preventing the formation of blood clots. This reduces the risk of blocked arteries and other issues caused by blood clots.

can cause a range of side effects.

Antidepressants can cause a variety of unpleasant side effects, such as nausea, headaches, dizziness, insomnia, sexual dysfunction, dry mouth, and increased sweating. In some cases, they can also cause agitation, anxiety, and suicidal thoughts.

are used to treat fungal infections.

Antifungal medicines are used to treat fungal infections, which can cause symptoms such as itching, redness, discharge, and pain. These medicines are typically taken orally or applied topically to the infected area.

are used to relieve symptoms of allergies, including:

Antihistamines are used to relieve symptoms of allergies, such as sneezing, itchy and watery eyes, runny nose, and itchy throat. They can also help with congestion, coughing, and hives.

is an autoimmune disorder that affects the clotting system.

Antiphospholipid Syndrome (APS) is an autoimmune disorder that causes the body to produce antibodies that attack phospholipids, which are fats in the blood that help with clotting. Symptoms include recurrent miscarriages, stroke, and blood clots in the legs and lungs. People with APS may also experience fatigue, headaches, and cold hands and feet.

Antisocial personality disorder is a mental health condition in which a person has a long-term pattern of manipulating, exploiting, or violating the rights of others. People with antisocial personality disorder tend to antagonize, manipulate or treat others harshly or with callous indifference. They show no remorse for their behavior, and may have an exaggerated sense of self-worth. Other symptoms include disregarding social norms, impulsivity, aggression, and irresponsibility.
The symptoms are an itchy anus, also known as an itchy bottom.

Anxiety disorders in children can manifest in physical, emotional, and behavioral symptoms. These symptoms can include difficulty sleeping, restlessness, difficulty concentrating, difficulty controlling worry, physical symptoms such as headaches and stomachaches, and avoidance of social situations.

The patient is experiencing symptoms of shortness of breath, tiredness, chest pain, and palpitations. These are all signs of aortic valve replacement, which is a procedure to replace a damaged or diseased aortic valve with a new one. The procedure is necessary to ensure proper blood flow to the heart and other organs.

is an inability to understand or express language, usually caused by brain damage.

Aphasia is a language disorder caused by brain damage, which results in difficulty understanding or expressing language. People with aphasia may struggle to produce or comprehend words, sentences, or conversations.

is a condition in which the appendix becomes inflamed and filled with pus

Appendicitis is an inflammation of the appendix which causes abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and fever. In some cases, the appendix may become filled with pus, leading to further complications. Symptoms may worsen over time and may require medical attention in order to avoid rupture.

is a condition in which the heart beats irregularly.

Arrhythmia is a condition where the heart beats irregularly, either too fast or too slow, or with an irregular pattern. Symptoms of arrhythmia can include palpitations, shortness of breath, chest pain, dizziness, or fatigue.

is a clot formed in a blood vessel due to a slow flow of blood

Arterial thrombosis is a medical condition that occurs when a clot forms in an artery due to a slow flow of blood. Symptoms of arterial thrombosis include pain in the affected area, numbness and tingling, discoloration of the skin, and coldness in the affected area. In some cases, the clot can lead to a complete blockage of the artery, which can result in tissue death.

is a painful condition that affects the joints.

Arthritis is a condition that causes joint pain and stiffness, often making everyday activities difficult. It can also cause inflammation, swelling and tenderness in the affected area.

is a minimally invasive surgical procedure used to diagnose and treat joint problems.

Arthroscopy is a surgical procedure used to diagnose and treat joint problems. It is minimally invasive and involves the use of a small camera inserted into the joint to diagnose and treat the issue. Symptoms that may be treated with arthroscopy include pain, swelling, stiffness, and instability in the joint.

is a chronic lung disease caused by breathing in asbestos fibers.

Asbestosis is a lung disease caused by the inhalation of asbestos fibers, which leads to inflammation and scarring of the lungs. Symptoms of asbestosis include shortness of breath, chest tightness, and a dry cough. Other symptoms may include fatigue, clubbing of the fingers, and an increased risk of lung cancer.

Spectrum Disorder

Asperger's is a type of Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) that is characterized by difficulties with social interaction, communication, and behavior. People with Asperger's often have difficulty understanding and interpreting nonverbal communication, such as body language and facial expressions, and have difficulty making and maintaining friendships. They may also have difficulty understanding the perspectives and emotions of others, and may have restricted and repetitive behaviors.

is a fungal infection that can affect one or both lungs.

Aspergillosis is a fungal infection that can cause symptoms such as coughing, chest pain, and difficulty breathing. It can also cause fever, fatigue, and shortness of breath. It can affect one or both lungs.

poisoning can cause serious symptoms, including nausea, vomiting, drowsiness, confusion and ringing in the ears.

Aspirin poisoning can lead to severe symptoms such as nausea, vomiting, drowsiness, confusion and ringing in the ears. These symptoms can be very dangerous if left untreated.

is a chronic, long-term respiratory illness that can cause a person to experience difficulty breathing, wheezing, coughing, and chest tightness.

Asthma is a chronic respiratory illness characterized by difficulty breathing, wheezing, coughing, and chest tightness. These symptoms can be severe and require medical attention.

is a vision disorder caused by an irregularly shaped cornea

Astigmatism is a vision disorder that causes blurred vision due to an irregularly shaped cornea. It can cause problems with both near and far vision, and can lead to headaches, eyestrain, and fatigue. The condition can be corrected with eyeglasses, contact lenses, or refractive surgery.

is a neurological disorder that affects the coordination of movement.

Ataxia is a neurological disorder that impairs the coordination of movement. Symptoms may include clumsiness, slurred speech, poor coordination, lack of muscle control, and difficulty walking. Other symptoms may include tremors, confusion, and problems with vision, balance, and speech.

is a condition in which the arteries become narrowed by a buildup of plaque.

Atherosclerosis is a medical condition in which plaque accumulates and builds up on the walls of the arteries, causing them to narrow over time. This can lead to reduced blood flow and a higher risk of stroke, heart attack, and other cardiovascular complications.

is a common fungal infection caused by a variety of fungi.

Athlete's foot is a fungal infection that affects the skin on the feet and toes. It is caused by a variety of fungi, and is most commonly characterised by itching, redness, and flaking of the skin. It can also cause cracking and scaling of the feet and toes.

is a chronic inflammatory skin condition that is characterized by red, itchy, and scaly patches of skin.

Atopic eczema is a skin condition that causes red, itchy, and scaly patches on the skin. It is a chronic, inflammatory condition that can be quite uncomfortable.

is a type of arrhythmia, which is an irregular heart rhythm.

Atrial fibrillation is an irregular heart rhythm caused by an arrhythmia. It causes an irregular and often rapid heartbeat, which can lead to other heart-related complications. Symptoms can include chest pain, shortness of breath, dizziness, and palpitations.

is a mental health condition that affects how well someone can sit still, focus, and pay attention.

ADHD is a mental health condition characterized by difficulty focusing and paying attention, as well as hyperactivity and impulsivity. Symptoms may include difficulty sustaining attention, difficulty controlling behavior, and excessive talking.

is a condition that affects how the brain processes sound.

Auditory processing disorder (APD) is a condition that affects the way the brain interprezes sound. People with APD struggle to understand and process what they hear, resulting in difficulty following directions, concentrating, and distinguishing between similar sounding words. They may also have difficulty with sound localization, such as determining where a sound is coming from.

is a complex neurobehavioral condition that includes impairments in social interaction and developmental language and communication skills combined with rigid, repetitive behaviors.

Autism is a neurological condition characterized by impairments in social interaction, communication, and repetitive behaviors. It can also cause difficulty with understanding language, developing verbal and nonverbal communication, and forming relationships.

(ADPKD) is a genetic disorder characterized by the growth of numerous cysts filled with fluid in the kidneys.

ADPKD is a genetic disorder that causes the growth of numerous cysts filled with fluid in the kidneys. Symptoms may include back or side pain, high blood pressure, blood in the urine, and kidney failure.

(ARPKD) is a rare, inherited disorder that affects the kidneys and liver.

ARPKD is an inherited disorder that affects the kidneys and liver. Symptoms may include enlarged kidneys, high blood pressure, fluid in the abdomen, and decreased urine output. It may also lead to liver problems such as biliary atresia and portal hypertension.

Avian flu, also known as Bird flu, is an infectious disease of birds caused by type A strains of the influenza virus. Symptoms of the virus in birds can include respiratory distress, reduced appetite, greenish diarrhea, and a drop in egg production. In some cases, the virus can cause more severe symptoms such as paralysis, tremors, and swelling of the head and neck.

is a type of vaginal inflammation caused by the overgrowth of bacteria naturally found in the vagina, which upsets the natural balance.

Bacterial vaginosis is an infection of the vagina marked by an overgrowth of bacteria and an imbalance of natural flora. Symptoms include an abnormal vaginal discharge, a fishy odor, itching, and burning.

Baker's cyst is a condition where a fluid-filled sac forms at the back of the knee. Symptoms include swelling and stiffness in the knee and calf area, a feeling of tightness behind the knee, and pain when bending or straightening the knee.

is a common condition that affects men.

Balanitis is an inflammation of the head of the penis that can cause redness, itching, and discharge. Symptoms can include pain or discomfort when urinating, difficulty pulling back the foreskin, and an unpleasant smell.

Bartholin's cyst is a small, fluid-filled sac located near the opening of the vagina. Symptoms include a lump near the opening of the vagina, swelling, redness, and pain. It may also cause discomfort during sexual intercourse.

diagnosis: Basal cell carcinoma, see Skin cancer (non-melanoma)
symptoms: Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer (non-melanoma). It is typically caused by overexposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun, and is characterized by a slow-growing, painless, pink or pearly-white bump on the skin. It can also present as a flat, scaly area.

have been found in the bedroom

The symptoms of a bedbug infestation in the bedroom include the presence of small, red-brown bugs, small dark spots on bedding and furniture, and a musty odor. Bedbugs may also cause itchy, red bumps on the skin.

Bedwetting in children is a common condition where a child is unable to control their bladder and involuntarily urinates while sleeping. It is usually more common in younger children and can last until the age of 8 or 9. It can cause embarrassment and anxiety for the child and can lead to social issues.

Behçet's disease is a rare disorder that causes inflammation of the blood vessels. It can cause symptoms such as ulcers in the mouth and on the genitals, skin rashes, red and painful eyes, joint pain, and inflammation of the digestive system. It can also lead to more serious complications such as blindness, stroke, and inflammation of the brain and spinal cord.

diagnosis: Being sick, see Diarrhoea and vomiting
symptoms: The person is showing signs of being sick with diarrhoea and vomiting. These are common symptoms of an infection or digestive disorder.

is a form of facial paralysis that results in an inability to control facial muscles on the affected side.

Bell's palsy is a form of facial paralysis that causes an inability to control the muscles on one side of the face. Symptoms include drooping of the mouth, eye, and cheek on the affected side, decreased ability to make facial expressions, and difficulty eating and drinking.

A benign brain tumour is an abnormal growth of tissue in the brain that does not contain cancer cells. Symptoms may include headaches, seizures, balance problems, memory loss, personality changes, and vision or hearing issues. In some cases, a benign brain tumour can cause increased pressure in the skull, resulting in nausea, vomiting, and blurred vision.

Benign prostate enlargement is a condition in which the prostate gland is enlarged, but not due to cancer. Symptoms include an increased frequency of urination, difficulty starting or stopping the flow of urine, weak or interrupted urine stream, and a feeling of incomplete bladder emptying.

are medications that are used to treat a number of conditions, including high blood pressure, heart failure, and anxiety.

Beta blockers are medications used to treat high blood pressure, heart failure, and anxiety. They work by reducing the activity of certain nerves in the body, allowing the heart to beat slower and the blood vessels to relax, which helps to reduce blood pressure and improve the symptoms of heart failure. They can also reduce the physical symptoms of anxiety, such as a racing heart, trembling, and sweating.

Bile duct cancer (cholangiocarcinoma) is a type of cancer that affects the bile ducts, which are tubes that carry bile from the liver to the small intestine. Symptoms of bile duct cancer include jaundice, abdominal pain, weight loss, itching, fatigue, and clay-colored stools.

Bilharzia, also known as Schistosomiasis, is an infectious disease caused by parasitic worms. It is spread through contact with contaminated water and can cause symptoms such as fever, fatigue, and abdominal pain. In severe cases, it can lead to serious organ damage.

is a serious condition where you frequently eat large amounts of food

Binge Eating Disorder is a serious condition characterized by eating large amounts of food in a short period of time, often in an out-of-control manner. It is often accompanied by feelings of guilt and shame. Symptoms include eating rapidly, eating until feeling uncomfortably full, eating large amounts of food even when not hungry, and eating alone due to embarrassment.

is a mental health condition that causes extreme mood swings that include emotional highs (mania or hypomania) and lows (depression).

Bipolar disorder is a mental health condition that causes drastic changes in mood, ranging from extreme happiness (mania or hypomania) to deep sadness (depression). These changes can be sudden and can last for long periods of time.

is a contagious disease caused by the H5N1 virus.

Bird flu is a contagious disease caused by the H5N1 virus that affects birds, including poultry. Symptoms include lack of energy, coughing, sneezing, and reduced egg production. In some cases, the virus can be fatal.

are usually harmless and cause no medical problems

Birthmarks are discolored patches of skin that appear at birth or shortly after. They can vary in size, shape, color, and texture, and can be found anywhere on the body. Birthmarks are usually harmless and cause no medical problems, although they may require monitoring to ensure they do not change in size, shape, or color over time.

diagnosis: Bite (animal or human), see Animal and human bites
symptoms:
Animal bites can cause swelling, pain, redness, and bruising. Human bites can cause similar symptoms, as well as puncture wounds, infection, and tetanus. Both types of bites should be treated by a doctor as soon as possible.

Animal and human bites can cause swelling, pain, redness, bruising, puncture wounds, infection, and tetanus. It is important to seek medical attention immediately to prevent further complications.

is a type of cancer that begins when cells in the bladder start to grow uncontrollably.

Bladder Pain Syndrome (Interstitial Cystitis) is a chronic condition characterized by persistent pain in the bladder and pelvic area. Symptoms may include frequent and urgent urination, pelvic pain, and pressure in the bladder area.

are often asymptomatic, but when symptoms do occur, they can include pain in the lower abdomen, pain during urination, frequent urination, and blood in the urine.

Bladder stones can cause abdominal pain, pain while urinating, the need to urinate frequently, and blood in the urine. In some cases, however, they may not cause any symptoms.

diagnosis: Bleeding after the menopause, see Postmenopausal bleeding
symptoms: Postmenopausal bleeding is an abnormal vaginal bleeding that occurs after a woman has gone through menopause. It can last for a few days up to several weeks, and can range in severity from light spotting to heavy bleeding. It can also be accompanied by other symptoms, such as pain and abnormal discharge.

Rectal bleeding is the presence of bright red blood on the tissue paper, in the toilet bowl, or in one's underwear. It is usually a sign of a medical condition and should be checked by a physician. Symptoms of rectal bleeding include the passage of bright red blood with or without stools, pain or discomfort in the rectal area, and feeling faint or lightheaded.

is a common eye condition that causes the eyelids to become inflamed.

Blepharitis is an eye condition that causes inflammation of the eyelids. Symptoms include red, swollen eyelids, itching and burning sensation, crusting of the eyelashes, and dry eyes.

The symptoms of blindness and vision loss include difficulty seeing or distinguishing shapes and colors, an inability to recognize faces, difficulty reading and writing, and a decreased ability to navigate and orient oneself.

are very important when it comes to blood transfusions

Blood groups are used to determine compatibility when it comes to blood transfusions. A successful blood transfusion requires that the blood donor and recipient have compatible blood types. If the wrong blood type is given, it can lead to serious medical complications.
The patient is experiencing blood in their semen, which is an abnormal symptom. This may be accompanied by pain, discomfort, or a burning sensation during urination or ejaculation.

The patient is experiencing blood in their urine, which can be a sign of a serious medical condition. This symptom is often accompanied by pain or a burning sensation when urinating, fatigue, and changes in urine color or odor. It is important to seek medical attention right away if blood in the urine is suspected.

Sepsis is a life-threatening condition caused by an infection that leads to a severe, full-body inflammatory response. Symptoms of sepsis include fever, chills, rapid breathing, rapid heart rate, confusion, low blood pressure, and signs of shock. If left untreated, sepsis can lead to organ failure and death.

diagnosis: Blood pressure (high), see High blood pressure (hypertension)
symptoms: High blood pressure, also known as hypertension, is a medical condition characterized by consistently high readings of systolic and diastolic blood pressure. Symptoms of high blood pressure include headaches, shortness of breath, dizziness, and chest pain. Long-term high blood pressure can lead to serious health complications such as heart disease, stroke, and kidney failure.

diagnosis: Blood pressure (low), see Low blood pressure (hypotension)
symptoms: Low blood pressure, or hypotension, is a condition in which blood pressure is lower than normal. Symptoms may include dizziness, lightheadedness, and fainting. Other symptoms may include nausea, blurred vision, and fatigue.

A blood pressure test measures the amount of pressure applied by the blood against the walls of the arteries. Symptoms of high blood pressure include headaches, shortness of breath, nosebleeds, and anxiety. Low blood pressure can cause dizziness, fatigue, and fainting.

show that the patient has anemia

The patient has a decreased number of red blood cells, leading to symptoms such as fatigue, pale skin, shortness of breath, and dizziness. Anemia can also cause headaches, cold hands and feet, and a rapid or irregular heartbeat.

reactions occur when the recipient’s body recognizes the donated blood as foreign and attacks it.

Blood transfusion reactions occur when the body of the recipient recognizes the donated blood as foreign and mounts an immune response against it. The body can cause a reaction by producing antibodies which can cause fever, low blood pressure, and other symptoms. In severe cases, it can lead to shock, organ failure, and even death.

diagnosis: Blue or grey skin or lips (cyanosis)
symptoms: Cyanosis is a condition in which the skin and lips become bluish or gray in color due to a lack of oxygen in the blood. It is a sign of a serious medical condition and should be evaluated by a medical professional. Symptoms include skin and lips that are blue or gray in color, difficulty breathing, and feeling weak or tired.

, sweating, and trembling

The person is experiencing physical signs of anxiety, such as blushing, sweating, and trembling. These are common symptoms of anxiety and can be signs of embarrassment, fear, or other strong emotions.

is a mental health condition

Body dysmorphic disorder (BDD) is a mental health condition characterized by an intense preoccupation with one or more perceived flaws in one's physical appearance. Symptoms of BDD include obsessive comparison of one's appearance to that of others, an excessive focus on grooming and hygiene, frequent checking in mirrors and other reflective surfaces, and excessive attempts to camouflage the perceived flaws.

Body dysmorphic disorder (BDD) is a mental health condition where a person is excessively preoccupied with perceived flaws in their physical appearance. Symptoms include obsessive comparison to others, excessive focus on grooming and hygiene, frequent mirror checking, and attempts to camouflage perceived flaws.

is a common problem

Body Odour (BO) is a common problem which is characterized by an unpleasant smell that is emitted from the body. It is caused by bacteria that break down the proteins and fatty acids in sweat. It is often associated with poor hygiene, but it can also be caused by certain medical conditions. Treatment may include using antiperspirants, showering regularly, and changing clothes frequently.

are painful, red bumps on the skin that are caused by bacteria

Boils are painful, red bumps on the skin that are caused by bacteria. They are usually filled with pus and can be accompanied by swelling and tenderness in the area. Boils often start as small, hard lumps that slowly become painful, swollen, and filled with pus. They can also be accompanied by fever and chills.

can cause a variety of symptoms.

Bone cancer can cause pain in the affected area, swelling, and tenderness. It can also lead to fatigue, weight loss, fever, and anemia. Other common symptoms include difficulty moving the affected area, fractures, and visible lumps in the area.

A bone cyst is a fluid-filled cavity within a bone. It is usually painless and can occur in any bone, but is most common in the long bones of the arms and legs. Symptoms of a bone cyst may include pain, swelling, and tenderness around the affected area. The cyst may also be visible on an X-ray.

is a test used to measure bone mineral density

A Bone Density Scan (DEXA scan) is a test used to measure bone mineral density. It is used to detect bone loss and diagnose osteoporosis. It is a quick and painless procedure that uses a small amount of radiation to produce images of the inside of the bones. It can help determine a person's risk of developing fractures and can help monitor the effectiveness of treatments for conditions such as osteoporosis.

A Bone Density Scan is a test used to measure bone mineral density, detect bone loss, and diagnose osteoporosis. It is a quick and painless procedure that uses a small amount of radiation to produce images of the inside of the bones and can help determine a person's risk of fractures and monitor the effectiveness of treatments for conditions such as osteoporosis.

Borderline personality disorder is a mental health condition characterized by difficulty managing emotions and thoughts, unstable relationships, and impulsive behavior. Symptoms may include intense fear of abandonment, frequent mood swings, feelings of emptiness, self-harming behavior, and difficulty controlling anger.

is a serious paralytic illness caused by a nerve toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum

Botulism is a serious illness caused by a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum. Symptoms of botulism include muscle weakness, blurred vision, difficulty speaking, and difficulty swallowing. In severe cases, it can cause paralysis and even death.

can cause a variety of symptoms, including:

Bowel cancer can cause a range of symptoms, such as changes in bowel habits, blood in the stool, abdominal pain, weight loss, and fatigue. Other less common symptoms may include bloating, anemia, and vomiting.

is used to detect signs of cancer in the large bowel (colon) and rectum.

Bowel cancer screening is used to detect signs of cancer in the large bowel and rectum. Symptoms that may indicate the presence of cancer include unexplained changes in bowel habits, persistent abdominal discomfort, unexplained weight loss, and rectal bleeding.

is the inability to control one’s bowel movements.

Bowel incontinence is an inability to control one's bowel movements, resulting in involuntary passing of stool and loss of control over bowel movements. Symptoms include frequent passing of loose or liquid stools, difficulty in holding back bowel movements, and feeling of incomplete evacuation.

are growths on the inner lining of your large intestine or rectum.

Bowel polyps are growths on the inner lining of the large intestine or rectum that can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, rectal bleeding, and changes in bowel habits. They can also lead to other serious health problems if left untreated.

diagnosis: Bowel transplant, see Small bowel transplant
symptoms: A small bowel transplant is a surgical procedure in which a healthy small intestine is transplanted from a donor into a recipient. It is used to treat a variety of conditions, including short bowel syndrome, intestinal failure, and certain types of cancer. The most common symptoms associated with these conditions are malnutrition, dehydration, electrolyte imbalance, and abdominal pain. Other symptoms can include fatigue, weight loss, diarrhea, vomiting, and an inability to absorb nutrients from food.

is a precancerous skin condition that affects the outer layers of skin.

Bowen's disease is a skin condition characterized by scaly patches of skin that can become red, thickened, or crusted. It typically appears on sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the face, arms, or legs. It may also be itchy or painful.

can help correct problems with the alignment of the teeth, such as overcrowding, gapped teeth, and misaligned bite.

Braces and orthodontics can be used to treat issues with the alignment of the teeth, such as overcrowding, gaps between teeth, and an incorrect bite. These issues can cause difficulty in eating and speaking, as well as affect the appearance of the teeth.

diagnosis: Brachycephaly and plagiocephaly, see Plagiocephaly and brachycephaly (flat head syndrome)
symptoms: Plagiocephaly and brachycephaly, also known as flat head syndrome, are conditions where the shape of a baby's head is abnormally flattened. Plagiocephaly is an asymmetrical flattening of the head, while brachycephaly is a symmetrical flattening of the head. Both conditions can be caused by positioning and pressure on the baby's head.

is a potentially life-threatening condition.

Brain abscess is a serious infection of the brain caused by bacteria, fungi, or other organisms. Symptoms can include, headaches, fever, confusion, seizures, and loss of consciousness. If left untreated, it can lead to serious complications, including death.

is a condition in which a weak area in the wall of a blood vessel in the brain bursts.

A brain aneurysm is a potentially life-threatening condition in which a weak area in the wall of a blood vessel in the brain ruptures, causing bleeding in the brain. Symptoms may include a severe headache, stiff neck, nausea, confusion, blurred vision, and loss of consciousness.

is the complete and irreversible loss of all brain functions.

Brain death is an irreversible medical condition in which all brain functions cease to exist. It is characterized by the absence of brain activity, lack of response to stimuli, and lack of breathing. Brain death is the ultimate form of brain injury and is considered to be the same as death of the body.

Subarachnoid haemorrhage is a type of brain haemorrhage which occurs when a blood vessel on the surface of the brain bursts and bleeds into the space between the brain and the skull. Symptoms include a sudden and severe headache, stiff neck, confusion, seizures, and loss of consciousness.

diagnosis: Brain tumour (benign), see Benign brain tumour (non-cancerous)
symptoms: A benign brain tumour is a non-cancerous growth in the brain. Symptoms may include headaches, nausea, vomiting, seizures, vision problems, and changes in personality or behavior. It may also cause hearing loss, facial numbness, or weakness in the limbs. The severity of symptoms depends on the size and location of the tumour. Treatment may involve surgery, radiation, or chemotherapy.

diagnosis: Brain tumour (malignant), see Malignant brain tumour (brain cancer)
symptoms: A malignant brain tumour is a type of cancer that develops in the brain. Symptoms may include headaches, seizures, difficulty speaking, confusion, changes in personality, and difficulty with balance and coordination. In some cases, a person may experience nausea, vomiting, or increased pressure within the skull. Treatment for a malignant brain tumour typically involves surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation, depending on the type and size of the tumour.

can cause a variety of symptoms, depending on the size, location, and type of tumour.

Brain tumours can cause a wide range of physical, cognitive and neurological symptoms, depending on the size, location and type of the tumour. Symptoms may include headaches, vision changes, difficulty speaking or hearing, seizures, balance problems, personality changes, and loss of sensation or motor control.

A breast abscess is a localized collection of pus in the breast tissue. Symptoms include a painful, tender lump in the breast, redness and warmth in the area, fever, swollen lymph nodes, and a foul-smelling discharge from the abscess.

is often a hidden symptom.

Men with breast cancer often have no visible symptoms, so it can be difficult to detect. Common signs of breast cancer in men include lumps or swelling in the breast area, changes in the size or shape of the breast, a nipple that is inverted or turned inward, and discharge from the nipple. Other symptoms may include pain in the breast area, a rash on the nipple, or swelling under the arm.

can be a complex process and can manifest in numerous ways. 

Breast cancer in women can cause a variety of symptoms, such as a lump in the breast, changes in the shape or size of the breast, nipple discharge, and pain in the breast. Other symptoms may include swelling of the lymph nodes in the armpit or neck and changes in the skin of the breast, such as dimpling or redness.

can be caused by a variety of conditions.

The main symptom of breast lumps is a lump or area of thickening in the breast. Other symptoms can include breast pain, redness, changes in the size or shape of the breast, and nipple discharge.

is a common symptom of breast cancer

Breast pain is a common symptom of breast cancer that can range from a mild discomfort to a sharp, stabbing sensation. It can occur in one or both breasts, and may be localized in one area or be more widespread. It may also be accompanied by other symptoms such as swelling and tenderness.

is available to treat medical problems caused by large breasts.

Breast reduction on the NHS can help treat medical issues caused by overly large breasts, such as back and neck pain, skin irritation, and difficulty exercising. It can also improve the patient's self-esteem and quality of life.

A mammogram is a low-dose X-ray of the breast. It is used to detect changes in the breast tissue that cannot be felt during a breast exam. Common symptoms that may lead to a mammogram include a lump, thickening, or swelling in the breast, changes in the size or shape of the breast, dimpling or puckering of the skin, nipple discharge, and a change in the position of the nipple.

A mammogram is used to detect changes in the breast tissue that cannot be felt during a breast exam. Symptoms that may lead to a mammogram include lumps, thickening, swelling, changes in size or shape, dimpling or puckering of the skin, nipple discharge, and changes in the position of the nipple.

is usually a response to a sudden surprise or fear.

Breath-holding in babies and children is a reflexive reaction to a sudden surprise or fear. It is usually characterized by a sudden pause in breathing followed by a period of crying. It may also include a bluish tint to the skin, stiffening of the body, and loss of consciousness.

A broken arm or wrist is a common injury that can cause pain, swelling, and difficulty moving the affected area. It may also cause bruising, numbness, or tingling in the area. The affected limb may appear deformed, and the person may not be able to move it at all.

The symptoms of a broken finger or thumb include pain, swelling, bruising, and difficulty moving the affected finger or thumb. In some cases, the broken bone can be visible through the skin.

A broken hip is a fracture in the hip joint. Symptoms of a broken hip include pain in the hip area, difficulty bearing weight on the affected leg, and a visible deformity in the hip area. Other symptoms may include swelling, tenderness, and bruising.

can cause pain when breathing

Broken or bruised ribs can cause a lot of pain and discomfort when breathing, as the ribs move with each breath. It can also cause sharp pains when coughing or sneezing. Other symptoms include tenderness and swelling in the area of the injury.

A broken toe is a common injury that can cause pain, swelling, and difficulty walking. It is usually caused by a direct blow to the toe or a heavy object falling on it. Symptoms may include pain, swelling, bruising, difficulty walking, and difficulty moving the toe.

is a long-term condition that affects the airways of the lungs

Bronchiectasis is a long-term condition that affects the airways of the lungs, causing them to become widened and damaged. Symptoms of bronchiectasis include a persistent cough, breathlessness, wheezing, chest pain, and coughing up large amounts of mucus. It can also lead to frequent chest infections and fatigue.

is a common viral respiratory illness in infants and young children

Bronchiolitis is a respiratory illness in infants and young children caused by a virus. Symptoms include coughing, wheezing, difficulty breathing, rapid breathing, fever, and a runny nose. It can be serious in infants and may require medical intervention.

is a common respiratory illness that is usually caused by a virus.

Bronchitis is an inflammation of the airways in the lungs, usually caused by a virus. Symptoms typically include a cough, shortness of breath, chest tightness, and fatigue.

, such as albuterol, are used to treat asthma.

The main symptom of asthma is difficulty breathing, and bronchodilators such as albuterol are used to help open the airways and improve breathing. This can help reduce symptoms such as wheezing, coughing, and chest tightness.

is an infectious disease caused by bacteria of the genus Brucella.

Brucellosis is an infectious disease caused by bacteria of the genus Brucella. Symptoms include fever, chills, sweats, headache, back pain, joint pain, and fatigue. Other symptoms may include loss of appetite, weight loss, and depression.

is a rare genetic disorder characterized by abnormal heart rhythms (arrhythmias).

Brugada Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the heart's electrical system, causing abnormal heart rhythms, known as arrhythmias. It can cause sudden death in some cases.

Bruxism is a condition characterized by grinding and clenching of the teeth. It can occur during sleep, or during periods of stress or anxiety. It can lead to jaw pain, headaches, earaches, and tooth sensitivity. It can also cause wear and tear on the teeth, leading to damage and tooth loss.

Bulging eyes, also known as exophthalmos, is a symptom characterized by an abnormal protrusion of the eyes from the eye sockets. This can cause the eyes to appear larger than normal and can be accompanied by pain, redness, and light sensitivity. Other symptoms may include double vision and difficulty closing the eyelids.

is an eating disorder

Bulimia is an eating disorder characterized by bouts of overeating, followed by purging or other compensatory behaviors. Common symptoms include frequent cycles of binging and purging, eating in secret, feeling out of control around food, and feeling ashamed or guilty after eating. Additional symptoms may include irritability, extreme mood swings, and fatigue.

is a rare autoimmune skin disorder.

Bullous pemphigoid is a rare autoimmune skin disorder characterized by the formation of large, fluid-filled blisters on the skin. It typically affects the elderly, and causes itchy, red skin, with blisters that can form on the stomach, legs, arms, and other areas of the body. It can cause severe discomfort and can lead to secondary infections.

are bony bumps that form on the side of your big toe

Bunions are a common foot condition that cause a bony bump to form on the side of the big toe. They can be painful and cause the big toe to angle toward the other toes. The skin over the bunion may be swollen, red, and sore. Bunions can also cause other foot problems, such as hammertoe and calluses.

Burns and scalds are injuries caused by heat. They can cause pain, redness, and blisters in the affected area, as well as swelling and tenderness. Burns may also cause more serious damage to the skin, nerves, and underlying tissues.

is an inflammation of a bursa.

Bursitis is a condition where the bursa, a fluid-filled sac that acts as a cushion between tendons and bones, becomes inflamed. Symptoms include pain, swelling, and tenderness in the affected area.
The main symptom of Sciatica is pain in the buttocks that can go down the back of the leg and into the foot. It is usually accompanied by a tingling and numbness in the leg and can be very painful.

diagnosis: CABG, see Coronary artery bypass graft
symptoms: Coronary artery bypass graft (CABG) is a surgical procedure used to treat coronary artery disease. The procedure involves bypassing a blocked artery with a healthy artery or vein from another part of the body to improve blood flow to the heart and reduce the risk of a heart attack. Symptoms of coronary artery disease can include chest pain, shortness of breath, fatigue, and an irregular heartbeat.

is a major abdominal surgery that is done when a natural childbirth is not possible.

Caesarean section is a surgical procedure usually performed when a natural childbirth is not possible. It involves making an incision in the abdomen and uterus to deliver a baby. The procedure can be done to protect the health of the mother or baby and can be used in cases of emergency or if a medical condition makes natural childbirth impossible.

of the pancreas is a cancer that starts in the pancreas.

Cancer of the pancreas is a type of cancer that begins in the pancreas, an organ located behind the stomach. Symptoms of pancreas cancer include abdominal pain, jaundice, weight loss, and loss of appetite. Other symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, and blood clots.

diagnosis: Cannabis oil (medical cannabis), see Medical cannabis (and cannabis oils)
symptoms: Medical cannabis, also known as cannabis oil, is a form of medical marijuana that is used to treat a variety of medical conditions. It is composed of the active ingredients found in cannabis plants, most notably THC and CBD, which are believed to have a therapeutic effect on the body. Cannabis oil is typically ingested orally, or applied topically or inhaled for relief from symptoms such as pain, inflammation, and anxiety.

Carbon monoxide poisoning is a serious health hazard caused by inhaling fumes of carbon monoxide gas. Symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning include headache, dizziness, confusion, nausea, and fatigue. Long-term exposure can lead to more severe symptoms such as loss of consciousness, coma, and death.

The CEA test is used to measure the levels of the CEA protein in the blood. It is used to monitor the progress of some types of cancer and to look for a recurrence of cancer after treatment. It can also be used to detect cancer in people with no symptoms.

revealed severe triple vessel coronary artery disease.

Cardiac catheterisation and coronary angiography showed that the patient had a severe blockage in three of the major coronary arteries. This blockage could lead to an increased risk of heart attack or stroke.

is a condition in which the heart muscle becomes thickened, enlarged, and/or stiff.

Cardiomyopathy is a disease of the heart muscle that causes it to become thickened, enlarged, and/or stiff. This can result in decreased heart function and an increased risk of heart failure, arrhythmias, and sudden cardiac death.

is a group of diseases that affect the heart and blood vessels.

Cardiovascular disease is a group of diseases that can affect the heart and blood vessels, leading to symptoms such as chest pain, shortness of breath, and fatigue. It can also cause heart attack, stroke, and other life-threatening conditions.

is a procedure used to remove plaque buildup in the carotid arteries.

Carotid endarterectomy is a surgical procedure used to treat carotid artery disease. It is performed to remove plaque buildup in the carotid arteries, which can cause stroke or transient ischemic attack (TIA). Symptoms of carotid artery disease include stroke, TIA, and difficulty speaking or understanding.

Carpal tunnel syndrome is a condition caused by the compression of the median nerve in the wrist, causing pain, tingling, and numbness in the hands and fingers. Symptoms may worsen with certain activities, such as gripping or typing, and can lead to weakness in the affected hand.

diagnosis: Cat bites, see Animal and human bites
symptoms: A cat bite is a puncture wound from a cat's sharp teeth that can cause severe infection. Symptoms include swelling, redness, pain, and tenderness at the site of the bite, as well as fever and swollen lymph nodes. Cat bites can also lead to abscesses, which can be difficult to treat.

Cataract surgery is a procedure to remove the clouded lens in the eye that causes vision loss. Symptoms of cataracts include blurred vision, difficulty seeing at night, double vision, and a halo effect around lights.

Cataracts are a common cause of vision loss and can be treated with surgery. Symptoms include blurred vision, difficulty seeing at night, double vision, and a halo effect around lights. Surgery involves the removal of the cloudy lens and the insertion of an artificial lens to improve vision.

Age-related cataracts are a common eye condition in which the lens of the eye becomes clouded and affects the person's vision. Symptoms of age-related cataracts include blurry vision, difficulty seeing at night, sensitivity to light, and seeing halos around lights.

Childhood cataracts are a vision disorder in which the lens of the eye becomes cloudy or opaque, blocking or blurring light from entering the eye and making it difficult for a child to see. Symptoms of childhood cataracts can include blurred vision, poor night vision, double vision, and sensitivity to light.

is a condition that causes inflammation in the mucous membranes

Catarrh is a condition that causes swelling and irritation in the lining of the nose, throat and sinuses. It is often accompanied by other symptoms such as sneezing, congestion, a runny nose and a sore throat. In some cases, it can also cause difficulty breathing and a loss of smell.

is a condition where a cluster of abnormal blood vessels form a mass in the brain or spine

Cavernoma is a condition in which clusters of abnormal and weakened blood vessels form a mass in the brain or spine. Symptoms can include seizures, headaches, weakness, and changes in vision or speech. In serious cases, it can cause bleeding in the brain and spinal cord, leading to paralysis.

Cavernous sinus thrombosis is a medical condition which occurs when a blood clot forms within the cavernous sinus, a cavity at the base of the brain. Symptoms of this condition include fever, headache, double vision, and drooping of one side of the face. Other symptoms may include pain around the eyes, seizures, nausea, and confusion.

is a skin infection caused by bacteria.

Cellulitis is a bacterial skin infection that causes redness, swelling, and pain in the affected area. It can often cause fever and chills, and the skin may be warm to the touch. Symptoms may also include fatigue and a general feeling of being unwell.

is a group of permanent movement disorders that appear in early childhood.

Cerebral palsy is a neurological disorder that affects a person's ability to move, usually appearing in early childhood. It is characterized by impaired muscle coordination, involuntary movements, and an inability to control movement. It can also cause problems with posture, balance, and coordination.

is a type of cancer that occurs in the cells of the cervix — the lower part of the uterus that connects to the vagina.

Cervical cancer is a type of cancer that affects the cells of the cervix, the lower part of the uterus which connects to the vagina. Symptoms of cervical cancer can include abnormal vaginal bleeding, pain during intercourse, and pelvic pain.

is a rare medical condition in which an extra rib is present in the neck.

Cervical rib is a rare condition in which an extra rib is present in the neck area. It can cause symptoms such as numbness and tingling in the arm and hand, pain in the neck and shoulder, and difficulty with movement of the arm.

is a test used to detect abnormal cells on the cervix.

Cervical screening is a test used to detect abnormal cells on the cervix. It is usually done by taking a sample of cells from the cervix and examining them under a microscope. It can help to identify changes in the cells that could lead to cervical cancer if left untreated. It is performed as a preventative measure and does not usually cause any symptoms.

Cervical spondylosis is a condition that causes pain and stiffness in the neck and shoulders. Symptoms may include neck pain, headaches, shoulder pain, and numbness or tingling in the arms or legs. In severe cases, it can lead to reduced mobility and balance issues.

(CMT) is an inherited neurological disorder that affects the peripheral nerves.

Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease is a genetic disorder which causes damage to the peripheral nerves, leading to muscle weakness, decreased sensation in the limbs, and foot and ankle deformities. Symptoms typically include aching, burning, and tingling in the feet and legs, loss of reflexes, and difficulty walking.

Charles Bonnet Syndrome is a condition in which a person experiences vivid, complex visual hallucinations in the absence of any other medical condition or drug use. It primarily affects elderly people with vision loss due to conditions such as macular degeneration. The hallucinations can vary in complexity and can include shapes, people, animals, and landscapes. Symptoms of Charles Bonnet Syndrome include vivid, complex visual hallucinations, often in the form of shapes, people, animals, or landscapes, experienced by elderly people with vision loss. There is no physical cause or drug use associated with Charles Bonnet Syndrome.

is a type of cancer treatment that uses drugs to destroy cancer cells.

Chemotherapy is a type of cancer treatment that involves the use of drugs to destroy cancer cells. Symptoms of chemotherapy treatment may include nausea, hair loss, fatigue, and a weakened immune system.

A chest infection is a type of lung infection causing symptoms such as coughing, difficulty breathing, chest pain, and fever. It is usually caused by a virus or bacteria and can range from mild to severe.

Chiari malformation is a neurological disorder caused by a structural defect in the brain. Symptoms include headache, neck pain, balance problems, numbness and tingling, difficulty swallowing, vertigo, and blurred vision. In more severe cases, it can lead to hydrocephalus, paralysis, and difficulty breathing.

is a very contagious disease caused by the varicella-zoster virus.

Chickenpox is a contagious disease caused by the varicella-zoster virus. Symptoms include an itchy rash, fever, and fatigue. It is most common in children, but can affect adults as well.

are red, swollen, itchy and painful patches of skin that can appear when exposed to cold temperatures

Chilblains are a skin condition caused by cold temperatures, which can cause red, swollen, itchy, and painful patches of skin. They can be accompanied by burning, stinging, and increased sensitivity to touch.

can cause vision problems

Childhood cataracts can cause a range of vision problems, including blurred vision, difficulty seeing in low light, double vision, and sensitivity to light. In some cases, cataracts can cause a complete loss of vision.
