patients experience a wide range of symptoms

Chiropractic patients may experience a variety of symptoms, including back pain, neck pain, headaches, joint pain, muscle soreness, and stiffness. They may also have difficulty moving or have a restricted range of motion. In addition, they may have tingling, numbness, or radiating pain in the arms or legs.

is a common sexually transmitted infection (STI) caused by bacteria.

Chlamydia is an STI caused by bacteria that can lead to symptoms such as abnormal discharge, pain while urinating, and pain in the lower abdomen. Left untreated, it can cause long-term complications such as pelvic inflammatory disease, infertility, and an increased risk of ectopic pregnancy.

Cholangiocarcinoma is a type of cancer that develops in the bile ducts, which are the tubes that carry bile from the liver to the small intestine. Symptoms of cholangiocarcinoma can include jaundice, abdominal pain, weight loss, appetite loss, and itching.

Acute cholecystitis is an inflammation of the gallbladder that causes severe abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. It can also cause fever, abdominal tenderness, and jaundice. In some cases, the pain can radiate to the back or shoulder.

is an infection of the small intestine caused by the bacterium Vibrio cholerae.

Cholera is an intestinal infection caused by the bacterium Vibrio cholerae. Symptoms include watery diarrhea, vomiting, and abdominal cramps. In severe cases, it can lead to dehydration and even death.

is a serious ear condition that can cause a wide range of symptoms.

Cholesteatoma is a serious ear condition that can cause hearing loss, ear pain, dizziness, and a feeling of fullness in the ear. It can also lead to infection, facial paralysis, and even brain damage if left untreated.

High cholesterol is a condition in which there is an elevated level of cholesterol in the blood. Symptoms of high cholesterol can include chest pain, shortness of breath, fatigue, and difficulty concentrating. It can also increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, and other cardiovascular diseases.

(CVS) is a prenatal test that can identify certain chromosomal abnormalities and genetic conditions

Chorionic villus sampling is a prenatal test that can detect genetic and chromosomal abnormalities in the fetus. It involves taking a small sample of cells from the placenta and testing them for any genetic abnormalities. This test can be performed as early as 10 weeks into the pregnancy and can provide information about the health of the fetus.

diagnosis: Chronic fatigue syndrome (ME/CFS), see Myalgic encephalomyelitis or chronic fatigue syndrome (ME/CFS)
symptoms: Chronic fatigue syndrome (ME/CFS) is a disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that cannot be explained by any underlying medical condition. Symptoms include significant fatigue, post-exertional malaise, unrefreshing sleep, cognitive dysfunction, and pain. Additionally, many people with ME/CFS experience a range of other symptoms such as headache, muscle pain, joint pain, and stomach pain.

is an ongoing journey of managing your health and treatment.

Chronic kidney disease is a long-term condition where the kidneys do not function properly. Symptoms may include fatigue, nausea, loss of appetite, swelling of the hands and feet, and difficulty concentrating. Treatment options may include medications, lifestyle changes, and dialysis.

(CLL)

Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia (CLL) is a type of cancer that affects the white blood cells. Symptoms of CLL include fatigue, swollen lymph nodes, fever, night sweats, and weight loss. Additionally, CLL can cause anemia, which can lead to shortness of breath, weakened immune system, and increased risk of infection.

is a cancer of the white blood cells

Chronic myeloid leukaemia is a type of cancer that affects the white blood cells. Symptoms of CML include fatigue, fever, night sweats, weight loss, and an enlarged spleen. Other symptoms may include anemia, bleeding and bruising, bone pain, and frequent infections.

is a type of obstructive lung disease characterized by long-term breathing problems and poor airflow.

COPD is a chronic lung disease that causes long-term breathing problems and difficulty in breathing due to decreased airflow. Symptoms include shortness of breath, wheezing, chest tightness, and coughing.

is a long-term inflammation of the pancreas.

Chronic pancreatitis is a medical condition characterized by long-term inflammation of the pancreas, which can cause abdominal pain, malabsorption, and diabetes. Symptoms may also include weight loss, malnutrition, diarrhea, and jaundice.

(CTE) is a progressive degenerative disease of the brain found in people with a history of repetitive brain trauma (e.g., athletes, military veterans, and others with a history of head injuries).

Chronic traumatic encephalopathy is a degenerative brain disease caused by repetitive brain trauma. It is most commonly found in athletes, military veterans, and people with a history of head injuries. Symptoms can include cognitive, behavioral, and mood issues, as well as memory loss, confusion, and more.

can cause bleeding, infection, and pain

Circumcision in boys can lead to bleeding, infection, and pain. Bleeding can occur during and after the procedure, and the wound can become infected if proper care is not taken. Pain may also be experienced during and after surgery.

is a surgical procedure in which the foreskin of the penis is removed.

Circumcision in men is a surgical procedure that involves the removal of the foreskin from the penis. It can cause pain, bleeding, and swelling in the area. It may also lead to infection and scarring.

is a serious condition in which the liver is permanently damaged.

Cirrhosis is a serious condition that affects the liver, causing permanent damage. Symptoms include fatigue, weight loss, nausea, appetite loss, jaundice, abdominal pain, and spider-like blood vessels on the skin.

Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD) is a rare, degenerative, and fatal brain disorder. Symptoms typically include rapidly progressive dementia, involuntary muscle jerks, visual disturbances, and difficulty walking. As the disease progresses, mental deterioration and blindness become increasingly common. Death usually occurs within a few months to a year after diagnosis.

is an anxiety disorder

Claustrophobia is an anxiety disorder characterized by intense fear and distress in enclosed or confined spaces. Symptoms of claustrophobia include a feeling of being trapped, difficulty breathing, increased heart rate, sweating, shaking, and feeling a need to escape. People with the disorder may also experience panic attacks, avoidance of small spaces, and fear of being trapped.

are birth defects that occur when a baby’s lip or mouth do not form properly during pregnancy.

Cleft lip and palate are birth defects that occur when a baby's lip and mouth do not form properly during pregnancy. Symptoms include a gap in the upper lip, an opening in the roof of the mouth (palate), and/or misaligned teeth. These birth defects can also cause problems with eating, speaking, and hearing.

is a serious mental health condition that can cause a wide range of emotional and physical symptoms.

Clinical depression is a serious mental health condition that can cause a person to experience a wide range of emotional and physical symptoms, such as low mood, loss of interest, lack of energy, feelings of worthlessness, difficulty sleeping, changes in appetite, and feelings of hopelessness.

have shown that the new drug can reduce pain, inflammation, and swelling in people with arthritis.

The new drug has been proven to be effective in reducing the symptoms of arthritis, including pain, inflammation, and swelling. It has been tested in clinical trials and has been shown to be successful in treating the condition.

is a serious condition that usually affects the large intestine.

Symptoms of C. diff infection include abdominal cramping, diarrhea, and fever. Other symptoms may include nausea, loss of appetite, and dehydration. In more severe cases, the infection can cause life-threatening complications. 

C. diff infection is a serious condition that causes abdominal cramping, diarrhea, fever, nausea, loss of appetite, and dehydration. In severe cases, it can lead to life-threatening complications.

is a common birth defect in which one or both feet are rotated inward.

Club foot is a birth defect in which the feet are rotated inward, causing them to point downward and turn inwards. It is a common defect, affecting one or both feet. Symptoms may include pain, difficulty walking, and an abnormal appearance of the feet.

are one of the most painful types of headaches.

Cluster headaches are a type of headache that are characterized by intense, debilitating pain on one side of the head, usually around the eye. They may also be accompanied by other symptoms such as a runny or stuffy nose, tearing, and/or facial swelling. Cluster headaches can last anywhere from 15 minutes to 3 hours.

Coccyx pain, also known as tailbone pain, is a type of pain that is felt in the lower back near the coccyx, or tailbone. It can be caused by a variety of factors, including sitting for long periods of time, childbirth, and trauma. Symptoms of coccyx pain include soreness, tenderness, and pain when sitting or moving.

Coeliac disease is an autoimmune disorder which affects the digestive system, specifically the small intestine. Symptoms include abdominal bloating and pain, fatigue, diarrhoea, constipation, and weight loss. Other symptoms may include nausea, anemia, and neurological symptoms such as tingling in the hands and feet.

Coeliac disease is an autoimmune disorder affecting the digestive system, causing abdominal pain and bloating, fatigue, diarrhoea, constipation, weight loss, nausea, anemia, and neurological symptoms such as tingling in the hands and feet.

is a type of psychotherapy used to treat a variety of mental health issues.

Cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT) is used to treat a variety of mental health issues, such as depression, anxiety, post-traumatic stress disorder, obsessive-compulsive disorder, and eating disorders. It focuses on helping the individual identify and modify negative beliefs and behaviours, and develop healthy coping strategies. It can also help the individual develop better problem-solving and communication skills.

are painful blisters that form on or around the lips.

Cold sores are painful blisters that appear on or around the lips. They can be red, swollen and filled with fluid, and may cause burning, itching and tingling sensations.

is a common condition in babies that is often seen in the first few months of life.

Colic is a common condition in babies that causes them to experience frequent episodes of inconsolable crying, often lasting for several hours. It usually affects babies between the ages of three weeks and four months, and is most common during the evening or night.

Colon cancer, also known as Bowel cancer, is a type of cancer that develops in the large intestine, or colon. Common symptoms include changes in bowel habits, such as constipation or diarrhea, blood in the stool, abdominal pain, and unexplained weight loss.

is a procedure used to detect changes or abnormalities in the large intestine

A colonoscopy is a procedure used to examine the large intestine (colon) for any abnormal changes or growths. It involves the use of a long, thin, flexible tube with a light and camera at the end to look inside the rectum and entire colon. During the procedure, the doctor may take tissue samples (biopsy) or remove any abnormal growths.

patients often experience abdominal cramps, gas, bloating, and constipation

Colostomy patients may experience abdominal cramps, gas, bloating, and constipation as common symptoms. These can be managed with dietary and lifestyle modifications.

diagnosis: Colour blindness, see Colour vision deficiency (colour blindness)
symptoms: Colour blindness is a condition where the individual has difficulty distinguishing between certain colours, often red and green. It is caused by the absence of certain types of cones in the eye, which are responsible for colour vision. Symptoms include difficulty distinguishing between certain colours, trouble distinguishing colours in low-light conditions, and confusion when presented with multiple colours at once.

is a condition where a person is unable to distinguish certain colours.

Colour vision deficiency is a condition where a person is unable to see certain colours, resulting in difficulty distinguishing between colours. This can range from difficulty distinguishing between shades of the same colour to an inability to distinguish any colours at all.

is a procedure used to examine an enlarged cervix

Colposcopy is a medical procedure used to examine the cervix of a woman when it is enlarged. It uses a colposcope, which is an instrument with a light and magnifying lens to provide a detailed view of the cervix. The procedure may involve the use of a special solution to make any abnormal areas easier to see.

is a state of profound unconsciousness.

Coma is a medical condition in which a person is unable to respond to their environment and is in a deep state of unconsciousness. It is usually caused by a serious medical condition or injury and can last for days, weeks, months, or even years.
Common cold is a viral infection of the upper respiratory system, which can cause symptoms such as a runny nose, sneezing, a sore throat, coughing, congestion, and fatigue.

is a medical emergency caused by increased pressure in an enclosed space in the body, such as an arm or a leg.

Compartment Syndrome is a medical emergency that occurs when increased pressure builds up in a confined space in the body, typically an arm or leg. Symptoms include severe pain, swelling, numbness, tingling, and a tight feeling in the affected area.

(CAM) has been used to treat a variety of symptoms ranging from anxiety to chronic pain.

Complementary and alternative medicine (CAM) is used to treat a wide range of symptoms, including anxiety, chronic pain, and other physical and mental health issues. It is used in combination with traditional treatments to improve overall health and wellbeing.

(CRPS)

Complex regional pain syndrome (CRPS) is a chronic pain disorder that typically affects one limb (arm, leg, hand, or foot). It is characterized by persistent severe and debilitating pain, swelling, and changes in the skin. Other symptoms can include joint stiffness, decreased range of motion, and changes in skin temperature, color, and texture.

Complex Regional Pain Syndrome (CRPS) is a chronic pain disorder that causes persistent severe and debilitating pain, swelling, joint stiffness, decreased range of motion, and changes in skin temperature, color, and texture, typically affecting one limb.

is a type of traumatic brain injury that affects your brain function.

Concussion is a traumatic brain injury that can cause changes in a person's thinking, behavior, and physical functioning. Symptoms of a concussion can include headaches, dizziness, confusion, difficulty concentrating, memory problems, nausea, and sleep disturbances.

diagnosis: Concussion, see Head injury and concussion
symptoms: Concussion is a type of traumatic brain injury that affects the functioning of the brain. It is usually caused by a blow to the head, which can cause a temporary disruption in the brain's normal functioning. Symptoms of concussion may include confusion, headache, nausea, dizziness, amnesia, and fatigue.

Sudden confusion, also known as delirium, is a sudden change in mental status that can cause disorientation, agitation, and difficulty focusing. Symptoms can include difficulty concentrating, confusion about time and place, restlessness, and difficulty understanding instructions.

is a condition present at birth where the structure of the heart and the way it works is different from normal.

Congenital heart disease is a birth defect which affects the structure and functioning of the heart. It can cause symptoms such as difficulty breathing, fatigue, and poor circulation. It can also cause heart murmur, an abnormal heartbeat, and cyanosis, a bluish tint to the skin.

diagnosis: Congenital hip dislocation, see Developmental dysplasia of the hip
symptoms: Congenital hip dislocation (also known as Developmental Dysplasia of the Hip) is a condition where the hip joint does not form correctly in newborns, resulting in a dislocated hip. Symptoms may include a distinctive waddling gait, asymmetric skin folds in the thigh area, and the hip being out of place when touched.

is an inflammation of the conjunctiva, a thin, clear membrane that lines the inside of the eyelid and covers the white part of the eyeball.

Conjunctivitis is an inflammation of the conjunctiva, a membrane that lines the inside of the eyelid and covers the white part of the eyeball. Symptoms include redness, swollen eyelids, itching, burning, and a discharge.

is a common digestive problem that can cause discomfort and pain.

Constipation is a digestive issue that results in infrequent and difficult bowel movements, causing pain and discomfort. Symptoms include abdominal pain, bloating, straining to pass stool, and feeling like there is a blockage in the intestines.

is a skin condition caused by contact with a foreign substance.

Contact dermatitis is a skin condition caused by coming into contact with an irritant or allergen. Symptoms include redness, itching, burning, and blisters. In some cases, the skin may also become dry, cracked, or scaly.

Cornea transplant rejection is a complication of cornea transplant surgery in which the body's immune system recognizes the transplanted tissue as foreign and rejects it. Symptoms may include redness, pain, blurred vision, and a decrease in visual acuity.

are areas of thick, hardened skin.

Corns and calluses are areas of skin that have become thick and hardened due to excessive pressure or friction. They can be painful and can cause discomfort when walking or wearing shoes.

Coronary angioplasty and stent insertion is a medical procedure used to treat patients with coronary artery disease. Symptoms of this condition include chest pain, shortness of breath, nausea, and fatigue. The procedure is used to open blocked or narrowed coronary arteries, which can improve symptoms and reduce the risk of a heart attack.

ing (CABG) is a type of surgery that improves blood flow to the heart.

CABG is a type of surgery used to treat coronary artery disease, which is caused by blocked or narrowed arteries that reduce blood flow to the heart. Symptoms of coronary artery disease include chest pain, shortness of breath, and fatigue. CABG can help relieve these symptoms by restoring normal blood flow to the heart.

is a condition that affects the heart's blood supply

Coronary heart disease is a condition that affects the heart by reducing its blood supply. Symptoms of coronary heart disease can include chest pain, shortness of breath, fatigue, and irregular heartbeats. Other signs may include swelling in the legs, ankles, and feet.

Coronavirus, also known as COVID-19, is associated with fever, cough, and difficulty breathing. These are some of the most common symptoms associated with the virus.

(CBD) is a rare condition that affects movement and thinking.

Corticobasal degeneration (CBD) is a rare neurological condition that affects movement and thinking. Symptoms can include stiffness or jerky movements, impaired speech, and cognitive decline. Other associated symptoms may include muscle weakness, changes in sensation, and changes in personality or behavior.

The symptoms of eczema include inflammation and itching of the affected area. Corticosteroid cream may be prescribed to help reduce these symptoms.

Corticosteroids are a type of steroid hormone that can cause a wide range of symptoms, including increased appetite, weight gain, fatigue, mood swings, slowed growth in children, increased risk of infection, and thinning of the skin. In some cases, long-term use can lead to osteoporosis, cataracts, glaucoma, and high blood pressure.

are becoming increasingly popular, but they can cause complications.

Cosmetic procedures, such as plastic surgery, are becoming more popular, but they can lead to potential complications such as infection, scarring, and changes in sensation. Additionally, there is a risk of psychological distress and dissatisfaction with the results of the procedure.

is an inflammation of the costal cartilage, the structure that connects the ribs to the breastbone

Costochondritis is an inflammation of the costal cartilage, a connective tissue that links the ribs to the breastbone. Symptoms of costochondritis include sharp chest pain, tenderness when touching the chest, and difficulty breathing.

is a respiratory illness

COVID-19 is a contagious illness that affects the respiratory system, causing symptoms such as coughing, shortness of breath, sore throat, and fever. Other common symptoms include fatigue, body aches, and loss of appetite. In severe cases, it can cause difficulty breathing, chest pain, and pneumonia.

is a skin condition that typically affects newborns and infants.

Cradle cap is a skin condition that affects newborns and infants. Symptoms include a yellow, scaly, crusty scalp and patches of greasy skin on the head, eyebrows, and eyelids. The affected area may also be itchy, red, and inflamed.

is a condition in which the bones in a baby's skull join together too early.

Craniosynostosis is a condition in which the bones in the skull of a baby join together too soon, before the brain is fully developed. This can cause the head to have an abnormal shape and may lead to pressure on the brain. It can also affect the growth of the face and may cause problems with vision and hearing.

Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease is a rare and fatal neurodegenerative brain disorder. Symptoms typically include rapidly progressive dementia, psychiatric problems, and abnormal movements. Other symptoms may include vision and balance problems, speech difficulties, and changes in behavior.

is an inflammatory bowel disease (IBD).

Crohn's disease is an IBD that causes inflammation of the digestive tract, leading to abdominal pain, severe diarrhea, fatigue, weight loss, and malnutrition. It can also cause complications outside of the digestive system, such as skin problems, arthritis, and eye inflammation.

is a respiratory condition that can cause a barking cough, hoarseness, and difficulty breathing.

Croup is a respiratory condition which causes a characteristic barking cough, hoarseness, and difficulty breathing. It is often accompanied by a runny nose and sore throat.

is a hormonal disorder caused by prolonged exposure of the body's tissues to high levels of the hormone cortisol.

Cushing's syndrome is a disorder caused by an excess of cortisol in the body. Symptoms include weight gain, particularly in the face, neck and abdomen, thinning or patches of skin, and high blood pressure.

are common injuries that can happen to anyone at any time.

Cuts and grazes are minor injuries that occur when the skin is broken due to a scrape, tear, or puncture. They can be caused by accidents, falls, and contact with sharp objects. Symptoms include pain, bleeding, swelling, and tenderness.

diagnosis: Cyanosis, see Blue or grey skin or lips (cyanosis)
symptoms: Cyanosis is a symptom characterized by a bluish or grey discoloration of the skin or lips due to an insufficient amount of oxygen in the blood. It is most commonly seen around the mouth and nailbeds, but can also be seen in other parts of the body.

(CVS) is a disorder that causes recurring episodes of nausea, vomiting, and tiredness

Cyclical Vomiting Syndrome is a disorder characterized by recurrent episodes of nausea, vomiting, and fatigue. These episodes can last anywhere from several hours to several days, and can occur at regular intervals.

Cyclospora infection causes watery diarrhea, loss of appetite, nausea, fatigue, and abdominal cramps. It can also cause bloating, gas, stomach pain, vomiting, and a low-grade fever.

is a milder form of bipolar disorder

Cyclothymia is a milder form of bipolar disorder that is characterized by periods of low-level depression and hypomania, alternating with periods of normal mood. Symptoms of the disorder include mood swings, irritability, restlessness, changes in sleep patterns, low self-esteem, and difficulty concentrating.

is an inherited disease that affects the respiratory and digestive systems.

Cystic fibrosis is a genetic disorder that affects the lungs and digestive system by causing an accumulation of thick, sticky mucus in the lungs, pancreas, and other organs. This mucus buildup can cause breathing difficulties, frequent lung infections, and digestive problems.

is an inflammation of the bladder, usually caused by a bacterial infection.

Cystitis is an infection of the bladder that causes inflammation and is usually caused by bacteria. Symptoms may include pain or burning when urinating, an urgent need to urinate, and feeling the need to urinate more often. Other symptoms may include pain in the lower abdomen, cloudy or bloody urine, and a strong-smelling urine.

is a common virus that can cause serious health problems for people with weakened immune systems, such as those with HIV/AIDS or people who have had an organ transplant.

Cytomegalovirus (CMV) is a virus that can cause serious health issues in people with weakened immune systems, such as those with HIV/AIDS or those who have had an organ transplant. Symptoms can include fever, fatigue, sore throat, body aches, and swollen lymph nodes. In more severe cases, it can lead to organ failure, blindness, and other neurological problems.

is a common scalp condition marked by flaking of the skin on your scalp.

Dandruff is a scalp condition that causes the skin on the scalp to flake off. It is a common condition and can cause itching and irritation.

is a combination of both hearing and vision loss.

Deafblindness is a condition where a person experiences both hearing and vision loss. It can cause difficulties with communication, mobility, and daily activities. People with deafblindness may also experience sensory overload, which can cause confusion and difficulty understanding their environment.

Deafness, or hearing loss, is a condition in which a person is unable to hear sound in one or both ears. It can range from mild to severe, and can be caused by a variety of factors, including genetics, age, noise exposure, disease, or injury. Symptoms of deafness include difficulty hearing and understanding speech, difficulty hearing in noisy environments, and difficulty navigating in unfamiliar places.

diagnosis: Decompression sickness, see Air or gas embolism
symptoms: Decompression sickness, also known as Air or gas embolism, is a condition caused by a rapid decrease in pressure, which leads to the formation of nitrogen bubbles in the bloodstream. Symptoms include joint pain, dizziness, headache, fatigue, skin rash, and itching. In severe cases, paralysis, unconsciousness, and death can occur.

are used to treat the symptoms of allergies and colds.

Decongestants are used to reduce congestion in the nose and sinuses, providing relief from the symptoms of allergies and colds such as a stuffy nose, sinus pressure, and postnasal drip.

is a condition that occurs when the body loses more fluid than it takes in.

Dehydration is a condition in which the body loses more fluid than it takes in, resulting in symptoms such as extreme thirst, dry mouth, decreased urination, fatigue, confusion, and dizziness.

Delirium is a sudden and often temporary change in mental state or behavior, characterized by confusion, disorientation, and difficulty in focusing or maintaining attention. It can present with symptoms such as restlessness, agitation, delusions, hallucinations, and altered levels of consciousness. It can also cause changes in sleep patterns, mood, and behavior.

Frontotemporal dementia is a group of disorders that cause changes in behavior, language, and movement. Symptoms can include changes in personality, behavior, difficulty speaking, difficulty understanding language, and difficulty with movement. Other symptoms may include difficulty with planning and organization, changes in eating habits, and a lack of motivation.

Vascular dementia is a form of dementia caused by reduced or blocked blood flow to the brain, which can cause brain cells to die. Symptoms of vascular dementia can include memory loss, difficulty with problem solving and reasoning, confusion, changes in behaviour, and difficulty with coordination and movement.

is a progressive neurological disorder that affects a person's thinking and movement.

Dementia with Lewy bodies is a progressive neurological disorder that affects a person's thinking, memory, behavior, and movement. Symptoms can include confusion, memory loss, visual hallucinations, and movement issues such as tremors and stiffness.

fever is a mosquito-borne tropical disease caused by the dengue virus.

Dengue fever is a mosquito-borne tropical disease caused by the dengue virus. Symptoms include fever, headache, muscle and joint pain, skin rash, and nausea. It can also cause severe bleeding and difficulty breathing in more severe cases.

is a condition in which pus collects in a tooth or in the bone at the base of the tooth.

Dental abscess is a condition characterized by the accumulation of pus in a tooth or in the bone at the base of the tooth. Symptoms include toothache, facial swelling, fever, and bad breath.

The symptom of toothache is a sharp, throbbing pain in the teeth or jaw. It can be caused by a cavity, gum disease, or an injury to the mouth. Other symptoms may include sensitivity to temperature and pressure, a sour taste in the mouth, and difficulty eating or drinking.

can cause sore spots, pain and discomfort

Dentures can cause sore spots, pain and discomfort in the mouth due to the denture rubbing against the gums and causing irritation. They can also cause difficulty speaking and eating, and a lack of taste sensation.

is a mood disorder that causes a persistent feeling of sadness and loss of interest.

Depression is a mental health condition characterized by persistent feelings of sadness and lack of interest in activities. It can also lead to a variety of physical and emotional symptoms such as changes in sleep, appetite, energy level, concentration, and self-esteem.

A detached retina is a medical emergency that occurs when the retina, the light-sensitive layer of tissue lining the back of the eye, pulls away from its normal position. Symptoms of a detached retina include flashes of light, floaters, and peripheral vision loss.

Developmental co-ordination disorder (dyspraxia) in children is a neurological disorder that affects movement, coordination and speech. Symptoms can include difficulty with fine and gross motor skills, difficulty with activities such as hopping, skipping, and catching a ball, difficulty with handwriting, and difficulty with speech and language.

is a condition in which the hip joint is not formed properly in the womb.

Developmental dysplasia of the hip is a condition that affects the hip joint, causing it to be malformed in the womb. Symptoms can include difficulty walking, hip pain, and a difference in leg length.

diagnosis: DEXA scan, see Bone density scan (DEXA scan)
symptoms:
is a test that measures the mineral density of bones. It is used to diagnose osteoporosis and other conditions that cause bone loss.

A DEXA scan is used to measure the mineral density of bones and diagnose conditions such as osteoporosis that can cause bone loss. It is a quick and painless procedure that helps identify potential health risks.

can cause a number of symptoms, including:

Diabetes can cause a wide range of symptoms, including increased thirst, frequent urination, fatigue, blurred vision, weight loss, slow-healing sores, and yeast infections. It can also lead to long-term issues such as nerve damage, eye problems, kidney disease, and heart disease.

Type 1 diabetes is an autoimmune condition in which the body's immune system attacks and destroys the cells in the pancreas that produce insulin. Symptoms include increased thirst, frequent urination, weight loss, fatigue, and blurred vision. Long-term complications of type 1 diabetes can include heart disease, kidney disease, nerve damage, and eye problems. 

Type 1 diabetes is an autoimmune condition that destroys the cells in the pancreas that produce insulin. Symptoms include increased thirst, frequent urination, weight loss, fatigue, and blurred vision. Long-term complications can include heart disease, kidney disease, nerve damage, and eye problems.

Type 2 diabetes is a chronic condition that affects the way the body processes blood sugar (glucose). It is caused by the body's inability to make enough insulin or to use the insulin it does make effectively. Symptoms of type 2 diabetes include increased thirst, frequent urination, fatigue, blurred vision, slow wound healing, and weight loss.

diagnosis: Diabetes in pregnancy, see Gestational diabetes
symptoms: Gestational diabetes is a type of diabetes that develops during pregnancy. It is characterized by high blood sugar levels and can lead to complications such as excessive birth weight and preterm labor. Symptoms include increased thirst, hunger, and frequent urination. If left untreated, it can lead to serious health risks for both mother and baby.

is a rare condition that occurs when a person's kidneys are unable to conserve water.

Diabetes insipidus is a rare condition characterized by excessive urination, thirst, and dehydration. It is caused by the kidneys not being able to conserve water and is often treated with hormone replacement therapy.

is a critical procedure for people with diabetes

Diabetic eye screening is an important procedure for people with diabetes, as it helps to detect any changes in the eyes that may be caused by diabetes. It is recommended that people with diabetes have their eyes checked regularly to ensure that their vision is not affected by diabetes-related complications. Symptoms to watch for include blurred vision, double vision, and difficulty seeing at night.

(DKA) is a serious complication of diabetes that occurs when your body produces high levels of blood acids called ketones.

Diabetic ketoacidosis is a serious complication of diabetes characterized by high levels of ketones in the blood. Symptoms include nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, excessive thirst and urination, fatigue, and fruity-smelling breath.

is a diabetic complication that affects eyes.

Diabetic retinopathy is a complication of diabetes that affects the eyes. It is caused by damage to the blood vessels of the light-sensitive tissue at the back of the eye (retina). Symptoms can include blurred vision, difficulty seeing colors, and dark spots in vision.

is a medical procedure used to filter and purify the blood of toxins and excess fluid when the kidneys are no longer able to do so.

Dialysis is a medical procedure used to help people with failing kidneys. It involves filtering and purifying the blood, removing toxins and excess fluid, as the kidneys are no longer able to perform this function. Symptoms of kidney failure can include swelling, fatigue, nausea, and difficulty breathing.

are common symptoms of food poisoning

Diarrhoea and vomiting are common symptoms of food poisoning. They can both occur shortly after eating contaminated food, and can last for several days. Diarrhoea is frequent, watery stools, whilst vomiting is the expulsion of stomach contents through the mouth.

The symptoms of diarrhoea and vomiting include frequent loose or watery stools, nausea, abdominal cramps, and sometimes fever. Vomiting may also occur, leading to dehydration. Diarrhoea can be caused by a range of illnesses and infections.

Differences in sex development is a condition in which a person's biological sex characteristics do not match the sex they were assigned at birth. Symptoms include abnormal hormone levels, ambiguous genitalia, and reproductive issues.

is a rare disorder caused by a missing piece of chromosome 22.

DiGeorge Syndrome is a genetic disorder caused by a deletion of a small piece of chromosome 22. Symptoms of this disorder include heart defects, low calcium levels, poor immune system function, cleft palate, and learning difficulties.

is an acute bacterial infection that primarily affects the throat and upper airways.

Diphtheria is an infectious disease that affects the throat and upper respiratory system. Symptoms include sore throat, fever, swollen glands, and a thick, gray coating on the throat and tonsils. It can also cause difficulty breathing and heart problems.

Discoid eczema is a chronic skin condition that causes red, scaly, and itchy patches to appear on the skin. The patches are usually round in shape and can occur on any part of the body. They may ooze and crust over, and can be accompanied by swelling and tenderness.

A dislocated kneecap is a painful injury that causes the knee to become misaligned. Symptoms include severe pain in the knee, swelling, difficulty moving the knee, and an inability to bear weight on the affected leg.

A dislocated shoulder is a painful injury that occurs when the upper arm bone pops out of the shoulder socket. Symptoms may include intense pain, swelling, bruising, and difficulty moving the shoulder. Numbness or tingling in the arm or hand may also occur.

can stem from a variety of causes, including traumatic brain injury, stroke, and other neurological diseases.

Disorders of consciousness are medical conditions that affect a person's ability to be aware of their environment and themselves. They can be caused by traumatic brain injury, stroke, or other neurological diseases. Symptoms may include confusion, impaired responsiveness, and changes in alertness.

are mental health conditions that involve disruptions or breakdowns of memory, awareness, identity and/or perception

Dissociative disorders involve disruptions in a person's memory, awareness, identity, and/or perception, resulting in feelings of detachment from one's self and reality. Symptoms may include memory loss, depersonalization, derealization, and/or identity confusion.

Diverticular disease is a condition in which small pouches form in the lining of the large intestine. Diverticulitis is a complication of diverticular disease in which the pouches become inflamed or infected. Symptoms of diverticulitis include abdominal cramping, fever, nausea, and changes in bowel habits.

diagnosis: Dog bites, see Animal and human bites
symptoms: A dog bite can cause serious injury and infection. The area may be swollen, red, and painful. The wound may also bleed. In some cases, there may be broken skin, puncture wounds, or even a loss of tissue. In humans, the wound may become infected, leading to fever, chills, and other symptoms.

is a genetic disorder caused by an extra chromosome 21.

Down's syndrome is a genetic disorder caused by an extra chromosome 21. It is characterized by physical and cognitive delays, such as flattened facial features, decreased muscle tone, and intellectual disabilities. Common physical features include small stature, upward slanting eyes, and a single deep crease across the center of the palm. Cognitive delays may present as difficulty speaking, learning, and understanding social cues.

can be caused by a variety of things, including dehydration, weather changes, vitamin deficiencies, and even certain medications.

The symptoms of dry or sore lips include chapped, cracked, or flaky skin on the lips, as well as a burning, tingling, or itching sensation. These symptoms can be caused by dehydration, weather changes, vitamin deficiencies, and certain medications.

, dry eyes, fatigue

The symptoms described are common signs of dehydration. They include a dry mouth, dry eyes, and fatigue. These symptoms may be a sign that the body needs more fluids.

is a condition that affects the hands

Dupuytren's contracture is a condition that affects the hands, causing thickening of the connective tissue in the palm, which leads to the fingers curling inwards and being unable to be straightened. It is a progressive condition that can lead to pain and reduced mobility in the fingers.

DVT is a condition where a blood clot forms in a deep vein, usually in the leg. Symptoms include pain, swelling, and tenderness in the leg, a feeling of warmth in the leg, and skin discoloration in the affected area.

DVT is a condition where a blood clot forms in a deep vein, usually in the leg. Symptoms may include pain, swelling, tenderness, warmth, and discoloration in the affected area.

Dwarfism is a condition in which an individual's growth is significantly restricted. It is typically characterized by abnormally short stature, disproportionate limbs and a variety of other physical characteristics. People with dwarfism typically experience physical and health-related difficulties throughout their lives. They may face issues with mobility, visibility, and medical complications due to their size.

Dysarthria is a motor speech disorder that affects the muscles used for speech production. Symptoms can include slurred speech, difficulty articulating words, and changes in volume or pitch. Other symptoms may include difficulty producing certain sounds, drooling, and difficulty swallowing.

is an intestinal infection that causes inflammation and severe diarrhea.

Dysentery is an intestinal infection that can cause inflammation in the intestines and severe diarrhea. Symptoms of dysentery include abdominal pain, nausea, fever, and bloody stools.

is a learning disability that affects reading, writing, spelling, and sometimes speaking

Dyslexia is a learning disability that affects a person's ability to read, write, spell, and sometimes speak. It can cause difficulty in understanding written language, difficulty in writing and organizing thoughts, and difficulty in memorizing information. It can also cause difficulty in understanding spoken language and difficulty in expressing thoughts and ideas clearly.

Dysphagia is a medical condition that affects an individual's ability to swallow. Symptoms of dysphagia include difficulty in initiating swallowing, feeling a lump in the throat, a sensation of food sticking in the throat or chest, and coughing or choking while eating. Other symptoms may include excessive salivation, heartburn, and frequent throat clearing.

Dyspraxia (developmental co-ordination disorder) in adults is characterized by difficulty with fine and gross motor skills, and with planning and carrying out tasks. Symptoms can include clumsiness, difficulty with handwriting, difficulty with activities of daily living such as dressing, difficulty with language and communication, and difficulty with managing time, money, and organizing.

Dyspraxia in adults is characterized by difficulty with motor skills, activities of daily living, language and communication, and managing time, money, and organizing. Symptoms include clumsiness, difficulty with handwriting, and difficulty carrying out tasks.

diagnosis: Dyspraxia in children, see Developmental co-ordination disorder (dyspraxia) in children
symptoms: Developmental co-ordination disorder (dyspraxia) in children is a disorder that affects motor skills, such as balance and coordination. Symptoms include difficulty with activities such as drawing, writing and playing sports, as well as clumsiness, poor posture, and difficulty with fine motor skills. Additionally, children with dyspraxia may struggle with social skills, have difficulty following instructions, and have difficulty with memory and organization.

is a neurological disorder that causes involuntary muscle contractions.

Dystonia is a neurological disorder that causes involuntary and sustained muscle contractions, often resulting in repetitive and twisting movements or abnormal postures. It can affect any part of the body, and can range from mild to severe. Symptoms may include difficulty walking, speaking, and swallowing, and can cause pain or fatigue.

are a common problem among children

Ear infections are a common problem in children, with symptoms such as earache, fever, tugging at the ear, and difficulty hearing. Other symptoms can include loss of balance, vomiting, and drainage from the ear.

, sore throat, and fever

A perforated eardrum is an injury to the thin membrane that separates the middle ear from the outer ear. Symptoms of a perforated eardrum include hearing loss, pain, drainage of fluid from the ear, and ringing in the ear.

is a condition in which a woman’s ovaries stop producing hormones, leading to the end of her menstrual cycle.

Early menopause is a condition in which a woman's body stops producing hormones from the ovaries, resulting in the end of her menstrual cycle. This can cause symptoms such as hot flashes, night sweats, vaginal dryness, and irregular periods.

Early or delayed puberty refers to the onset of physical changes associated with puberty occurring either before or after the usual age range. Symptoms of early puberty include breast development, growth of pubic and armpit hair, and menstrual cycles in girls and increased testicle size and pubic hair growth in boys. Symptoms of delayed puberty include lack of breast development in girls, lack of testicle or penis growth in boys, and lack of pubic and armpit hair in both sexes.

, muffled hearing, itching, and pain

The symptoms of earwax build-up are muffled hearing, itching, and pain in the ear. It can also cause discharge from the ear.

are serious mental health conditions that cause people to adopt unhealthy eating habits.

Eating disorders are serious mental health conditions that cause people to engage in unhealthy eating habits such as restricting food intake, binging and purging, or overeating. These behaviors can lead to physical, emotional, and social complications.

Ebola virus disease is a severe, often fatal illness in humans. Its symptoms include fever, severe headache, muscle pain, fatigue, diarrhea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and unexplained bleeding or bruising. In some cases, it can also lead to an infection of the lungs, eyes, or central nervous system.

Ectopic beats, commonly referred to as heart palpitations, are an abnormality of the heart rhythm which can lead to feelings of skipped beats, fluttering, or irregular heartbeats. They are typically harmless, but can be indicative of more serious issues.

is a complication of pregnancy in which the fertilized egg implants outside of the uterus.

Ectopic pregnancy is a medical complication in which a fertilized egg implants outside of the uterus, usually in the fallopian tube. This can cause abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, and other symptoms. If left untreated, ectopic pregnancy can be life-threatening.

is a medical condition in which the eyelid turns outward away from the eye.

Ectropion is a medical condition in which the affected eyelid turns outward, away from the eye. Symptoms may include redness, irritation, tearing, and a burning sensation in the eye. In some cases, the eyelid may become swollen and the eye may become dry.

Atopic eczema is a chronic skin condition that causes itchy, red and dry patches to appear on the skin. Symptoms can range from mild to severe, with the most common being inflammation, itching, redness, dryness, and flaking of the skin. Symptoms can vary from person to person, but may worsen with stress, environmental triggers, and allergies.

Contact dermatitis is a skin reaction to an allergen or irritant. Symptoms of contact dermatitis include red, itchy, and scaly patches on the skin, as well as swelling, burning, and sometimes blisters. It is often caused by contact with an allergen or irritant, such as a chemical, plant, or animal.

Discoid eczema is a skin condition that causes a red, itchy, scaly rash. It is usually seen on the face, scalp, chest, and back. It can also cause thickened, discolored patches of skin. Symptoms may include intense itching, dryness, and cracking of the skin. In more severe cases, the rash may become infected.

Varicose eczema is a skin condition in which the skin becomes dry, itchy, and inflamed, and may develop scaly patches, blisters, and cracks. It is most common in the lower legs and can be caused by increased pressure in the veins due to poor circulation or an underlying medical condition. Symptoms can also include pain, swelling, and discoloration.

Edwards' syndrome, also known as trisomy 18, is a chromosomal disorder caused by the presence of a third copy of all or part of chromosome 18. It is associated with severe intellectual disability, developmental delays, and physical abnormalities. Symptoms may include low birth weight, a small head, a small jaw, clenched fists, overlapping fingers, and malformation of the heart and other organs.

(EDS) is a group of inherited disorders that affect connective tissues, which are tissues that support the skin, bones, blood vessels, and other organs.

Ehlers-Danlos syndromes (EDS) is a group of inherited disorders that cause problems with the connective tissues in the body. Symptoms can include joint hypermobility, loose and fragile skin, and easy bruising. Other symptoms may include weak muscles, poor wound healing, organ prolapse, and stretchy tissue in the skin or internal organs.

is a test

An electrocardiogram (ECG) is a test that records the electrical activity of the heart. It is used to detect heart rate and rhythm abnormalities, as well as to diagnose heart conditions such as arrhythmias, heart attacks, and other heart diseases. Symptoms of a heart condition may include chest pain, shortness of breath, palpitations, dizziness, or fainting. ECG can help diagnose the cause of these symptoms.

An electroencephalogram (EEG) is a test used to measure electrical activity in the brain. It is typically done by attaching electrodes to the scalp, which measure the brain's electrical signals. Symptoms that may indicate the need for an EEG include seizures, headaches, confusion, or changes in behavior or personality. An EEG can also be used to diagnose certain types of brain disorders.

An electroencephalogram (EEG) is a test used to measure electrical activity in the brain. Symptoms that may indicate the need for an EEG include seizures, headaches, confusion, or changes in behavior or personality. An EEG can also be used to diagnose certain types of brain disorders.

Electrolyte tests measure levels of electrolytes in the blood, such as sodium, potassium, and chloride. Low levels can cause symptoms like fatigue, dizziness, muscle cramps, confusion, and irregular heartbeat, while high levels can lead to nausea, vomiting, excessive thirst, and weakness.

is a blood clot that has traveled through the bloodstream and become lodged in a blood vessel.

Embolism is a medical condition that occurs when a blood clot becomes lodged in a blood vessel, blocking the flow of blood. Symptoms of embolism include pain, swelling, and discoloration of the affected area, as well as difficulty breathing and loss of consciousness.

are used to treat dry skin conditions, such as eczema, which cause the skin to become dry, itchy and inflamed.

Emollients are used to treat dry skin conditions, such as eczema, which cause dryness, itching, and inflammation of the skin. They help to soothe and moisturize the skin, reducing the symptoms of these conditions.

is a rare disease that is caused by bacteria and is characterized by a collection of pus in the chest cavity.

Empyema is a rare bacterial infection that causes a collection of pus to form in the chest cavity. Symptoms of the condition include chest pain, difficulty breathing, fever, and fatigue.

is an inflammation of the brain, usually caused by a viral infection.

Encephalitis is a medical condition where the brain becomes inflamed, usually due to a viral infection. Symptoms of encephalitis include headache, fever, confusion, seizures, and drowsiness. In severe cases, it can cause coma, paralysis, and even death.

is a serious infection of the inner lining of the heart chambers and valves.

Endocarditis is an infection of the inner lining of the heart, including the heart chambers and valves. Symptoms may include fever, fatigue, shortness of breath, chest pain, and swelling of the legs and feet. Other symptoms may include a heart murmur, joint pain, and small areas of bleeding under the skin.

Endometrial cancer is a type of cancer that affects the uterus, specifically the endometrium or inner lining of the uterus. Symptoms of this type of cancer can include vaginal bleeding, pain or discomfort in the pelvic area, and abnormal vaginal discharge. Other symptoms may include fatigue, nausea, and feeling full quickly after eating.

is a condition where tissue that usually grows inside the uterus grows outside the uterus.

Endometriosis is a condition where the endometrial tissue, which is normally found inside the uterus, grows outside of the uterus. Symptoms of endometriosis include lower abdominal pain, pain during or after sexual intercourse, painful periods, and heavy menstrual bleeding.

after surgery (ERAS)

Enhanced Recovery After Surgery (ERAS) is a program designed to reduce the physical and psychological stress of surgery and speed up recovery time. The goal is to reduce the time spent in the hospital, reduce post-operative complications, and improve patient outcomes. Common components of ERAS include preoperative education and preparation, optimized nutrition and hydration, multimodal pain management, early mobilization and functional exercises, and early discharge planning.

is a rare genetic disorder that causes the skin to become very fragile and blister easily.

Epidermolysis bullosa is a rare genetic disorder characterized by fragile skin that blisters easily. Affected individuals may experience blistering of the skin, mucous membranes and internal organs. Blisters can be painful and lead to infection, scarring, and disability.

is an inflammation of the epididymis, a tube located at the back of the testicles.

Epididymitis is an inflammation of the epididymis, a tube located at the back of the testicles. Symptoms include pain in the scrotum or testicles, swelling of the scrotum, pain when urinating, fever, and a discharge from the penis.

hematoma is a condition caused by a head injury that results in bleeding between the skull and the outermost covering of the brain.

Epidural hematoma is a condition caused by a head injury that results in bleeding between the skull and the outermost covering of the brain. Symptoms of this condition include headache, confusion, drowsiness, nausea, and vomiting. Loss of consciousness, seizures, and paralysis on one side of the body may also occur.

is an infectious disease that affects the epiglottis.

Epiglottitis is an infectious disease that affects the epiglottis, the flap of cartilage that covers the entrance to the larynx. Symptoms include sore throat, high fever, difficulty swallowing, and muffled voice. In severe cases, the airway can become blocked, leading to difficulty breathing.

is a neurological disorder that causes recurrent, unprovoked seizures.

Epilepsy is a neurological disorder that causes recurrent seizures that can occur without warning. These seizures can be caused by a variety of factors, including genetics, brain injuries, or medical conditions. Symptoms of epilepsy can include loss of consciousness, convulsions, and uncontrollable muscle twitching.

is the inability to get and keep an erection firm enough for sex.

Erectile dysfunction (impotence) is a condition in which a man is unable to get or maintain an erection firm enough for sexual intercourse. It can be caused by physical or psychological factors.

(EM) is a skin disorder that is typically characterized by a rash with target-like lesions.

Erythema multiforme (EM) is a skin disorder that causes a rash with target-like lesions. These lesions are usually red in color and may be raised or flat. They can appear anywhere on the body and usually cause itching, burning, and pain.

is a skin condition that causes tender red bumps to appear on the shins, arms, and face.

Erythema nodosum is a skin condition that causes red, tender bumps to appear on the shins, arms, and face. The bumps are usually painful and may be accompanied by fever, joint pain, and fatigue.

is a medical condition characterized by an increase in the number of red blood cells (RBCs) in the blood

Erythrocytosis is a medical condition where there is an abnormally high number of RBCs in the blood. The symptoms of this condition may include headaches, dizziness, shortness of breath, fatigue, and an increased heart rate.

is a rare disorder characterized by episodes of burning pain, redness, and swelling in the hands and feet

Erythromelalgia is a rare disorder that causes episodes of burning pain, redness, and swelling in the hands and feet. Symptoms can be triggered by heat, exercise, or emotional stress. Sufferers may also experience tingling, numbness, and a feeling of tightness in the affected areas.

diagnosis: Essential tremor, see Tremor or shaking hands
symptoms: Essential tremor is a neurological disorder characterized by a tremor or shaking in the hands. The tremor can also affect other parts of the body such as the head, voice, and even the legs.

are two different methods of ending life.

Euthanasia is the act of ending someone's life in a painless way, usually at their request. Assisted suicide is when a doctor provides a person with the means to end their own life.

is a rare type of cancer that typically affects bone or soft tissue.

Ewing sarcoma is a rare type of cancer that affects bone or soft tissue. Symptoms can include pain, swelling, and/or tenderness around the affected area, as well as fever and fatigue. It may also cause bone fractures or cause limping and other difficulties in movement.

Excessive daytime sleepiness (hypersomnia) is a condition in which a person experiences abnormal sleepiness during the day. It can cause a person to become very sleepy during the day and have difficulty staying awake or alert. Symptoms of hypersomnia can include difficulty waking up in the morning, excessive sleepiness during the day, difficulty concentrating, and feeling tired even after sleeping for long periods of time.

Hirsutism is a condition that causes excessive hair growth on areas of the body where hair is typically not seen in women, such as the face, chest, abdomen, and back. It is often caused by an excess of androgens, or male hormones, in the body. Symptoms include thick, dark hair growth on the face, chest, or other body parts, as well as acne and irregular periods.

Hyperhidrosis is a condition which causes excessive sweating. It can affect any area of the body, but commonly affects the hands, feet, armpits and face. Symptoms include profuse sweating, clammy skin, and a strong odor. In extreme cases, it can cause discomfort and embarrassment.

Burns can cause severe pain, redness, and swelling of the affected area. Blisters may also form in more severe cases. First aid for a burn includes running cool water over the area for at least 20 minutes, removing any clothing or jewelry from the area, and applying a clean bandage.

diagnosis: Fits (children with fever), see Febrile seizures
symptoms: Febrile seizures are convulsions caused by a high fever in children. Symptoms include shaking and stiffness of the body, loss of consciousness, and difficulty breathing. The child may also experience confusion, sleepiness, and changes in vision.

diagnosis: Fits (seizures), see What to do if someone has a seizure (fit)
symptoms:
Someone having a seizure may experience a variety of symptoms, including loss of consciousness, muscle twitching or jerking, stiffening of the body, confusion, and/or changes in vision. They may also experience loss of bladder or bowel control, unusual noises or vocalizations, and/or feelings of fear or panic. 

Someone having a seizure may experience a loss of consciousness, muscle twitching or jerking, stiffening of the body, confusion, changes in vision, loss of bladder or bowel control, unusual noises or vocalizations, and feelings of fear or panic.

is a condition in which the arch of the foot collapses and the entire sole of the foot comes into complete or near-complete contact with the ground.

Flat feet is a condition where the arch of the foot collapses, causing the entire sole of the foot to come into contact with the ground completely or nearly completely. This can result in pain, discomfort, and difficulty with walking.

diagnosis: Flat head syndrome, see Plagiocephaly and brachycephaly (flat head syndrome)
symptoms: Flat head syndrome is a condition in which the head has an abnormal shape due to pressure on the back or side of the skull. It is also known as plagiocephaly or brachycephaly. Symptoms include an asymmetrical or flattened shape of the head, a bulge on one side of the head, and the ear may be positioned higher or lower than the other. It is most commonly seen in infants due to the shape of their skulls.

Flatulence is the passing of gas from the digestive system out of the back passage. It is a normal and usually healthy occurrence, however it can be embarrassing. Symptoms can include abdominal bloating, discomfort or pain, and sometimes a loud noise (farting).

diagnosis: Floaters and flashes in the eyes
symptoms: Floaters and flashes in the eyes are symptoms of a possible retinal detachment. Floaters are small spots or lines that appear in the field of vision, while flashes are streaks of light that appear in the corner of the eye. Both of these symptoms can be signs of a serious eye condition and should be checked out by an ophthalmologist right away.

toxicity is caused by excessive intake of fluoride

Fluoride toxicity is a condition where a person has taken in too much fluoride. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and weakness. In extreme cases, it can lead to seizures, coma, and even death.

(FASD)

Foetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder (FASD) is a range of physical, mental, and behavioural problems that can occur in a person whose mother consumed alcohol during pregnancy. Symptoms may include physical growth deficiencies, facial abnormalities, learning disabilities, and behavioural problems such as difficulty with attention, social skills, and problem-solving.

Food allergy is a condition in which the body's immune system reacts abnormally to certain foods. Symptoms can include itching, hives, swelling, abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and difficulty breathing. In severe cases, anaphylaxis can occur, which is a life-threatening reaction.

This text discusses the potential link between food colours and hyperactivity in children. It states that studies have shown that certain food colours, especially artificial ones, may lead to increased hyperactivity in children. This can lead to increased restlessness, impulsiveness, and difficulty concentrating.

Food intolerance is an abnormal response to certain foods, which occurs after eating or drinking them. Symptoms of food intolerance can include bloating, stomach cramps, nausea, diarrhoea, and headaches. These symptoms can occur within a few minutes to a few hours after consuming the food.

is an illness caused by eating contaminated food

Food poisoning is an illness caused by eating food that has been contaminated with bacteria, viruses, or other toxins. Symptoms can include nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and diarrhea. In severe cases, food poisoning can cause dehydration, fever, and even death.

is a symptom of an underlying neurological or muscular disorder

Foot drop is a condition in which a person has difficulty lifting the front part of their foot, resulting in an inability to walk normally. It may be caused by an underlying neurological or muscular disorder, such as nerve damage or muscle weakness. Symptoms of foot drop include difficulty lifting the foot and toes, dragging the toes when walking, tripping or catching the toes on the ground, and a decreased ability to walk.

is a common problem that can be caused by a variety of conditions.

Foot pain is a common issue that can have a variety of causes. Symptoms may include tenderness, swelling, burning, tingling, and numbness in the feet.

Tight foreskin (phimosis) is a condition where the foreskin is too tight to be pulled back over the head of the penis. Symptoms of this condition include difficulty retracting the foreskin, pain, redness, and swelling at the tip of the penis. In some cases, infection and balanitis may occur.

is a neurological disorder that affects the frontal and temporal lobes of the brain.

Frontotemporal dementia is a neurological disorder that affects the frontal and temporal lobes of the brain, causing a progressive decline in cognitive abilities. Symptoms may include difficulty with language, changes in personality, and difficulty performing daily activities. Other symptoms may include changes in behavior, difficulty with memory, and difficulty with decision-making.

can cause severe tissue damage

Frostbite is a condition caused by the freezing of skin and underlying tissues. Symptoms include a loss of feeling and a white or pale appearance to the affected area. In severe cases, blisters and skin discoloration can occur, and the tissue may become hard and numb. In extreme cases, the tissue may even die, leading to long-term damage and even amputation.

is a condition that causes pain and stiffness in the shoulder

Frozen shoulder (also known as adhesive capsulitis) is a condition characterized by pain and stiffness in the shoulder joint. It is usually accompanied by a limitation in the range of motion of the shoulder, making it difficult to move the arm. It is a common cause of shoulder pain and typically affects people aged 40-70 years old.

diagnosis: Functional neurological disorder, see Medically unexplained symptoms
symptoms: Functional neurological disorder (FND) is a medical condition characterized by neurological symptoms such as weakness, sensory disturbances, and altered movement that cannot be explained by a neurological disease or other medical condition. It is also known as medically unexplained symptoms. Symptoms may come and go, vary in intensity, and can affect any part of the body. Possible treatments include physical and occupational therapy, cognitive behavior therapy, and medications.

is a common condition that begins as a white or yellow spot under the tip of your fingernail or toenail.

Fungal nail infection is a common condition that affects the nails. It is characterized by a white or yellow spot under the tip of the fingernail or toenail. It may also cause the nail to become thick, brittle, and discolored. Other symptoms include pain, discomfort, and foul odor.

Gallbladder cancer is a rare type of cancer that affects the gallbladder, an organ in the abdomen that stores bile from the liver. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, yellowing of the skin and eyes, or a lump in the abdomen.
Acute cholecystitis is an inflammation of the gallbladder that causes severe pain in the upper right abdomen, nausea, vomiting and fever. There may also be pain in the right shoulder and back.
The patient is experiencing pain in their upper-right abdomen, fever, chills, nausea, and vomiting. These symptoms suggest that the gallbladder may need to be removed.

are hard, pebble-like deposits that form in the gallbladder.

Gallstones are deposits that form in the gallbladder and are usually hard and pebble-like in shape. They can cause pain and discomfort, as well as nausea, vomiting, and jaundice.

A ganglion cyst is a fluid-filled bump that usually appears near a joint. It can cause pain, swelling, and a feeling of tightness around the affected area. It may also interfere with the movement of the joint.

is a serious condition

Gangrene is a serious condition that occurs when tissues in the body die due to a lack of blood flow. Symptoms include pain, discoloration of the skin, and a foul smell. Left untreated, gangrene can lead to serious health complications, including infection, tissue death, and even death.

is a surgical procedure to remove all or part of the stomach

Gastrectomy is a surgical procedure to remove all or part of the stomach. Symptoms of needing a gastrectomy may include nausea, vomiting, difficulty swallowing, unexplained weight loss, and abdominal pain.

is an inflammation of the stomach lining which can cause stomach pain, nausea, and loss of appetite.

Gastritis is an inflammation of the stomach lining which can cause symptoms such as stomach pain, nausea, and loss of appetite. This can lead to discomfort and difficulty eating.

diagnosis: Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD), see Heartburn and acid reflux
symptoms: Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) is a condition in which stomach acid leaks back up into the oesophagus, causing symptoms such as heartburn and acid reflux. It is a common condition, affecting around 1 in 5 adults. Symptoms can include chest pain, a burning sensation in the throat, difficulty swallowing, and a sour taste in the mouth.

Gastroenteritis is a condition that causes diarrhoea and vomiting. Symptoms include abdominal pain, nausea, and cramps. In some cases, fever, chills, and fatigue may also occur. It is usually caused by a virus or bacteria, and can be spread through contact with an infected person or contaminated food or water.

is a condition in which the stomach takes too long to empty its contents.

Gastroparesis is a condition where the stomach takes longer than normal to empty its contents. Symptoms include nausea, vomiting, feeling full quickly, abdominal pain, and changes in blood sugar levels.

showed erosive gastritis with multiple erosions.

Gastroscopy revealed a condition of erosive gastritis, which is characterized by multiple erosions on the lining of the stomach. These erosions can cause discomfort, pain, and other symptoms.

is a condition where a person experiences discomfort or distress because there’s a mismatch between their biological sex and gender identity.

Gender dysphoria is a condition where an individual experiences distress due to a mismatch between their biological sex and gender identity. Symptoms may include a strong desire to be of a different gender, a strong dislike of one's own gender, and a strong desire to have a different gender role. Other symptoms may include feeling disconnected from one's body, feeling a strong sense of shame or anxiety, and feeling a sense of isolation.

is a medical procedure

General anaesthesia is a medical procedure in which patients are put into a deep sleep-like state to undergo surgery or other medical procedures. Symptoms of general anaesthesia include sleepiness, confusion, and loss of consciousness. Patients may also experience temporary amnesia, muscle relaxation, and loss of reflexes.

Generalised anxiety disorder (GAD) in adults is characterised by persistent and excessive worry about a variety of topics and activities for at least six months. People with GAD often feel overwhelmed and struggle to control their worries. Some common symptoms of GAD include difficulty concentrating, feeling restless or on edge, feeling tired, having difficulty sleeping, and having muscle tension or headaches.

Genetic and genomic testing is a type of medical test that involves examining a person's DNA, genes, and chromosomes to determine if they have a genetic disorder, identify their risk of developing a genetic disorder, or identify their risk of passing a genetic disorder to their children. It can also help diagnose a wide range of medical conditions, including birth defects, developmental delays, and inherited diseases. Symptoms associated with genetic and genomic testing include abnormal physical features, developmental delays, and other health issues.

diagnosis: Genetic test for cancer gene, see Predictive genetic tests for cancer risk genes
symptoms: Predictive genetic tests for cancer risk genes are tests that can help identify individuals who have an increased risk of developing certain types of cancer due to inherited genetic mutations. These tests can help identify individuals who are at higher risk of developing certain types of cancer, such as breast, ovarian, colorectal, and prostate cancer. These tests can also help inform decisions regarding prevention and treatment options.

is a common sexually transmitted infection that is caused by the herpes simplex virus.

Genital herpes is an infection caused by the herpes simplex virus, which is spread through sexual contact. Symptoms include itching, burning, and blisters or sores in the genital area. Other symptoms may include fever, headache, and muscle aches.

are small, fleshy, non-cancerous growths that appear on or around your genitals.

Genital warts are small, fleshy growths that appear on or around the genitals. They are non-cancerous, but can be itchy or uncomfortable. They can spread through skin-to-skin contact and can be treated with medication.

Rubella, commonly known as German measles, is a viral infection that is usually mild and causes a rash on the body. Symptoms include a mild fever, sore throat, swollen glands, and a rash that usually starts on the face and spreads to the rest of the body. Complications are rare but can include inflammation of the brain and deafness.

is a type of diabetes that develops during pregnancy

Gestational diabetes is a type of diabetes that affects pregnant women. It is caused by an increase in the body's resistance to insulin, resulting in high blood sugar levels. Symptoms include increased thirst, frequent urination, fatigue, and blurred vision. Left untreated, gestational diabetes can cause complications for both mother and baby.

diagnosis: Giant cell arteritis, see Temporal arteritis
symptoms: Giant cell arteritis (also known as temporal arteritis) is a condition in which the lining of the arteries become inflamed. Symptoms include pain in the temples, jaw pain, vision changes, headache, fever, and scalp tenderness. In severe cases, blindness may occur.

is an intestinal infection caused by a parasite

Giardiasis is an intestinal infection caused by a parasite that can cause diarrhea, abdominal cramps, bloating, gas, weight loss, fatigue, and nausea. In some cases, the infection may not cause any symptoms at all.

Gigantism is a condition where abnormal growth of the body is caused by an excess of growth hormone in children before the growth plates in their bones close. It is characterized by an increase in height and body size, with larger hands, feet, and facial features. Acromegaly is a similar condition that occurs in adulthood and is caused by the same excess of growth hormone. Symptoms include enlarged hands, feet, and facial features, as well as joint and muscle pain.

is a common, mild liver disorder in which the liver doesn't properly process bilirubin.

Gilbert's syndrome is a disorder that affects the liver, causing an inability to process bilirubin properly. This results in elevated levels of bilirubin in the blood, which can cause fatigue, pale stools and yellowing of the skin and eyes.

is a type of viral infection that causes fever, sore throat, swollen glands, and extreme tiredness.

Glandular fever is a viral infection that causes a high fever, a sore throat, swollen glands, and extreme fatigue. It is also known as the 'kissing disease' due to the common mode of transmission.

is a condition that causes damage to the optic nerve.

Glaucoma is an eye condition that causes damage to the optic nerve, which can lead to vision loss and blindness. Symptoms of glaucoma include increased pressure in the eye, blurred vision, and loss of peripheral vision.

is a group of diseases that injure the part of the kidney that filters blood (called glomeruli).

Glomerulonephritis is a group of diseases that affect the glomeruli, the part of the kidneys that filters blood. Symptoms can include swelling, blood in the urine, high blood pressure, fatigue, and foamy or bubbly urine.

is a condition where fluid builds up in the middle ear.

Glue ear is a condition where fluid accumulates in the middle ear, resulting in hearing loss. It is usually accompanied by other symptoms such as tinnitus, earache, itchiness, and a feeling of fullness in the ear.

is an inherited disorder in which the body is unable to properly break down certain proteins.

Glutaric aciduria type 1 is an inherited metabolic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down proteins. It results in an accumulation of glutaric acid, which can cause symptoms such as vomiting, low muscle tone, irregular movements, and potentially permanent neurological damage.

is a swelling in the neck due to an enlarged thyroid gland.

Goitre is a swelling in the neck caused by an enlarged thyroid gland. It can cause the neck to look swollen and can be tender to the touch. Symptoms may also include difficulty swallowing, a hoarse voice, and a tight feeling in the throat.

is a sexually transmitted infection

Gonorrhoea is a common sexually transmitted infection which is caused by the bacteria Neisseria gonorrhoeae. Symptoms can include a burning sensation during urination, discharge from the genitals, and pain in the lower abdomen. In women, the infection can also cause bleeding between periods. If left untreated, it can cause serious health complications.

is a type of arthritis that causes sudden, severe attacks of pain, redness, and tenderness in joints.

Gout is an inflammatory type of arthritis characterized by sudden and severe attacks of pain, redness, and tenderness in the affected joints. Symptoms can include joint swelling and intense joint pain, as well as redness and warmth in the affected area.

(GA) is a skin condition that typically appears as raised, reddish-brown bumps on the back of the hands, feet, and elbows.

Granuloma annulare is a skin condition that causes raised, reddish-brown bumps on the back of the hands, feet, and elbows. These bumps may be itchy or painful in some cases.

Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (GPA) is an autoimmune disorder that causes inflammation of the walls of small- and medium-sized blood vessels. The most common symptoms of GPA include sinus pain and congestion, nosebleeds, frequent infections, eye pain and vision loss, joint pain, and skin rashes.

Granulomatosis with polyangiitis is an autoimmune disorder that causes inflammation of the walls of small and medium-sized blood vessels. Symptoms can include sinus pain and congestion, nosebleeds, frequent infections, eye pain and vision loss, joint pain, and skin rashes.
