Group B strep is a type of bacteria that can cause a wide range of infections in newborns, pregnant women, and adults. Symptoms can include fever, chills, nausea, vomiting, difficulty breathing, and abdominal pain. In newborns, Group B strep can cause meningitis, sepsis, pneumonia, and other infections. In pregnant women, it can cause urinary tract infections, blood infections, and miscarriages. In adults, it can cause skin, bone, and joint infections.

are a common complaint of children between the ages of three and five.

Growing pains are a common occurrence in children between the ages of three and five. Symptoms may include aching and throbbing pain in the legs, usually in the evening or at night. The pain is usually not serious and typically resolves without treatment.

(GBS) is a rare disorder in which a person's own immune system damages their nerve cells, causing muscle weakness and sometimes paralysis.

Guillain-Barré syndrome (GBS) is a rare disorder where the body's own immune system damages nerve cells, resulting in muscle weakness and in some cases paralysis. Symptoms include tingling, numbness, and weakness in the legs, arms, and face, as well as difficulty breathing and swallowing. In severe cases, it can lead to complete paralysis.

is a chronic infection of the gums caused by plaque buildup.

Gum disease is a bacterial infection of the gums caused by the accumulation of plaque. Symptoms include red, swollen, and bleeding gums, receding gums, and bad breath. In advanced stages, the infection can lead to tooth loss.

is a condition caused by too much iron in the body

Haemochromatosis is a condition in which too much iron is stored in the body. Symptoms include joint pain, fatigue, abdominal pain, abnormal skin color, weight loss, and diabetes. Other complications can include heart disease, liver disease, and arthritis.

is an inherited blood disorder that impairs the body's ability to make blood clots.

Haemophilia is a genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to clot blood. It causes excessive bleeding, even from minor cuts, and can lead to serious health complications. Symptoms include spontaneous bleeding, abnormal bleeding after surgery or trauma, and excessive bleeding after dental work.

is a bacteria that can cause a serious infection.

Hib can cause a serious infection, including meningitis, pneumonia, ear infections, and epiglottitis. It can also cause blood poisoning, joint infections, and other serious illnesses. Symptoms of Hib infection can include fever, chills, headache, stiff neck, rash, and confusion.

Haemorrhoids, also known as Piles, are swollen veins in the rectum and anus that can cause discomfort, itching, and pain. Symptoms of haemorrhoids include bleeding, itching, and irritation in the anal area. In some cases, haemorrhoids can become large and painful.

Hair dye reactions can range from mild skin irritation, redness, and itching to more severe reactions such as hives, difficulty breathing, and swelling. Other symptoms may include burning, stinging, and tingling of the scalp.

Hair dye reactions can cause mild skin irritation, redness, itching, hives, difficulty breathing, swelling, burning, stinging, and tingling of the scalp.

Halitosis, or bad breath, is a condition that causes a person to have an unpleasant odor coming from their mouth. It can be caused by poor oral hygiene, dry mouth, certain medications, or other medical conditions. Symptoms include a bad taste in the mouth, a burning sensation, and an unpleasant odor.

is a seasonal allergic reaction to pollen and other airborne particles

Hay fever is an allergic reaction to pollen and other airborne particles in the air. Symptoms include sneezing, nasal congestion, itchy eyes, watery eyes, runny nose, and a scratchy throat. It is most common during the spring and fall months, when pollen counts are highest.

Head and neck cancer is a type of cancer that develops in the tissues of the head and neck, including the mouth, nose, throat, and salivary glands. are a common problem for school-aged children

Hormone headaches are headaches that are caused by fluctuations in hormone levels, such as those that take place during menstruation, pregnancy, menopause, or when taking birth control pills. Tension headaches, also known as tension-type headaches, are the most common type of headache. They are often triggered by stress, anxiety, fatigue, depression, or changes in sleep patterns.

is a condition in which a person is excessively worried about their health

Health anxiety is a mental health condition in which a person experiences an excessive and persistent fear of having a serious illness, even when there is no medical evidence to suggest that they are unwell. People with health anxiety often experience physical symptoms due to their fear and worry, such as sweating, increased heart rate, chest pain, and difficulty breathing. They may also experience psychological symptoms such as increased anxiety, difficulty sleeping, and difficulty concentrating.

Hearing aids and implants are used to help people with hearing loss. Hearing aids amplify sound and are worn in or behind the ear, while implants are surgically placed in the inner ear and help to bypass damaged parts of the auditory system. is a condition in which the electrical signal that tells your heart when to beat is partially or completely blocked.

Heart block is a condition where the electrical signal that controls the timing of the heartbeat is partially or completely blocked, resulting in the heart beating slower than normal or not at all. This can lead to symptoms such as dizziness, lightheadedness, shortness of breath, and fainting.

is a condition in which the heart can't pump enough blood to meet the body's needs

is a liver infection caused by the hepatitis C virus (HCV).

Hepatitis C is an infectious liver disease caused by the hepatitis C virus. Symptoms of the virus include fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, abdominal pain, dark urine, and jaundice.

are used in the form of capsules, tablets, syrups, and teas.

Herbal medicines can be taken in multiple forms, such as capsules, tablets, syrups, and teas. These forms can be used to treat a variety of symptoms.

is an inherited disorder characterised by abnormal blood vessel formation in the skin, mucous membranes, and often in organs such as the lungs, liver, and brain

Hereditary haemorrhagic telangiectasia (HHT) is a genetic disorder that results in the formation of abnormal blood vessels in the skin, mucous membranes, and organs such as the lungs, liver, and brain. Symptoms include frequent nosebleeds, coughing up blood, and easy bruising.

is a genetic disorder that affects the peripheral nerves. 

Hereditary Neuropathy with Pressure Palsies is a genetic disorder that affects the peripheral nerves, causing weakness, numbness, and tingling in the arms, legs, and hands. It can also cause muscle cramps, loss of reflexes, and difficulty walking. Symptoms may worsen with pressure on the affected nerves.

(HSP) is a group of neurological disorders that mainly affect the lower limbs.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia (HSP) is a group of neurological disorders characterized by spasticity, weakness, and stiffness in the lower limbs. Symptoms may include difficulty walking, involuntary movements, and difficulty with balance.

is a condition in which an organ or fatty tissue squeezes through a weak spot or tear in the muscle or connective tissue that holds it in place

Hernia is a condition where an organ or fatty tissue protrudes through a weakened area in the muscle or connective tissue that normally contains it. Symptoms of hernia include a noticeable bulge in the affected area, pain or discomfort, and a burning or aching sensation. In some cases, coughing or straining may worsen the symptoms.

A femoral hernia is a protrusion of abdominal tissue through the femoral canal in the groin area. Symptoms of a femoral hernia include pain and swelling in the groin area, a bulge in the upper thigh, or difficulty standing or lifting heavy objects. In rare cases, a femoral hernia can cause nausea or vomiting.

A femoral hernia is characterized by pain and swelling in the groin area, a bulge in the upper thigh, and difficulty standing or lifting heavy objects. In rare cases, nausea or vomiting can occur.

Hiatus hernia is a condition where part of the stomach pushes up through the diaphragm into the chest cavity. Symptoms can include chest pain, heartburn, difficulty swallowing, and a feeling of fullness or bloating. It can worsen when lying down or bending over.

An inguinal hernia is a medical condition in which a part of the intestine or other organ protrudes through the abdominal wall in the groin area. Symptoms include a bulge or lump in the groin area, pain or discomfort in the groin area when coughing, standing or lifting, and a feeling of pressure in the groin area.

Umbilical hernia is a medical condition in which a part of the intestine or other organs protrude through the abdominal wall near the belly button. Symptoms include a bulge or lump in the belly button region that can be seen or felt and pain or discomfort in the area. In some cases, the hernia can cause intestinal blockage, vomiting, or difficulty urinating.

Genital herpes is a sexually-transmitted infection caused by the herpes simplex virus (HSV). It is characterized by the appearance of painful blisters on the genitals, buttocks, and thighs. These blisters may cause itching, burning, and pain. In some cases, they may also cause fever, swollen lymph nodes, and headache. In severe cases, it can cause difficulty urinating and excessive vaginal discharge.

diagnosis: Herpes in babies, see Neonatal herpes (herpes in a baby)
symptoms: Neonatal herpes is a rare but serious condition caused by the herpes simplex virus. Symptoms in babies can include fever, irritability, lethargy, poor feeding, skin rash, and blisters. In severe cases, babies may develop seizures, brain damage, and even death.

Herpes simplex eye infections cause redness, swelling, and itching in the affected eye. They can also cause pain, discharge, and a feeling of pressure in the eye. In some cases, it may cause vision changes, such as blurred vision or sensitivity to light.

is an infection of the finger caused by the herpes virus.

Herpetic whitlow (whitlow finger) is an infection of the finger caused by the herpes virus. Symptoms include redness, swelling, pain, and blisters on the affected finger. It is usually very painful and can cause difficulty with daily activities.

is a condition in which part of the stomach protrudes through the diaphragm and into the chest cavity.

Hiatus hernia is a condition where part of the stomach pushes through the opening in the diaphragm and into the chest cavity. This can cause symptoms such as heartburn, chest pain, difficulty swallowing, and regurgitation.

diagnosis: Hib, see Haemophilus influenzae type b (Hib)
symptoms: Haemophilus influenzae type b (Hib) is a bacterial infection that can cause severe illnesses such as meningitis, pneumonia, and epiglottitis. Symptoms include fever, headache, vomiting, stiff neck, difficulty breathing, and a sore throat. Other symptoms may include confusion, drowsiness, and seizures. In some cases, there may be no symptoms at all.

are spasms of the diaphragm that cause a sudden intake of breath.

Hiccups are involuntary spasms of the diaphragm that cause a sudden intake of breath, accompanied by a characteristic "hic" sound. They can be short-lived or last for long periods of time.

is a chronic skin condition that causes painful, boil-like lumps to develop in areas where the skin rubs together.

Hidradenitis suppurativa (HS) is a chronic skin condition that causes painful lumps to develop in areas where skin rubs together, such as the armpits, groin, and under the breasts. These lumps are often filled with pus and can be very painful.

is a common condition in which the long-term force of the blood against your artery walls is high enough that it may eventually cause health problems, such as heart disease.

High blood pressure is a condition where the long-term force of the blood against the artery walls is too high. This can lead to health problems such as heart disease.

High blood sugar (hyperglycaemia) is a condition where the body has too much glucose in the blood. Symptoms can include increased thirst and urination, fatigue, and blurred vision. Long-term complications can include damage to the kidneys, eyes, and nerves.

is a condition in which you have too much of a certain type of fat, called cholesterol, in your blood.

High cholesterol is a condition in which there is an excess of cholesterol in the blood. It is caused by an imbalance in the ratio of cholesterol in the body, resulting in an unhealthy level of cholesterol in the blood.

High temperature (fever) in adults is a common symptom of illness and is typically accompanied by shivering, headaches, and general fatigue. It is usually an indication that the body is fighting off a virus or infection.

Children with high temperature (fever) may experience chills, sweating, headache, loss of appetite, body aches, and fatigue. They may also experience a flushed face, rapid breathing, and a fast heart rate.

diagnosis: Hip dysplasia, see Developmental dysplasia of the hip
symptoms: Hip dysplasia is a condition that affects the hip joint and can cause pain, instability and limited range of motion. It is a common condition in young children and can occur in one or both hips. Symptoms can include a hip or groin pain, a limp or difficulty walking, and a clicking or grinding sound when the hip is moved.

Hip pain in adults is a common problem that can be caused by a variety of issues, including bursitis, arthritis, and tendinitis. It can be sharp or dull, and can range from mild to severe. It can be localized to the hip or radiate to other areas of the body. It can be accompanied by stiffness and swelling.

Irritable hip is a type of hip pain commonly seen in children. It is caused by inflammation of the hip joint and can cause pain in the groin, hip or thigh area. Symptoms may include difficulty walking, limping, decreased hip movement, and pain when the hip is moved.

surgery is a surgical procedure in which a damaged hip joint is replaced with an artificial implant.

Hip replacement surgery is a surgical procedure used to treat a damaged hip joint. The damaged joint is replaced with an artificial implant, usually made of metal or plastic, to restore movement and relieve pain.

is a condition that affects the large intestine (colon).

Hirschsprung's disease is a gastrointestinal disorder that affects the large intestine (colon). It is characterized by an absence of nerve cells in the muscles of the colon, resulting in an inability to pass stools normally. Symptoms include abdominal pain, constipation, vomiting, and failure to pass meconium in newborns.

Hirsutism is a condition characterized by excessive hair growth, particularly in areas such as the face, chest, and back. It is caused by an excess of male hormones, such as testosterone, and can occur in both men and women. Symptoms include increased hair growth, darkening of the hair, and thickening of the hair. It can also cause acne, irregular menstrual cycles, and infertility.

HIV is a virus that weakens the immune system, making it difficult for the body to fight off infections and diseases. AIDS is the most advanced stage of HIV infection, when the body can no longer fight off infections. Symptoms of HIV and AIDS can vary, but can include fever, fatigue, swollen lymph nodes, and a rash.

are red, itchy, raised bumps that appear on the skin.

Hives are raised, itchy bumps on the skin that are red in color. They can cause discomfort and can be itchy.

is a mental health disorder characterized by excessive hoarding of possessions, with symptoms such as difficulty discarding items, strong attachment to possessions, and an inability to organize items.

Hoarding disorder is an excessive need to hoard possessions, which can lead to difficulty discarding items, an emotional attachment to these items, and difficulty organizing them. It can cause significant distress and impair the individual's ability to function.

is the most common type of cancer in the lymphatic system.

Hodgkin lymphoma is a type of cancer that affects the lymphatic system. Symptoms may include enlargement of the lymph nodes, fever, night sweats, and weight loss. Additional symptoms may include fatigue, itching, and an enlarged spleen or liver.

is used to treat people with COPD

Home oxygen therapy is used to treat people with COPD who have low oxygen levels in their blood. Symptoms of low oxygen levels include shortness of breath, fatigue, confusion, and difficulty sleeping. Home oxygen therapy helps to relieve these symptoms by providing a constant supply of oxygen to the patient.

is a form of alternative medicine that involves taking highly diluted substances that are thought to cause symptoms similar to those of the disease.

Homeopathy is an alternative form of medicine that involves taking highly diluted substances to cause symptoms similar to the ones of the disease. The symptoms are believed to help the body fight and heal the disease.

is a rare inherited metabolic disorder that affects the body's ability to process certain proteins.

Homocystinuria is a rare inherited metabolic disorder that causes the body to be unable to process certain proteins. Symptoms of this disorder include intellectual disability, developmental delay, skeletal abnormalities, vision problems, and seizures.

Hookworm is a type of parasitic worm that can cause infection in humans. Symptoms of a hookworm infection can include a rash, itching, abdominal pain, diarrhea, and fatigue. In severe cases, anemia and protein deficiency can occur.

are usually felt on both sides of the head and are characterized by a throbbing pain.

Hormone headaches are a type of headache that is characterized by a throbbing pain felt on both sides of the head. They are often associated with hormonal changes in the body.

is a treatment used to relieve symptoms of menopause.

Hormone replacement therapy (HRT) is a treatment used to alleviate the symptoms associated with menopause, such as hot flashes, night sweats, vaginal dryness, and mood swings. It can also help reduce the risk of osteoporosis and heart disease.

Hormone replacement therapy (HRT) is a treatment for menopause and other conditions that involve hormone imbalances. It involves taking hormones such as estrogen, progesterone, and testosterone to help relieve symptoms such as hot flashes, night sweats, mood swings, and vaginal dryness. It also helps reduce the risk of osteoporosis and heart disease.

Hughes Syndrome, also known as Antiphospholipid Syndrome (APS), is an autoimmune condition that can cause a variety of symptoms. These symptoms can include blood clots, miscarriages, stroke, and heart attack. Other symptoms can include headaches, fatigue, dizziness, and skin rashes. Treatment typically involves anticoagulant medications and lifestyle modifications.

diagnosis: Human bites, see Animal and human bites
symptoms: Human bites are injuries caused by the teeth of another human. They can range from minor scratches to more serious injuries that require medical attention. The risk of infection is high for human bites, especially if the wound is deep or not cleaned and treated properly.

is a virus that can infect the skin and lining of the cervix.

Human Papillomavirus (HPV) is a virus that can cause infection of the skin and lining of the cervix. Symptoms can include warts on the skin or around the genital area, abnormal vaginal discharge, and abnormal bleeding. In some cases, HPV can lead to cervical cancer.

is an inherited disorder that causes the progressive breakdown (degeneration) of nerve cells in the brain.

Huntington's disease is an inherited condition that affects the brain, causing degeneration of nerve cells. This can lead to physical, mental and behavioural symptoms, including movement problems, cognitive difficulties and changes in mood.

is a condition in which too much cerebrospinal fluid accumulates in the brain.

Hydrocephalus is a medical condition in which there is an abnormal accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid in the brain, leading to an increase in the size of the ventricles and putting pressure on the brain. Symptoms of hydrocephalus include headaches, vomiting, poor coordination, vision problems, and difficulty with thinking and learning.

is a condition where the kidneys become swollen due to a build-up of urine.

Hydronephrosis is a condition where the kidneys become swollen due to a blockage that prevents the normal flow of urine. Symptoms may include pain in the back or side, nausea, vomiting, and fever. In some cases, patients may experience decreased urine output, swelling of the abdomen, and bloody urine.

Hyperacusis is a condition in which a person experiences an increased sensitivity to normal environmental sounds. Symptoms include an intolerance of everyday sounds such as the sound of a vacuum cleaner, loud conversations, or a telephone ringing. People with hyperacusis may also experience pain or discomfort in response to normally tolerable sounds.

Hyperhidrosis is a condition characterized by excessive sweating, even when the body is at rest. Symptoms include increased sweating of the palms, soles of the feet, underarms, and face. In more severe cases, the entire body may be affected. Additionally, the sweating may occur at night or during exercise.

is a disorder in which the body produces too much of the parathyroid hormone

Hyperparathyroidism is a disorder that causes the body to produce an excessive amount of the parathyroid hormone. Symptoms of this condition include increased thirst, frequent urination, fatigue, weakness, confusion, and abdominal pain. Other symptoms can include depression, constipation, muscle weakness, and bone pain.

is a condition in which a person has trouble staying awake during the day.

Hypersomnia is a condition in which a person has an excessive need for sleep and difficulty staying awake during the day. Symptoms include excessive sleepiness during the day, difficulty waking up in the morning, and feeling unrefreshed after sleep.

Hypertension is a condition in which the force of the blood against the artery walls is too high. Symptoms may include headaches, nosebleeds, dizziness, and chest pain. It is a serious medical condition that can lead to stroke and heart attack. Regular monitoring and treatment are needed to keep blood pressure in a healthy range.

Hyperthyroidism is a medical condition caused by an overactive thyroid gland. Symptoms can include weight loss, increased heart rate, heat intolerance, anxiety, and frequent bowel movements. Other symptoms include fatigue, muscle weakness, tremors, and changes in menstrual cycles. In addition, patients may experience goiter, a noticeable enlargement of the thyroid gland.

is a form of psychotherapy that uses deep relaxation and focused attention to achieve a heightened state of awareness.

Hypnotherapy is a form of psychotherapy that induces a state of deep relaxation and focused attention in order to help individuals gain insight into their thoughts, feelings, and behaviors. It is used to help individuals with a variety of issues, such as anxiety, depression, and addiction.

diagnosis: Hypoglycaemia (low blood sugar), see Low blood sugar (hypoglycaemia)
symptoms: Hypoglycaemia is a condition where blood sugar levels drop below the normal range. Symptoms of hypoglycaemia can include feeling shaky, weak, confused, sweating, dizziness, hunger, and blurred vision.

is a rare disorder that occurs when the body produces insufficient amounts of parathyroid hormone.

Hypoparathyroidism is a disorder characterized by an insufficient production of parathyroid hormone, which can lead to a variety of symptoms such as muscle cramping, tingling in the hands and feet, fatigue, and seizures. It can also cause calcium levels in the blood to become abnormally low.

Hypotension is a medical condition characterized by abnormally low blood pressure, which can cause symptoms such as dizziness, fatigue, lightheadedness, and fainting. It can be caused by a variety of medical conditions, such as dehydration, shock, or heart problems. It can also be a side effect of certain medications.

Hypothermia is a condition in which an individual's body temperature drops below 95°F (35°C). Symptoms of hypothermia include shivering, confusion, exhaustion, slurred speech, and difficulty moving. In severe cases, a person may become unconscious and their breathing may become shallow.

Hypothyroidism is a condition in which the thyroid gland does not produce enough of the hormones that regulate metabolism. Symptoms can include fatigue, weight gain, constipation, dry skin, depression, and a slowed heart rate.

is a surgical procedure to remove a woman’s uterus.

A hysterectomy is a procedure to remove a woman's uterus and can be used to treat a variety of symptoms, such as pelvic pain, heavy menstrual bleeding, and endometriosis. It may also be recommended to treat uterine prolapse, fibroids, or cancer.

is a procedure used to diagnose and treat problems of the uterus.

Hysteroscopy is a procedure used to view the inside of the uterus and diagnose and treat problems of the uterus. It involves inserting a thin, lighted tube through the vagina and cervix into the uterus. Symptoms that may lead to a hysteroscopy include abnormal bleeding, pelvic pain, infertility, and recurrent miscarriages.

is a common, long-term condition of the digestive system. It can cause stomach pain, bloating, diarrhoea and constipation.

Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS) is a long-term digestive disorder characterized by stomach pain, bloating, diarrhoea, and constipation. It is a common condition that affects the digestive system.

is a family of genetic skin disorders

Ichthyosis is a family of genetic skin disorders characterized by dry, thickened, scaly skin. It can range from mild to severe and affect different parts of the body. Symptoms may include itching, redness, cracking, and peeling of the skin. In severe cases, the skin can become so thick that it looks like fish scales.

(IPF) is a lung disease that causes scarring of lung tissue.

Idiopathic Pulmonary Fibrosis (IPF) is a lung disease that causes scarring of the tissue in the lungs, which can lead to difficulty breathing, coughing, fatigue, and weight loss.

patients may experience nausea, vomiting, and abdominal pain.

Ileostomy patients may experience nausea, vomiting, and abdominal pain as symptoms of their condition. These symptoms may be caused by a number of factors, including changes in diet, stress, or infection.

is a bacterial skin infection that causes sores and blisters.

Impetigo is a bacterial skin infection characterized by the formation of sores and blisters. It is usually itchy and may cause redness and swelling around the affected area. It is highly contagious and can spread quickly from person to person.

Impotence is a medical condition in which a man is unable to achieve or maintain an erection sufficient for satisfactory sexual activity. This can be due to a variety of physical and psychological causes. Symptoms may include difficulty achieving or maintaining an erection, decreased libido, decreased sexual pleasure, and anxiety about performance.

Urinary incontinence is a condition in which an individual has difficulty controlling their bladder, resulting in the unintentional release of urine. Symptoms of urinary incontinence include urine leakage, frequent urination, and a strong urge to urinate.

is a discomfort or burning feeling in the chest or stomach.

Indigestion is a condition that causes a discomfort or burning feeling in the chest or stomach. Symptoms can include nausea, bloating, stomach pain, and belching.

The symptoms of an infected piercing include redness, swelling, and tenderness around the area, a yellow or green discharge from the piercing, and possible fever and fatigue. The area may also be warm to the touch and itchy.

is defined as the inability to conceive after 12 months of regular, unprotected sexual intercourse

Infertility is the inability to become pregnant after one year of having regular, unprotected sexual intercourse. This condition can cause emotional distress for those trying to conceive and may require medical assistance for successful conception.

(IBD) is a group of chronic disorders that cause inflammation or ulceration in the small and large intestines.

Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD) is a group of chronic disorders characterized by inflammation and/or ulceration of the small and large intestines. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, cramping, diarrhea, rectal bleeding, and weight loss.

Influenza, commonly known as the Flu, is a contagious respiratory illness caused by viruses. Symptoms include fever, chills, muscle aches, headaches, runny nose, sore throat, and coughing. It can also cause severe illnesses, such as pneumonia, and can even lead to death.

can cause red bumps, swollen skin, and pain.

Ingrown hairs can cause red bumps, swelling, and pain in the affected area. The bumps may be itchy and can become infected if not treated. In severe cases, the skin may become tender and painful.

is a common condition that occurs when the corner or side of a toenail grows into the soft flesh of the toe.

Ingrown toenails occur when the corner or side of a toenail grows into the soft flesh of the toe, causing pain, redness, and swelling. It can also lead to infection in the area.

An inguinal hernia repair is a surgical procedure to fix a hernia in the inguinal area, which is the area in the groin. Symptoms of an inguinal hernia include a bulge or lump in the groin, pain or discomfort in the groin area, and a burning or aching sensation in the groin.

Insect bites and stings are a common cause of skin irritation and pain. Symptoms include redness and swelling at the site of the bite, itching, burning, and in some cases, severe allergic reactions. In some cases, the bite may become infected, leading to further symptoms such as pus-filled blisters, fever, and chills.

is a sleep disorder characterized by difficulty falling asleep, difficulty staying asleep, waking up too early, or feeling tired after waking up.

Insomnia is a sleep disorder that causes difficulty falling asleep, staying asleep, waking up too early, and feeling tired after waking up. It can lead to fatigue, low mood, and difficulty concentrating.

patients with COVID-19 have a range of symptoms including fever, cough, shortness of breath, fatigue, body aches, and headache.

COVID-19 patients in intensive care display a variety of symptoms including fever, cough, difficulty breathing, exhaustion, body pains, and headache.

diagnosis: Intersex, see Differences in sex development
symptoms: Intersex is a term used to describe individuals who have characteristics of both male and female sexes. It can be present at birth with physical characteristics such as genitalia, chromosomes, and reproductive organs that do not fit typical definitions of male or female. It can also be discovered later in life due to the presence of hormonal imbalances or other medical conditions.

diagnosis: Interstitial cystitis, see Bladder pain syndrome (interstitial cystitis)
symptoms: Interstitial cystitis, also known as Bladder Pain Syndrome, is a chronic bladder condition that causes pain and pressure in the bladder and surrounding pelvic area. Symptoms may include frequent urination, an urgent need to urinate, pain in the bladder, and pain in the pelvic area.

is a condition in which the pressure in the skull is higher than normal.

Intracranial hypertension is a condition where pressure in the skull is higher than normal, causing symptoms such as headaches, nausea, vomiting, vision changes, and ringing in the ears. In severe cases, it can lead to neurological damage, coma, or death.

is a fertility treatment that involves placing sperm inside a woman’s uterus to facilitate fertilization.

Intrauterine insemination (IUI) is a fertility treatment that involves placing sperm directly into a woman's uterus to increase the chances of fertilization. It is used when a woman has difficulty becoming pregnant due to a variety of reasons, such as blocked fallopian tubes, low sperm count, or unexplained infertility.

Iron deficiency anaemia is a common disorder caused by lack of iron in the body. Symptoms may include fatigue, pale skin, palpitations, shortness of breath, dizziness, and poor appetite. It can also lead to brittle nails, headaches, cravings for non-nutritive substances, and an enlarged spleen.

Iron deficiency anaemia is a disorder caused by lack of iron in the body. Symptoms include fatigue, pale skin, palpitations, shortness of breath, dizziness, poor appetite, brittle nails, headaches, cravings for non-nutritive substances, and an enlarged spleen.

, heavy bleeding, cramping

The patient is experiencing irregular periods, heavy bleeding, and cramping. These symptoms could indicate a variety of medical issues, including hormonal imbalances or gynecological problems.

is a common disorder that affects the large intestine.

IBS is a common disorder that affects the large intestine, causing symptoms such as abdominal pain, cramping, bloating, constipation, and diarrhea. It can also cause fatigue, feelings of being bloated, and a feeling of incomplete evacuation after passing stool.

diagnosis: Irritable hip, see Hip pain in children (irritable hip)
symptoms: Irritable hip, also known as Hip pain in children, is a condition that affects young children and is characterized by pain in the hip area, difficulty walking, and limping. It is usually caused by an infection or a trauma and is usually self-limiting, resolving on its own within a few weeks.

is an inherited disorder that affects the metabolism of leucine, an amino acid found in many proteins.

Isovaleric acidaemia is an inherited disorder that affects the body's ability to process leucine, an amino acid found in proteins. Symptoms can include a distinctive body odor, vomiting, low muscle tone, and developmental delays.

, sore throat and headache

The symptoms described are itchy bottom, sore throat and headache. These could be indicative of a variety of illnesses and should be evaluated by a medical professional.

, redness, and swelling

The symptoms described are indicative of an allergic reaction. The person is likely experiencing itchy skin, redness, and swelling in the affected area.

is a medical procedure

In Vitro Fertilization (IVF) is a medical procedure in which eggs are removed from a woman's ovaries, fertilized with sperm in a laboratory, and then transferred back into the uterus. The procedure is used to treat infertility and other reproductive issues, such as genetic problems or blocked fallopian tubes. It can also be used to achieve pregnancy in same-sex couples.

is a mosquito-borne viral infection

Japanese encephalitis is a viral infection that is spread through the bite of infected mosquitoes. Symptoms of the infection include fever, headache, confusion, seizures, and paralysis. In severe cases, it can cause death.

is a yellowish discoloration of the skin, mucous membranes, and the whites of the eyes due to an accumulation of bile pigment (bilirubin) in body tissues.

Jaundice is a symptom characterized by yellowish discoloration of the skin, eyes, and mucous membranes. It is caused by an accumulation of bile pigment (bilirubin) in the body.

diagnosis: Jaundice in newborns, see Newborn jaundice
symptoms: Newborn jaundice is a common condition where a baby's skin and eyes become yellow, usually in the first few days after birth. It is caused by a build-up of a yellow pigment called bilirubin in the baby's blood. This can cause the baby to be lethargic, have difficulty breastfeeding, and may require treatment.

The patient is experiencing jaw pain, which is a symptom of Temporomandibular disorder (TMD). TMD is a disorder that affects the jaw joint and muscles that control the jaw, leading to pain and difficulty in opening and closing the mouth.

diagnosis: Jellyfish and other sea creature stings
symptoms: Jellyfish and other sea creature stings can cause a variety of symptoms, such as pain, itching, redness, swelling, and heat around the affected area. In more severe cases, symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, headaches, fever, and even anaphylaxis.

is a physiological condition which results from changes to the body's circadian rhythms

Jet lag is a condition that occurs when a person's internal body clock does not align with the time in their new environment. It can cause fatigue, headaches, difficulty concentrating, and difficulty sleeping.

is a condition that affects the joints,

Joint Hypermobility Syndrome is a condition that affects the joints, causing them to be overly flexible and move beyond the normal range of motion. This can lead to joint instability, pain, and fatigue. Additionally, people with this condition may have skin problems, digestive issues, and problems with the autonomic nervous system.

, fatigue, and fever

The patient is experiencing joint pain, fatigue, and a fever, indicating an infection or inflammatory process.

Kaposi's sarcoma is a type of cancer that manifests as lesions on the skin, often in a purple or dark red color. It can also occur in other organs, but this is less common. Symptoms may include fatigue, fever, night sweats, and swollen lymph nodes. It can also cause pain and difficulty breathing.

is a rare illness that affects the blood vessels and lymph nodes.

Kawasaki disease is a rare illness that causes inflammation in the blood vessels and lymph nodes. Symptoms of the disease may include fever, rash, swollen lymph nodes, red eyes, and red, cracked lips. In severe cases, the disease may also cause inflammation of the heart and coronary arteries.

are characterized by raised, reddish and itchy skin.

Keloid scars are raised, reddish and itchy areas of skin that can be painful to the touch. They are usually larger than the original wound and can spread beyond the area of the original injury. They can also be itchy and tender.

is a common skin condition that causes small, hard bumps that may make your skin feel like sandpaper.

Keratosis pilaris is a skin condition that causes small, hard bumps to appear on the skin, making it feel rough like sandpaper. These bumps are typically skin-colored or slightly red and are most often found on the upper arms, thighs, buttocks, and cheeks.

can cause a variety of symptoms.

Kidney cancer can cause a range of symptoms, such as lower back pain, blood in the urine, fatigue, unexplained weight loss, and a lump in the side or abdomen. Symptoms may not appear until the cancer has advanced.

diagnosis: Kidney failure, see Chronic kidney disease
symptoms: The symptoms of Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) include fatigue, swelling in the legs, feet, and ankles, loss of appetite, difficulty sleeping, nausea, and changes in urination frequency and color. In more advanced stages of CKD, patients may experience confusion, shortness of breath, and chest pain.

A kidney infection is an infection of the urinary tract caused by bacteria. Symptoms may include pain in the lower back, fever, chills, nausea, and vomiting. Urination may be painful and frequent, and the urine may be cloudy or contain blood.

Kidney stones are hard deposits of minerals and acid salts that form in the kidneys. Symptoms of kidney stones include pain in the lower back or side, abdominal pain, blood in the urine, nausea and vomiting, and fever.

patients often develop a condition called "chronic allograft nephropathy" (CAN).

Chronic allograft nephropathy (CAN) is a condition that affects kidney transplant patients, causing symptoms such as proteinuria, glomerulosclerosis, and tubulointerstitial fibrosis. It can also cause progressive deterioration of renal function, leading to graft failure.

is a genetic disorder that affects males.

Klinefelter Syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects males and is characterized by an extra X chromosome. Symptoms may include tall stature, low testosterone levels, infertility, behavioral and learning difficulties, and breast enlargement.

diagnosis: Knee cartilage damage, see Meniscus tear (knee cartilage damage)
symptoms: The symptoms of knee cartilage damage (meniscus tear) include pain, swelling, stiffness, and difficulty straightening the knee. It may also cause a clicking, popping, or catching sensation in the knee joint.

is a procedure to repair a torn anterior cruciate ligament (ACL).

Knee ligament surgery is a procedure used to repair a torn anterior cruciate ligament (ACL). Symptoms of a torn ACL may include pain, swelling, instability, and difficulty putting weight on the leg.

is a common complaint that affects people of all ages.

Knee pain is a frequent problem that can occur in people of any age. Symptoms may include soreness, stiffness, swelling, and difficulty moving the joint. In some cases, the pain may also be accompanied by a popping or grinding sensation when the knee is moved.

surgery is often necessary to treat severe knee pain or disability caused by arthritis, injury or other conditions.

Knee replacement surgery is a procedure used to treat severe knee pain or disability caused by arthritis, injury, or other conditions. It is often necessary when all other treatments have been unsuccessful in alleviating the pain or disability.

is a common condition in which a person’s knees touch each other when they are standing with their feet together.

Knock knees is a condition in which a person's knees touch each other when standing with their feet together. It is most common in children and can cause pain, discomfort, and difficulty walking. It can also cause the legs to appear bowed or curved.

The individual has suffered a knocked-out tooth, which is a dental injury in which a tooth is completely displaced from its socket in the bone. It can cause pain, swelling, and bleeding in the mouth, as well as difficulty speaking, eating, and drinking.

is a condition in which there is an excessive outward curvature of the spine

Kyphosis is a condition characterized by an excessive outward curvature of the spine, resulting in a hunched or rounded back. Symptoms of Kyphosis can include back pain, a rounded posture, decreased flexibility in the spine, and difficulty breathing.

occurs when the two labia minora, or inner labia, grow together

Labial fusion is a medical condition in which the two labia minora, or inner labia, grow together and fuse, causing the labia to appear as one large piece of tissue. Symptoms of labial fusion include difficulty urinating, pain during sexual intercourse, and an abnormal appearance of the labia.

Labyrinthitis and vestibular neuritis are inner ear infections that can cause symptoms such as vertigo, dizziness, nausea, loss of balance, and hearing loss. These symptoms can be accompanied by ringing in the ears, headaches, and difficulty concentrating.

measures an enzyme found in blood and other body tissues.

The LDH test measures the level of an enzyme found in blood and other body tissues. High levels of this enzyme may indicate tissue damage caused by conditions such as heart attack, stroke, or liver disease. Low levels of this enzyme may indicate an underlying condition such as anemia or malnutrition.

is a condition in which a person has digestive symptoms after consuming dairy products.

Lactose intolerance is a digestive disorder that causes individuals to experience symptoms such as nausea, bloating, gas, abdominal pain and diarrhea after consuming dairy products. These symptoms often occur within 30 minutes to two hours after eating dairy.

(LEMS) is an autoimmune disorder that affects the neuromuscular junction.

Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome (LEMS) is an autoimmune disorder that affects the neuromuscular junction, causing muscle weakness, decreased reflexes, fatigue, and difficulty walking. Other symptoms may include difficulty swallowing, dry mouth, and difficulty speaking.

Laparoscopy is a medical procedure in which a thin, lighted tube is inserted into the abdomen through a small incision. This allows the doctor to view the internal organs and assess any issues. Symptoms that may indicate a need for a laparoscopy include abdominal pain, bloating, nausea, and vomiting. Additionally, a doctor may recommend a laparoscopy if they suspect endometriosis, a blocked fallopian tube, or an ovarian cyst.

Laparoscopy is a medical procedure in which a thin, lighted tube is inserted into the abdomen through a small incision. Symptoms that may indicate a need for a laparoscopy include abdominal pain, bloating, nausea, and vomiting. A doctor may also recommend a laparoscopy if they suspect endometriosis, a blocked fallopian tube, or an ovarian cyst.

is a rare type of cancer that affects the larynx, which is the area of the throat responsible for producing sound and helping you swallow.

Symptoms of laryngeal cancer include a hoarse or raspy voice, difficulty breathing or swallowing, a sore throat that does not go away, a lump in the neck, and ear pain.

is an inflammation of the larynx, the voice box located in the throat.

Laryngitis is an inflammation of the larynx, which is the voice box located in the throat. Symptoms may include hoarseness, loss of voice, and a sore throat.

diagnosis: Laser eye surgery and lens surgery
symptoms: Laser eye surgery and lens surgery are two types of eye surgeries that are used to correct vision problems. Laser eye surgery uses a laser to reshape the cornea, while lens surgery involves replacing the natural lens with an artificial one. Both procedures can help to improve vision, reduce the need for glasses or contact lenses, and reduce the risk of some eye diseases.

can cause symptoms such as nausea, abdominal pain, and cramps.

Laxatives can cause unpleasant gastrointestinal symptoms, including nausea, abdominal pain, and cramps.

is a condition in which one eye turns inward or outward, and the affected eye has reduced vision.

Lazy eye is a condition where one eye is misaligned and has reduced vision. The misalignment can be inward or outward.

can vary in type and severity.

Learning disabilities can affect how a person receives, processes, stores and responds to information. Symptoms can include difficulty with reading, writing, math, organization, concentration and social skills.

The individual is experiencing painful leg cramps, which are described as intense and sudden contractions in the muscles of the leg. These cramps typically occur in the calf muscles and can last anywhere from a few seconds to several minutes.

diagnosis: Leg ulcer, see Venous leg ulcer
symptoms: A venous leg ulcer is an open sore on the leg caused by poor circulation. It is typically found on the lower part of the leg and can be caused by vein damage from conditions such as deep vein thrombosis. Symptoms of a venous leg ulcer include pain, swelling, and discoloration of the skin. The area may also be itchy and may ooze fluid. In some cases, the wound may become infected.

is a serious lung infection

Legionnaires' disease is a type of pneumonia caused by the Legionella bacteria. It is a serious lung infection that causes symptoms such as coughing, shortness of breath, high fever, muscle aches, and headaches. It can also cause diarrhea, confusion, and fatigue.

is an infectious bacterial disease that affects humans and animals.

Leptospirosis (Weil's disease) is an infectious bacterial disease that affects both humans and animals. Symptoms in humans include fever, headache, chills, muscle pain, jaundice, red eyes, abdominal pain, diarrhea, and rash. In severe cases, it can lead to kidney damage, meningitis, liver failure, and even death.

diagnosis: Leukaemia (acute lymphoblastic), see Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia
symptoms: Leukaemia (acute lymphoblastic), also known as acute lymphocytic leukaemia, is a type of cancer that affects the white blood cells. It is characterized by an overproduction of immature white blood cells in the bone marrow, which can lead to anemia, infections, and other complications. Symptoms include fatigue, weakness, paleness, frequent infections, and swollen lymph nodes.

diagnosis: Leukaemia (acute myeloid), see Acute myeloid leukaemia
symptoms: Acute myeloid leukaemia (AML) is a type of cancer that affects the blood and bone marrow. It is characterized by an abnormal overproduction of immature white blood cells called myeloblasts. Symptoms of AML may include fatigue, fever, weight loss, easy bruising and bleeding, frequent infections, and joint and bone pain.

diagnosis: Leukaemia (chronic lymphocytic), see Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia
symptoms: Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia is a type of cancer that affects the white blood cells. Symptoms include fatigue, swollen lymph nodes, night sweats, an enlarged spleen, and frequent infections. Other symptoms may include weight loss, bone pain, and shortness of breath.

diagnosis: Leukaemia (chronic myeloid), see Chronic myeloid leukaemia
symptoms: Chronic myeloid leukaemia (CML) is a type of cancer that affects the white blood cells. Symptoms of CML can include fatigue, weakness, night sweats, weight loss, bone pain, enlarged spleen, and an increased risk of infection.

diagnosis: Leukaemia (hairy cell), see Hairy cell leukaemia
symptoms: Leukaemia (hairy cell) is a rare type of cancer of the blood and bone marrow that causes an overproduction of a certain type of white blood cell. It is characterized by an accumulation of abnormal B cells, which are referred to as "hairy cells" due to the appearance of their cytoplasm. Symptoms include fatigue, weakness, weight loss, abdominal pain, enlarged spleen, and anemia.

is a white patch or plaque found in the mouth

Leukoplakia is a condition characterized by white patches or plaques in the mouth that cannot be scraped off. The patches can be found on the inner cheeks, gums, tongue, and roof of the mouth, and are usually painless. They may also be rough or slightly raised.

is an itchy rash that can affect many areas of the skin, including the wrists, ankles, lower back, and genitals.

Lichen planus is a skin condition that causes an itchy rash on the wrists, ankles, lower back, and genitals. The rash can be red or purple in color, and is often accompanied by a burning or stinging sensation.

is a skin condition that usually appears as whitish patches on the skin.

Lichen sclerosus is a skin condition that causes whitish patches to appear on the skin. These patches are often itchy and may cause discomfort. In some cases, they can also cause scarring and thinning of the skin.

Limping in children can be a symptom of a musculoskeletal injury or illness. It can be caused by trauma such as a sprain, strain, fracture, or dislocation, or by a medical condition such as arthritis, infection, or a bone tumor. It can also be caused by an underlying neurological condition. In some cases, the cause of limping may not be known.

is a chronic and often progressive condition of the lower limbs

Lipoedema is a chronic condition of the lower limbs characterized by an abnormal fat distribution and swelling. Symptoms include disproportionate enlargement of the legs and hips, dimpled skin, and tenderness in the area. It can cause pain and mobility issues, and can worsen over time if not addressed.

is a benign fatty tumor

Lipoma is a benign tumor composed of fat cells that can occur in almost any part of the body. Symptoms of a lipoma include a soft, rubbery or doughy lump under the skin that is usually painless and moves easily when touched. The lump is typically small and can range in size from a few millimeters to several centimeters.

diagnosis: Lips (sore or dry), see Sore or dry lips
symptoms: Sore or dry lips are a common symptom, characterized by the lips feeling chapped, cracked, or irritated. It may also be accompanied by inflammation, redness, and itching.

is an infection caused by the bacteria Listeria monocytogenes

Listeriosis is a serious infection caused by the bacteria Listeria monocytogenes. Symptoms can range from mild to severe, including fever, muscle aches, nausea, and diarrhea. In more severe cases, the infection can cause confusion, headaches, stiff neck, and convulsions.

can cause jaundice, fatigue, abdominal pain, loss of appetite, nausea, and weight loss.

The symptoms of liver cancer include jaundice, fatigue, abdominal pain, loss of appetite, nausea, and weight loss. These symptoms can be caused by the cancer itself or by the body's response to it.

is a condition that causes the liver to become damaged, which can lead to a loss of liver function.

Liver disease is a condition that causes the liver to become damaged, resulting in a decreased ability to function properly. Symptoms may include jaundice, abdominal pain, fatigue, weakness, and loss of appetite.

diagnosis: Liver disease (alcohol-related), see Alcohol-related liver disease
symptoms:
Alcohol-related liver disease is a condition caused by excessive alcohol consumption and can lead to a variety of symptoms, including jaundice, fatigue, abdominal pain, loss of appetite, and weight loss. It can also cause complications such as cirrhosis, which can be life-threatening.

Alcohol-related liver disease is caused by excessive alcohol consumption and can cause jaundice, fatigue, abdominal pain, loss of appetite, weight loss and potentially life-threatening complications such as cirrhosis.

ation is a major operation that is used to replace a damaged or diseased liver with a healthy one.

The symptoms of needing a liver transplant include severe liver damage or disease, yellowing of the skin and eyes, abdominal pain and swelling, itching, fatigue, and jaundice.

is a type of anaesthesia that numbs a specific area of the body

Local anaesthesia numbs a specific area of the body, reducing sensation in that area and blocking pain signals from that area to the brain. It is typically used for minor procedures and surgeries, such as dental work and minor skin repairs.

is a disorder of the heart's electrical activity that can potentially cause fast, chaotic heartbeats

Long QT Syndrome is a serious heart condition that causes irregular heartbeats, which can be fast and chaotic. This can lead to fainting, seizures, and even sudden death. It is caused by a problem with the heart's electrical system.

is a condition that affects the way you see things.

Long-sightedness is a condition that affects vision by making distant objects appear clearer than items that are close up. Symptoms of long-sightedness include difficulty focusing on objects that are close, headaches or eyestrain, and squinting to see objects clearly.

diagnosis: Lost or changed sense of smell
symptoms: The patient has experienced a sudden and complete loss of their sense of smell, or noticed a change in the way things smell. This occurs without any other symptoms such as a runny nose or congestion.

Low blood pressure (hypotension) is a condition in which the blood pressure is lower than normal. Symptoms of hypotension can include dizziness, lightheadedness, fainting, blurred vision, fatigue, and nausea. In severe cases, hypotension can cause difficulty breathing, confusion, and chest pain.

Low blood sugar (hypoglycaemia) is a condition that occurs when the body has an abnormally low level of blood sugar. Symptoms of hypoglycemia include dizziness, shakiness, confusion, sweating, hunger, and a rapid heart rate. It can also lead to fatigue, blurred vision, headaches, and difficulty concentrating.

Low sex drive (loss of libido) is a decrease in sexual desire or interest. It can be caused by physical or psychological factors, such as hormonal changes, depression, or relationship issues. Symptoms may include reduced interest in sexual activity, reduced sexual fantasies, and a decrease in sexual arousal.

can cause infertility.

Low sperm count is a condition in which the number of sperm in a man's semen is lower than normal. This can lead to infertility, as fewer sperm are available to fertilize an egg. Symptoms may include difficulty achieving pregnancy and reduced sexual desire.
A low white blood cell count can cause symptoms such as fatigue, increased susceptibility to infection, and bruising or bleeding. People may also experience chills, fever, and night sweats.

diagnosis: Lower back pain, see Back pain
symptoms: The individual experiences lower back pain in the lower back region. This pain can range from mild to severe and can be accompanied by other symptoms such as muscle stiffness and difficulty in movement.

Lumbago is a type of back pain that is usually caused by muscle strain or sprain in the lower back. It can cause pain in the lower back, buttocks, and legs that can range from mild to severe. Symptoms may include soreness, stiffness, and difficulty with movement.

is a surgical procedure that relieves pressure on the spinal cord by removing portions of the vertebrae and discs.

Lumbar decompression surgery is a procedure used to relieve pressure on the spinal cord. It involves the removal of parts of the vertebrae and discs to create more space for the spinal cord. This can help reduce pain and other symptoms caused by nerve compression.

revealed a clear fluid with slightly elevated protein and normal glucose.

The patient had a lumbar puncture which showed a clear fluid with slightly higher than normal protein levels, but a normal glucose level.

in the neck, fever, fatigue

The individual is having lumps in their neck, a fever, and feeling fatigued. These are common symptoms of an infection or illness.

is a disease characterized by uncontrolled cell growth in the tissue of the lungs.

Lung cancer is a type of cancer that affects the lungs, causing uncontrolled cell growth in the lung tissue. Symptoms can include shortness of breath, a persistent cough, coughing up blood, chest pain, and weight loss.

are important

Lung health checks are important in order to detect any potential issues with the lungs. Symptoms to look out for include shortness of breath, chest pain, coughing up blood, and wheezing. Early detection of any lung issues could lead to better outcomes for treatment.

is a surgery to replace a diseased lung with a healthy lung from a donor

Lung transplant is a surgery to replace a diseased lung with a healthy lung from a donor. Symptoms of lung disease that may lead to a lung transplant include difficulty breathing, chest pain, wheezing, fatigue, and coughing up blood. Individuals may also experience frequent lung infections, fluid buildup in the lungs, and decreased oxygen levels in the blood.

is a chronic autoimmune disease

Lupus is a chronic autoimmune disease that causes the body's immune system to attack its own healthy tissue and organs. Symptoms can range from mild to severe and can affect different parts of the body, including the skin, joints, and organs. Common symptoms include fatigue, joint pain and swelling, skin rashes, fever, and hair loss.

is an infection caused by the bacterium Borrelia burgdorferi.

Lyme disease is an infectious disease caused by the bacterium Borrelia burgdorferi. Symptoms of the disease include fever, headache, fatigue, and a characteristic skin rash. Other symptoms may include joint pain, facial palsy, and Bell's palsy. In more severe cases, complications such as neurological and cardiac problems can occur.

is a swelling that occurs in the body due to a buildup of lymph fluid.

Lymphoedema is a condition that is characterized by swelling in different parts of the body caused by a buildup of lymph fluid. Symptoms of lymphoedema can include swelling in the hands, feet, arms, legs, abdomen, and face, as well as pain, heaviness, and tightness in the affected area.

diagnosis: Macular degeneration (age-related), see Age-related macular degeneration (AMD)
symptoms: Age-related macular degeneration (AMD) is a condition that affects the central part of the vision, known as the macula. Symptoms of AMD include blurred vision, difficulty recognizing faces, and difficulty reading or driving. In more severe cases, blind spots may occur in the central vision.

is a small break in the macula, located in the center of the eye's light-sensitive tissue called the retina

Macular hole is a condition in which there is a small break in the macula, which is the central part of the light-sensitive tissue of the eye known as the retina. Symptoms of macular hole include blurred vision, distortion of straight lines, and a central black spot. Additionally, some people may experience difficulty reading, difficulty recognizing faces, and reduced color vision.

A magnesium test is used to measure the amount of magnesium in the blood. Symptoms of magnesium deficiency may include fatigue, muscle weakness, cramps, nausea, and seizures.

A magnesium test is used to measure the amount of magnesium in the blood. Symptoms of magnesium deficiency include fatigue, muscle weakness, cramps, nausea, and seizures. Low levels of magnesium can lead to a range of health problems.

is a serious disease caused by a parasite that is spread to humans through mosquito bites

Malaria is a life-threatening disease caused by a parasite that is transmitted to humans through mosquito bites. Symptoms include fever and chills, headaches, muscle aches, nausea and vomiting, and fatigue. In severe cases, it can lead to anemia, seizures, coma, and even death.

is a term used to describe the gradual decline of testosterone levels in men as they age. Symptoms of this condition include a decrease in libido, fatigue, irritability, depression, and difficulty concentrating.

Male menopause is a term used to describe the gradual decline of testosterone levels in men as they age, which can result in symptoms such as a decrease in libido, fatigue, irritability, depression, and difficulty concentrating.

A malignant brain tumour (brain cancer) is a mass of abnormal cells that grows in or around the brain. Symptoms may include headaches, seizures, changes in personality, loss of balance, nausea, vomiting, and fatigue. Other symptoms can include vision problems, hearing loss, and difficulty speaking.

is a condition that occurs when the tendon that straightens the end joint of a finger or thumb is injured

Mallet finger is an injury to the tendon that straightens the end joint of the finger or thumb. Symptoms include pain and stiffness of the affected joint, inability to straighten the finger or thumb, and a visible deformity or drooping of the fingertip.

can occur when the body does not get enough nutrients from food.

Malnutrition occurs when the body is not receiving the necessary nutrients from food. Symptoms of malnutrition may include fatigue, weight loss, irritability, and weakened immune system.

A mammogram is a procedure used to screen for breast cancer. It involves taking an X-ray of each breast and can detect changes in breast tissue that may indicate cancer. Symptoms of breast cancer, such as lumps or changes in shape or size, may not be visible or felt during a physical examination, so a mammogram can help to identify these changes.

Maple syrup urine disease is a rare, inherited metabolic disorder that affects the breakdown of certain amino acids. Symptoms typically include a maple syrup-like odor in the urine, poor feeding, vomiting, lethargy, seizures, and developmental delay. It can be fatal if left untreated.

is a genetic disorder that affects the connective tissue.

Marfan syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects the connective tissue of the body, leading to abnormal growth of the bones, abnormal curvature of the spine, and problems with the heart and blood vessels. Symptoms may include long arms, legs, and fingers; a tall, thin body type; a curved spine; floppiness of the joints; and heart murmurs.

is a surgical procedure to remove all or part of the breast.

Mastectomy is a surgical procedure that involves the removal of all or part of the breast. The procedure is often done to treat or prevent breast cancer. It can also be done to reduce the risk of cancer in people who are at high risk for the disease. Symptoms of mastectomy include pain, swelling, and bleeding at the site of the surgery.

is an infection of the breast that causes swelling, redness, pain, warmth, and a thick discharge from the nipple

Mastitis is a breast infection that causes symptoms such as swelling, redness, pain, warmth, and a thick discharge from the nipple. It is most common in breastfeeding women, but can occur in any woman.

is a group of diseases that affect the mast cells in the body.

Mastocytosis is a group of diseases that involve an increase in the number of mast cells in the body. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, skin lesions, flushing, itching, and anaphylaxis. Other symptoms may include fatigue, weight loss, bone pain, and diarrhea.

is a bacterial infection of the mastoid bone, which is located behind the ear.

Mastoiditis is an infection of the mastoid bone behind the ear that is caused by bacteria. Symptoms can include tenderness and swelling behind the ear, pain and fever, and hearing loss.

MCADD (medium-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase deficiency) is a rare disorder of fatty acid metabolism. Symptoms can include low blood sugar, poor feeding, vomiting, weak muscle tone, and liver problems.

MCADD is a rare disorder of fatty acid metabolism that can cause low blood sugar, poor feeding, vomiting, weak muscle tone, and liver problems.

is a highly contagious viral infection that affects the respiratory system.

Measles is a viral infection that causes respiratory symptoms such as coughing, runny nose, and fever. It is highly contagious and can spread rapidly through close contact. Symptoms may also include sore throat, red eyes, and a rash.

can be used to treat a range of symptoms, including pain, nausea, and lack of appetite.

Medical cannabis and cannabis oils can be used to relieve pain, reduce nausea, and stimulate appetite. They are used to treat a variety of symptoms related to illness or injury.

can include fatigue, headache, dizziness, and poor concentration

Medically unexplained symptoms are physical symptoms that do not have an identifiable cause and can include fatigue, headache, dizziness, and poor concentration. These symptoms can be debilitating and can interfere with daily life activities.

The patient is experiencing a range of symptoms including dizziness, nausea, headaches, and blurred vision.

The patient is experiencing dizziness, nausea, headaches, and blurred vision.

is a type of cancer that begins in the cells that give skin its color.

Melanoma skin cancer is a type of cancer that begins in the cells that give skin its color. It is usually characterized by the presence of a dark, irregularly shaped mole on the skin. Other symptoms may include changes in an existing mole, the development of a new mole, and itching, bleeding, or crusting of the skin.

Amnesia is a condition which causes a person to experience memory loss. It can affect both short-term and long-term memory, and can range from mild to severe. It can be caused by physical trauma, psychological trauma, or a disease. Symptoms may include difficulty recalling recent events, difficulty forming new memories, confusion, disorientation and difficulty recognizing familiar people and places.

is a serious infection of the thin lining that surrounds the brain and spinal cord.

Meningitis is an infection of the thin lining that surrounds the brain and spinal cord, which can be serious. Symptoms of meningitis can include fever, headache, stiff neck, confusion, and sensitivity to light.

A meniscus tear is a type of knee injury that damages the cartilage in the knee joint. Symptoms of a meniscus tear include pain, swelling, and difficulty moving the knee joint. Other symptoms may include a popping sensation, a feeling of the knee giving out, and locking of the knee joint.

is the time when a woman's menstrual periods stop permanently.

Menopause is the time when a woman's menstrual periods permanently stop. Symptoms can include hot flashes, night sweats, sleep disturbances, vaginal dryness, and mood changes.

Early menopause is the occurrence of menopause before the age of 45. It is also known as premature menopause. Symptoms include irregular periods, hot flashes, night sweats, and mood swings. Other symptoms include vaginal dryness, difficulty sleeping, and weight gain.

Period pain is a common symptom experienced by many women during their menstrual cycle. It is usually felt as cramping or pain in the lower abdomen and can range from mild to severe. Other symptoms include headache, nausea, diarrhoea, and fatigue.

Period pain is a common symptom experienced by many women during their menstrual cycle, typically as cramping or pain in the lower abdomen. It can range from mild to severe and may also be accompanied by other symptoms such as headache, nausea, diarrhoea and fatigue.

is a rare cancer caused by exposure to asbestos.

Mesothelioma is a rare type of cancer caused by exposure to asbestos. Symptoms of mesothelioma can include chest pain, shortness of breath, and coughing. Other symptoms may include fatigue, weight loss, and fluid buildup in the chest or abdomen.

is a cluster of conditions that occur together, increasing your risk of heart disease, stroke, and type 2 diabetes.

Metabolic Syndrome is a group of conditions that increase the risk of heart disease, stroke, and type 2 diabetes. These conditions include high blood pressure, high blood sugar, excess body fat around the waist, and abnormal cholesterol levels.

in the mouth, headache and nausea

The person is experiencing a metallic taste in their mouth, a headache and nausea. These are classic symptoms of a possible infection or food-borne illness.

diagnosis: Metatarsalgia, see Pain in the ball of the foot
symptoms: Metatarsalgia is a condition that causes pain and inflammation in the ball of the foot. It is usually caused by overuse and strain on the foot. Symptoms include pain, tenderness, and swelling in the affected area, as well as burning and tingling sensations.

is a viral respiratory illness

MERS is a viral respiratory illness that is characterized by fever, cough, and shortness of breath. Other symptoms may include body aches, headache, chills, and gastrointestinal symptoms such as vomiting and diarrhea. It can also lead to severe complications such as pneumonia and kidney failure.

is a common type of headache that may occur with symptoms such as nausea, vomiting, and extreme sensitivity to light and sound.

Migraine is a type of headache that can cause severe symptoms such as nausea, vomiting, and extreme sensitivity to light and sound. It is a very common type of headache.

A miscarriage is the loss of a fetus before the 20th week of pregnancy. Common symptoms of a miscarriage include vaginal bleeding, cramping, and the passing of tissue or clots from the vagina. Other symptoms may include back pain, abdominal pain, and fluid or tissue passing from the vagina.

can cause a wide range of symptoms.

Mitral valve problems can cause symptoms such as shortness of breath, chest pain, palpitations, fatigue, and swelling in the legs. In some cases, people may also experience dizziness or fainting.

is a type of gestational trophoblastic disease that occurs when a fertilized egg does not develop into an embryo, but instead forms a mass in the uterus.

Molar pregnancy is a type of gestational trophoblastic disease in which a fertilized egg does not develop into an embryo, but instead forms a mass in the uterus. Symptoms of molar pregnancy can include abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, and nausea.

can appear anywhere on the body, including the scalp, armpits, and groin.

Moles can appear as dark spots on the skin, typically with a distinct edge, and can vary in size from a few millimeters to several centimeters. They can be flat or raised, and can be either smooth or rough in texture. They may also be pigmented or not.

is a skin infection caused by a virus.

Molluscum contagiosum is a contagious skin infection caused by a virus. It is characterized by small, raised, pearl-like bumps that may be flesh-colored, pink, or red. These bumps can appear anywhere on the body, but are most commonly found on the face, neck, armpits, and groin. They may be itchy or tender, and may spread from person to person through direct contact.

is a painful condition that affects the ball of the foot

Morton's neuroma is a common condition that causes a sharp, burning pain in the ball of the foot, usually between the third and fourth toes. It is caused by a thickening of the tissue around one of the nerves leading to the toes. Symptoms can include tingling, numbness, and a feeling of having a pebble in the shoe.

is a feeling of queasiness or nausea caused by movement

Motion sickness is a condition in which a person experiences nausea, dizziness, and disorientation due to movement, such as riding in a car, boat, or airplane. Symptoms can include sweating, pallor, headache, and vomiting.

is a debilitating condition that causes muscles to weaken and waste

Motor Neurone Disease is a progressive, degenerative condition that affects the nerve cells responsible for controlling muscle movement. Symptoms include muscle weakness, twitching, difficulty speaking, difficulty swallowing, and difficulty breathing. In advanced stages, the muscles become completely paralyzed and the patient may become completely dependent on a ventilator for breathing.

can cause a number of symptoms, including

Mouth cancer can cause several symptoms, such as a sore or ulcer in the mouth that won't heal, a lump or swelling in the mouth, pain or numbness in the mouth or lips, white or red patches inside the mouth, difficulty chewing or swallowing, and a change in the voice.

diagnosis: Mouth thrush, see Oral thrush (mouth thrush)
symptoms: Mouth thrush is an infection caused by an overgrowth of yeast in the mouth. Symptoms include white patches on the tongue, inner cheeks, and roof of the mouth, as well as redness, soreness, and difficulty swallowing. Treatment may include antifungal medications and lifestyle changes.

, also known as canker sores, are small sores that form in the mouth.

Mouth ulcers, also known as canker sores, are small painful sores that form inside the mouth. They can appear on the tongue, the inside of the cheeks or the lips. They may be white or yellow in color and can be painful or cause discomfort when eating or speaking.

is a contagious viral infection that causes fever, headache, fatigue, and rash.

Mpox is a contagious viral infection that can cause a range of symptoms, including fever, headache, fatigue, and a rash. It is spread through contact with an infected person or their bodily fluids.

showed a mass in the left frontal lobe

An MRI scan revealed a mass in the left frontal lobe of the brain. Symptoms include loss of motor control, difficulty speaking, confusion, and changes in behavior.

This MRI scan showed a mass in the left frontal lobe of the brain, causing symptoms such as loss of motor control, difficulty speaking, confusion, and changes in behavior.

Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) is a type of bacterial infection that is resistant to certain antibiotics. Symptoms of MRSA include redness, swelling, warmth, and pain in the infected area, as well as fever and chills. In some cases, MRSA can cause more serious infections, such as pneumonia and bloodstream infections.

is an inflammation of the mucous membranes lining the digestive tract.

Mucositis is a condition characterized by inflammation of the mucous membranes lining the digestive tract, resulting in pain, swelling, and ulceration in the affected area. It can cause difficulty eating and swallowing, as well as nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea.

is a type of cancer that affects the bone marrow

Multiple myeloma is a type of cancer that affects the bone marrow and causes anemia, bone pain, frequent infections, and kidney problems. Symptoms may also include fatigue, weight loss, and an increased risk of bleeding and broken bones.

is a disorder in which the body's immune system attacks the covering of nerve cells, leading to inflammation and damage of the myelin sheath

Multiple sclerosis is an autoimmune disorder where the body's immune system mistakenly attacks the myelin sheath that covers the nerve cells, resulting in inflammation and damage. This can lead to a range of physical and mental symptoms such as muscle weakness, coordination problems, vision loss, and cognitive issues.

(MSA) is a rare neurological disorder that affects adult men and women.

MSA is a rare neurological disorder that affects both men and women. Symptoms of MSA include difficulty in coordinating movement, tremors, muscle stiffness, balance problems, and urinary incontinence.

is a contagious viral infection that affects the salivary glands.

Mumps is a contagious viral infection that causes inflammation of the salivary glands. Common symptoms include fever, headache, muscle aches, tiredness, and loss of appetite. Swelling of the salivary glands may also occur, resulting in painful swelling of the cheeks and jaw.

is a mental disorder in which people purposely make themselves sick or get sick

Munchausen Syndrome is a mental disorder in which people deliberately make themselves ill or pretend to be ill in order to draw attention and sympathy from others. Symptoms can include self-induced physical harm, exaggerating existing medical conditions, and seeking unnecessary medical care.

is a group of inherited muscle diseases that cause progressive weakness and loss of muscle mass.

Muscular dystrophy is a group of diseases that cause progressive weakness and wasting of the muscles, resulting in loss of muscle mass. Symptoms typically include difficulty in walking, climbing stairs, and lifting objects.

diagnosis: Myalgic encephalomyelitis or chronic fatigue syndrome (ME/CFS)
symptoms:
is a complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can’t be explained by any underlying medical condition.

Myalgic encephalomyelitis/chronic fatigue syndrome (ME/CFS) is a disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that cannot be explained by any other medical condition. Symptoms can include cognitive difficulties, headaches, muscle and joint pain, and sleep disturbances.

is a chronic autoimmune neuromuscular disease.

Myasthenia gravis is a chronic autoimmune disease that affects the nerves and muscles. It causes weakness in the muscles that worsens with activity and can lead to difficulty speaking, swallowing and breathing.

is an infection caused by a type of bacteria called Mycobacterium chimaera.

Mycobacterium chimaera infection is caused by a type of bacteria which can lead to fever, chest pain, coughing, and difficulty breathing. It can also cause inflammation of the lymph nodes, skin lesions, and joint pain. In some cases, it can cause organ failure and death.

is a group of disorders caused by poorly formed or dysfunctional blood cells in the bone marrow.

Myelodysplastic Syndrome is a group of disorders caused by abnormal or impaired formation of blood cells in the bone marrow. Symptoms may include fatigue, weakness, shortness of breath, easy bruising, and increased risk of infection.
