Multiple myeloma is a cancer of the plasma cells in the bone marrow. Symptoms of multiple myeloma can include bone pain, fatigue, anemia, frequent infections, and kidney problems. Other symptoms can include weight loss, constipation, and confusion.

Myopia, also known as short-sightedness, is a refractive error of the eye. People with myopia have difficulty seeing distant objects clearly, and instead can only see objects that are close to them clearly. Common symptoms associated with myopia include headaches, eye strain, and squinting.

is a rare type of muscle inflammation that can cause muscle weakness, pain, and fatigue.

Myositis is a rare type of muscle inflammation that can cause weakness, pain and fatigue. Symptoms include muscle weakness, pain, and fatigue.

is a disorder of the inner ear.

Ménière's disease is a disorder of the inner ear that affects hearing and balance. Symptoms include dizziness, vertigo, tinnitus, and hearing loss. These symptoms can occur suddenly and can last for hours or days.

diagnosis: Nail fungal infection, see Fungal nail infection
symptoms: Nail fungal infection is a common condition caused by a fungus that infects a fingernail, toenail, or the skin under the nail. Symptoms include discoloration of the nail, thickening of the nail, crumbling of the nail, and pain in and around the nail.

is a rare genetic disorder that affects the nails, knees, elbows, and hips.

Nail patella syndrome is a rare genetic disorder which affects the nails, knees, elbows, and hips. Symptoms include underdeveloped or absent fingernails and toenails, abnormally shaped kneecaps, and hip and elbow joint deformities.

can range from discoloration to thickening, brittleness, crumbling, and splitting.

Nail problems can include discoloration, thickening, brittleness, crumbling and splitting of the nails. These issues can cause discomfort and difficulty with everyday activities.

is a red, sore or spotty rash on your baby's bottom, genitals or thighs

Nappy rash is a common skin condition in babies and toddlers. It is characterised by a red, sore or spotty rash on the bottom, genitals or thighs. It can be caused by the baby's skin being in contact with urine or faeces, or by friction from a nappy that is too tight.

is a neurological disorder that affects the control of sleep and wakefulness.

Narcolepsy is a neurological disorder that causes excessive daytime sleepiness and disrupts the normal sleep-wake cycle. Symptoms include sudden and uncontrollable episodes of sleep, paralysis, hallucinations, and disrupted nighttime sleep.

is a rare type of cancer.

Nasal and sinus cancer is a rare type of cancer that causes symptoms such as nosebleeds, facial pain, headaches, and a blocked nose. Other symptoms can include a lump in the neck, swelling in the face, and changes in vision.

are soft, painless, noncancerous growths on the lining of your nasal passages or sinuses

Nasal polyps are growths that form on the lining of the nasal passages or sinuses. They are soft, painless, and noncancerous. They can cause a variety of symptoms, including a blocked or runny nose, loss of smell, and a feeling of pressure in the face.

may cause a variety of symptoms including a sore throat, earache, neck swelling, and difficulty swallowing.

Nasopharyngeal cancer can cause a sore throat, earache, neck swelling, and difficulty swallowing. These can be signs that something is wrong and should be checked out by a doctor.

Nausea is a feeling of unease and discomfort in the upper stomach that can lead to vomiting. It is often accompanied by a loss of appetite, dizziness, and fatigue. Nausea can be caused by a variety of factors, including motion sickness, certain medications, and certain medical conditions.
The patient is experiencing pain in their neck that radiates down their shoulder and arm. They may also experience headaches, tingling, numbness, and weakness in their arm and hand.

is a rare but serious bacterial infection that affects the tissue beneath the skin, in the surrounding muscles and in the wall of the fascia (the thin tissue that separates the muscles).

Necrotising fasciitis is a rare bacterial infection that can cause serious damage to the tissue beneath the skin, muscles, and fascia. Symptoms include redness, swelling, and intense pain. If left untreated, the infection can cause death of the tissue and spread quickly.

Neonatal herpes is a serious infection caused by the herpes simplex virus. Symptoms in newborns may include skin rash, blisters, fever, poor feeding, seizures, and lethargy. In some cases, the virus can cause serious brain damage, disability, or even death. 

Neonatal herpes is a serious infection caused by the herpes simplex virus. Symptoms in newborns can include skin rash, blisters, fever, poor feeding, seizures, lethargy, brain damage, disability, and in some cases, death.

Nephrotic syndrome in children is a condition characterized by high levels of protein in the urine, low levels of protein in the blood, swelling in the body, and high levels of cholesterol in the blood. Symptoms can also include weight gain, fatigue, and foamy urine.

is a type of cancer that most often begins in early childhood

Neuroblastoma is a type of cancer that typically affects young children, usually under the age of 5. Symptoms of neuroblastoma can include abdominal pain, swelling in the abdomen or neck, bone pain, difficulty breathing, fever, and fatigue.

(NETs) are rare tumours that start in cells that make hormones in the body.

Neuroendocrine tumours are rare tumours that originate from cells that produce hormones in the body. Symptoms of these tumours can include abdominal pain, diarrhea, weight loss, and hormonal imbalances.

Neuroendocrine tumours (NETs) are a type of cancer that can cause the release of hormones and other substances into the bloodstream. Carcinoid syndrome is a set of symptoms that may occur when these hormones are released in high amounts. Symptoms of carcinoid syndrome include flushing, diarrhea, wheezing, abdominal cramps, and heart valve damage.

is a genetic disorder that can cause tumors to grow on the nerves throughout the body.

Neurofibromatosis type 1 is a genetic disorder that can cause tumors to grow on the nerves in the body. Symptoms of this disorder may include skin changes, vision problems, headaches, learning disabilities, and skeletal abnormalities. Other symptoms may include hearing loss, seizures, and scoliosis.

(NF2) is a rare genetic disorder

Neurofibromatosis type 2 (NF2) is a rare genetic disorder that causes tumors to grow on the nerves in the brain and spine. Symptoms of the disorder include hearing loss, balance issues, facial weakness, and vision problems due to the growth of tumors on the nerves.

(NMO) is an autoimmune disorder that affects the central nervous system.

Neuromyelitis optica (NMO) is an autoimmune disorder that affects the central nervous system, causing damage to the optic nerves and spinal cord. Symptoms include vision loss, weakness, numbness, and pain in the arms and legs. It can also cause bladder and bowel dysfunction, fatigue, and cognitive decline.

is a condition in which a baby’s skin and whites of the eyes turn yellow.

Newborn jaundice is a condition in which a baby's skin and the whites of their eyes become yellow. It is caused by an increase in the level of bilirubin, a yellow-colored pigment, in the baby's blood. Symptoms include yellowing of the skin, yellowing of the whites of the eyes, and a yellowish tinge to the baby's urine and stool.

(NRDS) is a condition in which an infant has difficulty breathing due to immature lungs.

Newborn Respiratory Distress Syndrome (NRDS) is a condition in which an infant has difficulty breathing due to immature lungs. Symptoms of NRDS include rapid breathing, grunting noises when breathing, flaring of the nostrils, and cyanosis (blue skin color). Babies with NRDS may also experience chest retractions, nasal flaring, and low oxygen levels.

for type 2 diabetes

Type 2 diabetes is a serious condition that can cause serious health complications such as stroke, heart disease, and kidney disease. Symptoms of type 2 diabetes include increased thirst, increased hunger, frequent urination, fatigue, blurred vision, and slow healing of wounds. The NHS offers screening for type 2 diabetes to help identify those at risk.

Type 2 diabetes is a serious condition that can cause a range of health complications. Symptoms include increased thirst, hunger, frequent urination, fatigue, blurred vision, and slow healing of wounds. The NHS offers screening to help identify those at risk of developing the condition.

can be a sign of a variety of medical conditions.

Night sweats are episodes of excessive sweating that occur during the night, usually while sleeping. They are often accompanied by other symptoms, such as chills, fever, headaches, dizziness, and night sweats. They can be a sign of an underlying medical condition, such as an infection, an endocrine disorder, or even cancer.

Night terrors are episodes of screaming, intense fear and flailing while still asleep. Nightmares are vivid, disturbing dreams that elicit strong emotions such as fear, anxiety, or sadness. They usually occur during the Rapid Eye Movement (REM) stage of sleep.

can vary in color, consistency, and amount.

Nipple discharge is a symptom that can present itself in various forms. It can be clear, yellow, white, green, or brown in color, and can be thin, thick, sticky, or milky in consistency. The amount of discharge can range from a small amount to a large amount.

Noise sensitivity (hyperacusis) is a condition characterized by an increased sensitivity to certain frequencies and volumes of sound. People with hyperacusis often experience discomfort, pain, or even panic when exposed to everyday sounds that others may not even notice. Symptoms may include ringing in the ears, dizziness, headaches, and/or nausea.

is a condition in which excess fat accumulates in the liver.

Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) is a condition where there is an accumulation of fat in the liver. Symptoms can include fatigue, abdominal pain, and weight loss. In some cases, the disease can progress to more serious conditions such as cirrhosis or liver cancer.

is a condition that causes the inside of the nose to become inflamed and irritated.

Non-allergic rhinitis is a condition that causes irritation and inflammation in the inside of the nose. Symptoms include sneezing, a runny nose, congestion, postnasal drip, and an itchy or burning sensation in the nose.

Non-gonococcal urethritis is an infection of the urethra caused by bacteria. Symptoms include pain or burning when urinating, increased frequency or urgency of urination, and discharge from the urethra.

is a type of cancer that affects the lymphatic system.

Non-Hodgkin lymphoma is a type of cancer that affects the lymphatic system and can cause swelling of the lymph nodes, fever, night sweats, weight loss, and fatigue. It can also cause chest pain, coughing, and difficulty breathing.

is a genetic disorder that can cause a variety of signs and symptoms

Noonan Syndrome is a genetic disorder that can cause various physical and developmental issues. Common symptoms include heart defects, short stature, webbed neck, broad chest, and low-set ears. Other signs and symptoms may include vision and hearing problems, learning disabilities, and weak muscle tone.

Norovirus, commonly referred to as the "vomiting bug," is a highly contagious virus that causes sudden onset of nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, and stomach cramps. Other symptoms may include headache, fever, chills, and muscle aches. Symptoms usually last one to three days.

diagnosis: Nose cancer, see Nasal and sinus cancer
symptoms: Nose cancer, also referred to as Nasal and sinus cancer, is a type of cancer that affects the nasal passages, sinuses, and nasal cavity. Symptoms may include nasal obstruction, nasal discharge, facial pain, a lump in the neck, and difficulty or pain with swallowing.

, headache, nausea

The person is experiencing a nosebleed, a headache, and nausea. These are all symptoms of an underlying medical condition and should be checked out by a physician.

can cause gastrointestinal problems such as nausea and vomiting, abdominal pain and cramping, and ulcers.

NSAIDs can cause gastrointestinal problems including nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain and cramping, and ulcers. These symptoms can range from mild to severe.

is a medical condition in which excess body fat has accumulated to the extent that it may have an adverse effect on health, leading to reduced life expectancy and/or increased health problems.

Obesity is a medical condition in which an individual has accumulated excess body fat, resulting in adverse health effects, such as reduced life expectancy and increased health problems. It can also lead to psychological and social issues.

is a mental health disorder that affects people of all ages and walks of life, and occurs when a person gets caught in a cycle of obsessions and compulsions.

Obsessive Compulsive Disorder (OCD) is a mental health disorder that causes people to experience persistent and intrusive thoughts (obsessions) and to engage in repetitive behaviors (compulsions). Symptoms of OCD can include recurrent and unwanted thoughts, fear of contamination, and a need to do things in a certain order.

diagnosis: Obstructive sleep apnoea, see Sleep apnoea
symptoms: Obstructive sleep apnoea is a sleep disorder characterized by shallow breathing or pauses in breathing during sleep. It is caused by blockage of the airway, usually when the soft tissue in the back of the throat collapses and closes during sleep. Symptoms of obstructive sleep apnoea include loud snoring, episodes of stopped breathing during sleep, excessive daytime sleepiness, morning headaches, and difficulty concentrating.

can help with a wide range of issues, including physical impairments, mental health issues, and developmental disabilities.

Occupational therapy is a form of therapy that can help with a variety of issues including physical impairments, mental health problems, and developmental disabilities. It is designed to help individuals improve their functioning and quality of life by improving their physical, mental, and social abilities.

are two related congenital conditions that affect the oesophagus.

Oesophageal atresia and tracheo-oesophageal fistula are two congenital conditions that cause abnormal development of the oesophagus. Symptoms include difficulty feeding, coughing, choking and gagging, vomiting and blue skin due to lack of oxygen.

is a type of cancer that affects the oesophagus, the muscular tube that carries food and liquid from the throat to the stomach.

The symptoms of oesophageal cancer include difficulty or pain when swallowing, unexplained weight loss, persistent indigestion, and pain behind the breastbone or in the back.

is a condition in which the fungus Candida albicans accumulates on the lining of your mouth.

Oral thrush is a condition caused by the fungus Candida albicans, which causes an overgrowth in the lining of the mouth. Symptoms of oral thrush include white patches on the tongue, inner cheeks, and throat, as well as redness and soreness in the mouth.

is an infectious disease of sheep and goats

Orf is an infectious disease of sheep and goats which is caused by a virus. Symptoms of the disease include the formation of scabs, ulceration, and thickening of the skin around the mouth, nose, or feet. Lameness can also occur in infected animals.

is a branch of dentistry that specializes in the diagnosis, prevention, and treatment of dental and facial irregularities.

Orthodontics helps diagnose, prevent, and treat dental and facial irregularities such as crooked teeth, improper bite, and misaligned jaws. It also helps in improving facial aesthetics and symmetry.

is a degenerative joint disease.

Osteoarthritis is a degenerative joint disease that causes pain and stiffness in the joints due to the breakdown of cartilage. It can also cause swelling, tenderness, and a crunching sound when the joint is moved.

, is a softening of the bones due to inadequate or defective bone mineralization, resulting in pain and tenderness in the affected areas.

Osteomalacia is a condition characterized by a softening of the bones, causing pain and tenderness in the affected areas. It is caused by inadequate or defective bone mineralization.

is a bone infection caused by bacteria.

Osteomyelitis is an infection of the bone caused by bacteria. It can cause pain, swelling, warmth, and redness around the affected area, as well as fever, chills, fatigue, and an open wound near the site of the infection. It may also cause joint stiffness and difficulty moving the affected area.

is a medical condition that is caused by a lack of calcium in the bones.

Osteopathy is a medical condition characterized by weakened bones due to a lack of calcium. This can lead to increased risk of fractures and bone pain. Symptoms may include joint stiffness, pain, and difficulty moving the affected bones.

formation is a common symptom of degenerative joint disease.

Osteophyte formation is a symptom of degenerative joint disease, which is a condition in which the cartilage in the joints breaks down over time. This leads to the formation of extra bone, known as bone spurs, around the affected joint. These bone spurs can cause pain and stiffness, as well as limit the range of motion of the joint.

is a condition in which the bones become weak and brittle, leading to an increased risk of fracture.

Osteoporosis is a condition in which the bones become weaker and more brittle, making them more susceptible to fractures. This can lead to pain and other complications.

is a disorder of the middle ear that causes hearing loss.

Otosclerosis is a disorder of the middle ear that causes hearing loss. It occurs when abnormal bone growth in the ear interferes with the movement of the tiny bones of the middle ear, preventing sound from being conducted properly to the inner ear and resulting in hearing loss. Symptoms of otosclerosis may include hearing loss, ringing in the ears (tinnitus), and dizziness.

is a type of cancer that begins in the ovaries

Ovarian cancer is a type of cancer that affects the ovaries, the female reproductive organs located in the pelvis. Symptoms of ovarian cancer can include abdominal bloating, pelvic pain or pressure, difficulty eating or feeling full quickly, and urinary urgency or frequency.

Ovarian cysts are fluid-filled sacs that can develop on a woman's ovaries. Symptoms of an ovarian cyst may include pelvic pain, bloating, pressure, or discomfort in the lower abdomen. In some cases, menstrual irregularities, such as heavier or more painful periods, may occur.

Hyperthyroidism is a condition in which the thyroid gland produces too much of the hormone thyroxine. Symptoms of hyperthyroidism include restlessness, weight loss, rapid heartbeat, sweating, and intolerance to heat. Other symptoms may include fatigue, tremors, anxiety, and changes in menstrual cycles.

Ovulation pain is a type of abdominal pain that is experienced by some women during the middle of their menstrual cycle. It can range from a mild ache to a sharp or stabbing sensation, and typically lasts for a few minutes to a few hours. It is usually felt on one side of the lower abdomen or pelvis.

diagnosis: Oxygen therapy, see Home oxygen therapy
symptoms: Home oxygen therapy is a treatment for people who have difficulty breathing due to a lung condition. Symptoms may include shortness of breath, feeling tired, and having a decreased ability to exercise. Oxygen therapy can help reduce shortness of breath, improve energy levels, and increase the ability to exercise.

is indicated for symptomatic bradycardia

Pacemaker implantation is a procedure recommended for symptomatic bradycardia, which is a condition characterized by a slow heart rate. Symptoms of bradycardia include dizziness, fatigue, fainting, shortness of breath, and chest pain. In severe cases, cardiac arrest may occur.

is a chronic disorder that affects the skeleton.

Paget's disease of bone is a chronic disorder characterized by the abnormal breakdown and formation of bone tissue. Symptoms can include bone pain, fractures, joint pain, deformities, and enlarged head size. It can also cause hearing loss, neurological disorders, and other issues.

is a form of breast cancer

Paget's disease of the nipple is a form of breast cancer that affects the skin of the nipple and the darker area around it (areola). Symptoms may include an itchy, scaly, and/or inflamed nipple, a burning sensation in the nipple, and/or bloody or yellow discharge from the nipple. The affected nipple may also become flattened or inverted.

diagnosis: Pain in testicles, see Testicle pain
symptoms: Testicle pain is a symptom in which one or both testicles experience discomfort or pain. It can range from a mild ache to a sharp and sudden pain. It may be accompanied by other symptoms such as swelling, scrotal skin discoloration, and difficulty urinating.

diagnosis: Painful bladder syndrome, see Bladder pain syndrome (interstitial cystitis)
symptoms: Bladder Pain Syndrome (Interstitial Cystitis) is a chronic condition that causes pain and discomfort in the bladder and pelvic area. Symptoms include a frequent and urgent need to urinate, pain or burning during urination, and pain in the bladder, pelvis, or lower abdomen. Other symptoms may include pressure, tenderness, or spasms in the bladder or pelvic area.

Heart palpitations are a symptom that involve an individual feeling a strong and irregular heartbeat, which can be accompanied by a sensation of skipped beats, a fluttering feeling in the chest, or a pounding sensation in the neck. It can be a sign of an underlying medical condition and can cause anxiety and fear.

patients often experience abdominal pain, tenderness, nausea, vomiting, fever, and diarrhea

Pancreas transplant patients commonly experience abdominal discomfort, tenderness, nausea, vomiting, fever, and diarrhea. These symptoms can be severe and can be a sign of infection or rejection of the transplanted organ.

can cause a variety of different symptoms.

Pancreatic cancer can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, weight loss, jaundice, loss of appetite, fatigue, and changes in blood sugar levels. Other symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, dark urine, and light-colored stools.

, is a sudden inflammation of the pancreas.

Acute pancreatitis is a sudden inflammation of the pancreas, which causes pain in the upper abdomen, nausea, vomiting and fever. Other common symptoms include rapid pulse, jaundice, and abdominal tenderness.

Chronic pancreatitis is a long-term inflammation of the pancreas that can cause abdominal pain, digestive issues, and diabetes. Symptoms of chronic pancreatitis include abdominal pain that may radiate to the back, weight loss, oily or fatty stools, and diabetes. Other symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, indigestion, and jaundice.

Chronic pancreatitis is a long-term inflammation of the pancreas which can cause abdominal pain, digestive issues, and diabetes. Symptoms include abdominal pain, weight loss, oily or fatty stools, diabetes, nausea, vomiting, indigestion, and jaundice.

is a real illness that causes sudden and repeated attacks of fear that last for several minutes or longer.

Panic disorder is a mental health condition characterized by sudden and repeated episodes of intense fear and anxiety. These episodes can last for several minutes or longer and may include physical symptoms such as heart palpitations, shortness of breath, and chest pain.

of the facial nerve (Bell's palsy)

Bell's palsy is a form of facial paralysis that can cause one side of the face to droop or become weak. Symptoms can include partial or complete loss of facial movement, drooping of the eyelid and corner of the mouth, difficulty with eating and drinking, and increased sensitivity to sound on the affected side.

is a neurodegenerative disorder that affects the central nervous system.

Parkinson's disease is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder that affects the central nervous system, causing symptoms such as tremor, stiffness, slowness of movement, and difficulty with balance and coordination. It can also cause cognitive and behavioural changes.

Patau's Syndrome is a genetic disorder caused by a chromosomal abnormality. Symptoms include severe intellectual disability, physical abnormalities such as cleft lip/palate, extra fingers/toes, and heart defects, as well as weak muscle tone, seizures, and vision/hearing problems.

can be done to assess how well your lungs are working

A peak flow test measures the amount of air that can be exhaled in one forced breath to assess how well your lungs are functioning. It is commonly used to diagnose and monitor asthma, as well as to check for other lung diseases. Symptoms of decreased lung function include shortness of breath, wheezing, chest tightness, and coughing.

(PID) is an infection of the female reproductive organs.

Pelvic Inflammatory Disease (PID) is an infection of the female reproductive organs that can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, fever, abnormal vaginal discharge, pain during intercourse, and irregular menstrual bleeding. It can also lead to long-term complications such as infertility and chronic pelvic pain.

is a condition in which the female pelvic organs drop from their normal position and press against the walls of the vagina.

Pelvic organ prolapse is a condition in which the pelvic organs (uterus, bladder, rectum, etc.) of a female drop from their normal position and press against the walls of the vagina. Symptoms include feeling a bulge in the vagina, feeling pressure in the pelvic area, pain during sex, urinary problems, and difficulty with bowel movements.

is an autoimmune skin disorder that causes blisters and sores on the skin and mucous membranes.

Pemphigus vulgaris is an autoimmune disorder that causes blisters and sores on the skin and mucous membranes. These blisters and sores can be itchy and painful and may cause the skin to become red, swollen and raw.

is a rare form of cancer that affects a man's penis

Penile cancer is a rare form of cancer that affects the penis and is characterized by a growth or sore on the penis. Symptoms may include itching, bleeding, discharge, and/or a change in the color or texture of the penis. Pain may also be present.

A perforated eardrum is a hole or tear in the thin tissue that separates the ear canal and the middle ear. Symptoms include ear pain, hearing loss, ringing in the ear, fluid drainage from the ear, and dizziness.

is an inflammation of the pericardium, the thin sac-like membrane that surrounds the heart.

Pericarditis is an inflammation of the sac-like membrane around the heart, causing chest pain, difficulty breathing, and a rapid or irregular heartbeat. Other symptoms may include fever, fatigue, and an increased heart rate.

Perimenopause is the period of time leading up to menopause, and is characterized by hormonal changes and symptoms such as irregular periods, hot flashes, night sweats, and mood swings. It usually starts in a woman's 40s and can last up to a few years.

is a common complaint

Period pain is a type of abdominal pain that is experienced by women during their menstrual cycle. It is usually felt as cramping or throbbing in the lower abdomen, and can be accompanied by other symptoms such as nausea, fatigue, headaches, and lower back pain.

of feeling sad and low, difficulty concentrating, a lack of interest in activities and a lack of energy

The symptoms described are signs of depression, including periods of feeling sad and low, difficulty concentrating, a lack of interest in activities, and a lack of energy. These symptoms can be severe and interfere with daily life.

The patient is experiencing heavy periods, which is a symptom of menstrual disorders. This may include an unusually heavy or long flow of blood or cramping. Other symptoms may include headaches, bloating, fatigue, breast tenderness, and back pain.

The symptoms of irregular periods include having infrequent, irregular or unpredictable menstrual cycles, with cycles that are either too short or too long, or with light or heavy bleeding. Other symptoms can include spotting between periods, missed periods, or an absence of periods for several months.

is caused by a buildup of plaque in the walls of your arteries.

Peripheral arterial disease (PAD) is a condition caused by a buildup of plaque in the walls of the arteries, which can reduce or block the flow of oxygen-rich blood to the extremities. Symptoms of PAD can include pain, numbness or weakness in the legs, feet, or toes; coldness in the lower legs or feet; sores that won't heal; and a decrease in hair growth or color change in the legs.

is a condition in which the nerves in the peripheral nervous system become damaged

Peripheral neuropathy is a condition in which the nerves in the peripheral nervous system become damaged, causing pain, tingling, numbness and weakness in the affected areas of the body. It can affect the hands, feet, and other parts of the body. Symptoms may include burning pain, numbness, lack of coordination, and muscle weakness.

is an inflammation of the peritoneum, the thin tissue that lines the inner wall of the abdomen and covers most of the organs

Peritonitis is a medical condition that is characterized by inflammation of the peritoneum, which is the thin tissue that lines the inner wall of the abdomen and covers most of the organs. Symptoms of peritonitis include abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and fever.

are rare and aggressive forms of cancer.

Persistent trophoblastic disease and choriocarcinoma are rare and aggressive forms of cancer which can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, fever, and weight loss. These cancers can also spread to other parts of the body and cause more serious symptoms.

are mental health conditions that can affect a person’s emotions, thoughts and behaviour.

Personality disorders are mental health conditions that can cause a person to have difficulties in how they think, feel, and behave. These difficulties can make everyday life more challenging, and can lead to problems in relationships, work, and other areas of life.

A PET scan is a nuclear medicine imaging test which uses a small amount of a radioactive substance to produce detailed 3D images of the inside of the body. It is primarily used to detect cancer and other diseases such as heart disease, brain disorders and lung conditions. It can also help measure the effectiveness of treatments for these conditions.

A PET scan is a medical imaging test used to produce 3D images of the inside of the body. It is primarily used to detect cancer and other diseases such as heart disease, brain disorders, and lung conditions. It can also help measure the effectiveness of treatments for these conditions, by using a small amount of a radioactive substance.

is a rare tumour of the adrenal gland.

Phaeochromocytoma is a rare tumour of the adrenal gland that may cause symptoms such as high blood pressure, excessive sweating, headaches, and an irregular heart rate. It can also cause episodes of dizziness, nausea, and chest pain.

(PKU) is a rare inherited disorder

Phenylketonuria (PKU) is an inherited disorder characterized by an inability to metabolize the amino acid phenylalanine. Symptoms of PKU include intellectual disability, behavioral and developmental issues, seizures, and musty body odor. The disorder is usually diagnosed at birth through a newborn screening test.

Phimosis is a condition in which the foreskin of the penis is too tight to be pulled back over the head. It is most common in children, but can also occur in adults. Symptoms of phimosis include difficulty pulling back the foreskin, pain or discomfort during urination, and redness or swelling of the foreskin.

Phlebitis is an inflammation of the veins, usually in the leg. It is usually accompanied by pain, redness, and swelling in the affected area. It can also cause warmth, tenderness, and a feeling of heaviness in the leg. In some cases, a hard cord can be felt along the inflamed vein.

are intense, irrational fears of specific objects or situations

Phobias are irrational fears that cause extreme anxiety and distress in an individual when they are exposed to a certain object or situation. Symptoms can include trembling, rapid heartbeat, sweating, and difficulty breathing. People with phobias often go to great lengths to avoid the objects or situations that trigger their fear.

is a medical treatment that uses a drug and a particular type of light.

Photodynamic therapy is a medical treatment that combines the use of a drug with a certain type of light to treat a variety of medical conditions. The drug, which is activated by the light, works to destroy cancer cells or reduce inflammation.

can help reduce pain and stiffness, improve mobility and function, and increase strength.

Physiotherapy can help reduce pain and stiffness, improve mobility and function, and increase strength. It can be an effective way to treat certain conditions, such as arthritis, back pain, and sports injuries. The main symptoms that can be alleviated with physiotherapy are pain, stiffness, decreased mobility and strength.

are lumps that can form inside and around the anus.

Piles, also known as haemorrhoids, are swollen lumps that form inside and around the anus. Symptoms of piles can include pain, itching, swelling, and bleeding during bowel movements.

Pilonidal sinus is a painful condition that usually occurs in the crease of the buttocks near the tailbone. Symptoms may include a small dimple, a cyst, or a small tunnel filled with hair and pus. Pain and swelling may also be present.

is a sensation of numbness or tingling in different parts of the body.

Pins and needles is a sensation of numbness or tingling in different parts of the body. This sensation is often described as a prickling, burning, or tingling feeling. It can occur in the hands, feet, arms, and legs, but can also be felt in other areas of the body.

leak silicone gel into the body

PIP breast implants can cause leakage of silicone gel into the surrounding body tissue. This can cause inflammation, pain, and hardening of the breast area. In some cases, the gel can spread to other parts of the body, causing further health complications.

is a common skin rash that usually starts with a single, scaly, pink patch with a raised border on the chest, back, or abdomen

Pityriasis rosea is a common skin rash that affects many people. It typically starts with a single, scaly, pink patch with a raised border on the chest, back, or abdomen. This is often followed by other scaly, pink patches that may appear on the arms, legs, neck, or face. The rash is usually itchy and may last for several weeks.

is a skin condition that is caused by a yeast infection.

Pityriasis versicolor is a skin condition caused by a yeast infection. Symptoms include discolored patches of skin on the chest, back, arms, and neck that may be lighter or darker than the surrounding skin. It may also cause itching and scaling of the skin.

Plagiocephaly and brachycephaly (flat head syndrome) are conditions characterized by an asymmetrical or flattened shape of the head or skull. The head may be flattened on one side, or the back of the head may be flattened in a condition called brachycephaly. Symptoms may include a flat spot or ridge on the head, an unevenly shaped head, or a head shape that is more elongated than is typical.

is a common cause of heel pain.

Plantar fasciitis is a condition that causes pain in the heel and bottom of the foot. It is often caused by overuse and can cause stabbing or burning pain in the heel when first standing up after rest.

can result in physical and emotional side effects

Physical side effects of plastic surgery can include pain, swelling, numbness, scarring, and infection. Emotional side effects can include anxiety, depression, and body image issues.

is a condition in which there is pain in the chest due to inflammation of the pleura, a thin membrane that lines the chest cavity and covers the lungs.

Pleurisy is an inflammatory condition of the pleura, characterized by chest pain. This membrane lines the chest cavity and covers the lungs, causing pain when inflamed.

PMS is a common condition that affects women in the week or two before their period. Symptoms of PMS can include mood swings, irritability, depression, anxiety, bloating, fatigue, breast tenderness, headaches, food cravings, and difficulty sleeping.

is an infection of the lungs. It causes inflammation in one or both of the lungs.

Pneumonia is an infection of the lungs which causes inflammation in one or both of the lungs. Symptoms include coughing, fever, chest pain, and difficulty breathing.

from ingestion of lead can cause abdominal pain, headaches, confusion, fatigue, anemia, and irritability.

Ingestion of lead can cause a range of symptoms including abdominal pain, headaches, confusion, fatigue, anemia, and irritability. These symptoms can be indicative of lead poisoning, and should be taken seriously.

is a contagious disease caused by the poliovirus.

Polio is a contagious disease caused by the poliovirus which can lead to paralysis, difficulty breathing, and even death. Symptoms include fever, fatigue, headache, vomiting, stiffness in the neck and limbs, and pain in the limbs. In some cases, paralysis can occur in the legs, arms, and other parts of the body.

diagnosis: Polycystic kidney disease (autosomal dominant), see Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease
symptoms: Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD) is a genetic disorder characterized by the growth of numerous cysts in the kidneys. Symptoms may include high blood pressure, abdominal pain, blood in the urine, and kidney stones. In some cases, kidney failure may occur.

diagnosis: Polycystic kidney disease (autosomal recessive), see Autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease
symptoms: Autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease is a genetic disorder that causes cysts to form in the kidneys, leading to kidney failure. Symptoms may include high blood pressure, back or side pain, blood in the urine, kidney stones, and urinary tract infections. In severe cases, the cysts can cause enlarged kidneys, which can lead to abdominal swelling, kidney failure, and other complications.

(PCOS) is a hormonal disorder common among women of reproductive age.

The primary symptoms of PCOS include irregular or absent menstrual periods, excessive hair growth, and weight gain. It can also cause fertility problems, acne, and thinning of hair on the scalp.

Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a hormonal disorder common among women of reproductive age that can cause irregular or absent menstrual periods, excessive hair growth, weight gain, fertility problems, acne, and thinning of hair on the scalp.

Polyhydramnios is a condition in which there is too much amniotic fluid in the uterus. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, difficulty breathing, and an abnormally large uterus. Other possible signs are an increased heart rate in the baby, difficulty with fetal movements, and a decrease in fetal movements.

(PMLE) is a skin condition that's caused by exposure to sunlight.

Polymorphic light eruption (PMLE) is a skin condition triggered by exposure to sunlight. Symptoms include redness, itching, burning, and bumps on the skin, which can appear anywhere on the body. It can last up to several days after exposure to the sun.

is a disorder that causes muscle pain and stiffness, particularly in the neck, shoulders and hips

Polymyalgia rheumatica is a disorder that causes muscle pain and stiffness in the neck, shoulders and hips. It is usually accompanied by fatigue and a general feeling of being unwell. Symptoms may worsen with activity and improve with rest.

is a skin condition that causes itchy blisters on the palms of the hands and soles of the feet

Pompholyx is a skin condition that causes itchy blisters on the palms of the hands and soles of the feet. Symptoms include red, itchy patches on the skin and the formation of tiny, fluid-filled blisters. The blisters can be painful and can cause extreme itching.

Popliteal cyst, also known as Baker's cyst, is a fluid-filled swelling in the back of the knee. It is often accompanied by pain and stiffness in the knee, as well as a feeling of tightness and difficulty in bending the knee.

is a nerve disorder that occurs after a person has had shingles.

Post-herpetic neuralgia is a nerve disorder that causes pain and sensitivity to the skin in the area where the person had shingles. Symptoms may include burning and stabbing pain, hypersensitivity to touch, and itching.

examination has revealed that the death was due to a heart attack.

The cause of death was determined to be a heart attack through post-mortem examination. The heart attack was the direct cause of death.

(PPS) is a condition that affects people who have had poliomyelitis.

Post-polio syndrome (PPS) is a condition that affects people who have had poliomyelitis. Symptoms of PPS include fatigue, joint pain, muscle weakness, and breathing and swallowing difficulties. People with PPS may experience worsening of existing symptoms of polio or the development of new symptoms.

is a mental health condition that can be triggered by a terrifying event

PTSD is a mental health disorder that is caused by a traumatic event. Symptoms include flashbacks, nightmares, difficulty sleeping, irritability, difficulty concentrating, and feeling emotionally numb. People with PTSD may also experience physical symptoms such as increased heart rate and difficulty breathing.

Postmenopausal bleeding is a condition in which a woman experiences vaginal bleeding after menopause. It is considered abnormal and can be a sign of a medical condition such as endometrial cancer or uterine fibroids. Symptoms of postmenopausal bleeding include spotting or heavy bleeding from the vagina, pain, and changes in menstrual cycle.

(PND)

Postnatal depression (PND) is a mental health disorder that can affect women after giving birth. It is characterized by feelings of sadness, anxiety, exhaustion, and lack of interest in activities that used to bring pleasure. Other symptoms of PND can include difficulty bonding with the baby, sleeping problems, feeling overwhelmed, and difficulty concentrating.

is a rare mental health disorder that can occur after childbirth.

Postpartum psychosis is a mental health disorder that can occur after childbirth and is characterized by symptoms such as extreme mood swings, confusion, hallucinations, delusions, and difficulty sleeping. It can also cause feelings of paranoia, agitation, and detachment from reality.

is a condition

Postural tachycardia syndrome (PoTS) is a condition characterized by an increase in heart rate when standing up that is accompanied by symptoms such as lightheadedness, dizziness, fatigue, chest pain, and difficulty concentrating. It can also cause anxiety, headaches, and palpitations. Other symptoms include nausea, blurred vision, and fainting.

results indicate that the patient has a low potassium level.

The patient has a low potassium level, as indicated by their potassium test results. This is evidenced by a reading lower than the normal range for potassium levels.

is a medical condition that affects the way the body grows and develops.

Prader-Willi Syndrome is a genetic disorder characterized by low muscle tone, poor growth, intellectual disability, behavior problems, and an insatiable appetite which can lead to obesity. Symptoms include delayed motor skills, short stature, and mild to moderate intellectual disability.

is a condition in pregnancy characterized by high blood pressure and signs of damage to another organ system, most often the liver and kidneys

Pre-eclampsia is a pregnancy complication characterized by high blood pressure and damage to other organ systems, usually the liver and kidneys. Symptoms may include swelling, rapid weight gain, headaches, and changes in vision.

diagnosis: Predictive genetic tests for cancer risk genes
symptoms:
can help identify individuals who are at increased risk for cancer.

Predictive genetic tests can help identify people who may be more likely to develop certain types of cancer due to their genetic makeup. These tests can detect mutations in genes that are associated with an increased risk of cancer.

Premature ejaculation is a type of ejaculation problem which involves ejaculation occurring earlier than desired during sexual activity. It can be a source of distress for both partners, causing feelings of frustration and anxiety. Common symptoms include difficulty delaying ejaculation and a decrease in the intensity of orgasm.

are areas of damaged skin caused by staying in one position for too long.

Pressure ulcers are caused by prolonged pressure on the skin, which can lead to the skin breaking down and becoming damaged. They typically form on areas of the body that have the most contact with a surface, such as the heels, hips, and elbows. Symptoms include redness, discoloration, swelling, pain, and open sores.

Priapism is a medical condition characterized by prolonged, painful erections lasting for more than four hours without any sexual stimulation. It can be a medical emergency, as it can cause permanent damage to the penis if left untreated. Symptoms include a persistent, painful erection, tenderness in the penis, and a lack of response to sexual stimulation.

diagnosis: Prickly heat, see Heat rash (prickly heat)
symptoms: Prickly heat is a skin rash caused by blocked sweat glands. Symptoms include small red bumps that can be itchy and painful. It is most common in hot and humid climates, and is typically found on areas of the body that are covered by clothing.

is an autoimmune disorder that affects the liver

Primary biliary cholangitis (PBC) is an autoimmune disorder that affects the liver, causing inflammation and damage to the bile ducts. Symptoms of PBC can include fatigue, itching, jaundice, dark urine, abdominal pain, and weight loss. Over time, PBC can lead to cirrhosis, liver failure, and other serious complications.

have been shown to reduce stomach pain, bloating, and gas

Probiotics have been demonstrated to help relieve symptoms associated with digestive issues, such as stomach pain, bloating, and gas. They can also help improve overall digestion and gut health.

, a feeling of a lump in the throat, and coughing

The patient is experiencing difficulty swallowing pills, a sensation of a lump in their throat, and coughing.

Proctalgia is a type of anal pain. Symptoms include a sharp, severe, and sudden pain in the anus, which may last from a few seconds to several minutes. Other symptoms include aching and throbbing in the area, as well as an inability to sit comfortably.

(PSP) is a type of brain disorder that affects movement, control of walking, and balance.

Progressive supranuclear palsy (PSP) is a neurological disorder which causes difficulty with movement, walking, and balance. Symptoms include problems with coordination and balance, stiffness in the limbs, difficulty speaking, changes in vision, and difficulty swallowing.

diagnosis: Prolapse (pelvic organ), see Pelvic organ prolapse
symptoms: Pelvic organ prolapse is a condition in which the structures that support the pelvic organs become weak or stretched, causing the organs to descend from their normal position. Symptoms may include a feeling of heaviness or pressure in the pelvic area, painful intercourse, and difficulty with urination or bowel movements.

is a neurological disorder characterized by the inability to recognize faces.

Prosopagnosia is a neurological disorder that affects a person's ability to recognize faces. People with this disorder are unable to recognize familiar faces, including their own. They may also have difficulty recognizing facial expressions, distinguishing between similar faces, and remembering a face after seeing it only once.

usually doesn't cause symptoms until it has spread outside the prostate.

Prostate cancer is usually asymptomatic until it has metastasized to other areas of the body. When this happens, the patient may experience urinary difficulties, pain in the lower back, hips, or pelvis, and erectile dysfunction.

diagnosis: Prostate enlargement, see Benign prostate enlargement
symptoms: Benign prostate enlargement is a condition in which the prostate gland is enlarged, but is not cancerous. Symptoms may include difficulty urinating, a frequent need to urinate, a weak urine stream, and a feeling of incomplete bladder emptying.

can cause a variety of symptoms, including frequent urination, difficulty urinating, weak urine stream, and pain or burning during urination.

Prostate problems can cause a range of uncomfortable symptoms, such as needing to urinate more often, difficulty in urinating, a weak urine stream, and pain or burning sensations when urinating.

is an inflammation of the prostate gland and can cause pain or discomfort in the lower abdomen, pain in the genital area, pain when urinating, frequent urination, and difficulty urinating

Prostatitis is a condition that causes inflammation of the prostate gland, resulting in pain in the lower abdomen, genital area, and difficulty when urinating. Symptoms include pain when urinating, frequent urination, and difficulty emptying the bladder completely.

is a chronic skin condition that causes skin cells to multiply up to 10 times faster than normal.

Psoriasis is a skin condition that causes skin cells to grow and reproduce at a much faster rate than normal. This can lead to thick, red, scaly patches on the skin and can be itchy, painful, and uncomfortable.

is a form of arthritis that affects some people who have psoriasis.

Psoriatic arthritis is a type of arthritis that occurs in people with psoriasis, causing joint pain, stiffness, swelling, and tenderness. It can also cause fatigue, decreased range of motion, and nail changes.

is a branch of medicine that deals with the diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of mental, emotional, and behavioral disorders.

Psychiatry focuses on diagnosing and treating mental, emotional, and behavioral disorders. It covers diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of these disorders.

is a severe mental disorder in which thought and emotions are so impaired that contact is lost with external reality.

Psychosis is a severe mental disorder characterized by a loss of contact with reality. Symptoms include impaired thought and emotion, hallucinations, delusions, disorganized speech and behavior, and other cognitive difficulties.

is a serious mental health condition that requires professional diagnosis and treatment

Psychotic depression is a severe form of depression that can cause a person to experience psychosis, including delusions and hallucinations. Symptoms of psychotic depression include feelings of worthlessness and guilt, loss of interest in activities, fatigue, insomnia, and suicidal thoughts. Other symptoms may include changes in appetite and weight, and difficulty concentrating.

diagnosis: Puberty (early or delayed), see Early or delayed puberty
symptoms: Early or delayed puberty is a condition in which a person experiences physical changes associated with puberty either earlier or later than the normal age range. Symptoms of early puberty include the development of secondary sexual characteristics such as breast development in girls and facial hair in boys, as well as growth spurts and accelerated bone growth. Symptoms of delayed puberty include the lack of physical development associated with puberty, such as the absence of breast development in girls and facial hair in boys, as well as no growth spurts and slow bone growth.

infestations (crabs) are usually spread through sexual contact.

Pubic lice infestations, commonly referred to as crabs, are caused by tiny parasitic insects which are usually spread through sexual contact. Symptoms include itching and the presence of small white eggs, known as nits, which can be found on the pubic hair.

is a chronic pain disorder that affects the nerves in the pelvic region

Pudendal neuralgia is a chronic pain disorder that causes pain in the pelvic region due to nerve damage. Symptoms may include burning and stabbing sensations, as well as numbness and tingling sensations in the area. It may also cause pain during urination and sexual activity.

is a life-threatening condition that occurs when a blood clot gets lodged in an artery in the lungs, blocking blood flow.

Pulmonary embolism is a serious medical condition in which a blood clot gets stuck in an artery in the lungs, blocking the blood flow. This can lead to chest pain, shortness of breath, and low oxygen levels in the blood.

diagnosis: Pulmonary fibrosis, see Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis
symptoms: Pulmonary fibrosis is a lung disease where the tissue and air sacs in the lungs become thick and scarred, making it difficult to breathe. Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis is a type of pulmonary fibrosis of unknown cause, which can lead to a progressive decline in lung function. Symptoms include shortness of breath, a dry cough, fatigue, and weight loss.

is a rare lung disorder affecting the arteries of the lungs

Pulmonary hypertension is a rare lung disorder that affects the arteries that connect the heart to the lungs. Symptoms include shortness of breath, chest pain, fatigue, dizziness, and fainting. In severe cases, the right side of the heart may fail, leading to heart failure.

is an uncommon, ulcerative skin disorder

Pyoderma gangrenosum is a rare skin disorder that causes ulcers to form on the skin. These ulcers are typically painful, red, and may have a purplish-blue border. They can grow rapidly and may become infected. Other symptoms may include fever, malaise, and joint pain.

is an infection caused by the bacteria Coxiella burnetii

Q fever is an infectious disease caused by the bacteria Coxiella burnetii. Symptoms of Q fever include fever, chills, headache, muscle pain, chest pain, and a cough. In some cases, people may also experience fatigue, joint pain, abdominal pain, and shortness of breath.

Quinsy is a form of tonsillitis, an inflammation of the tonsils that can cause severe pain in the throat and difficulty swallowing. Symptoms can include fever, chills, sore throat, swollen tonsils, and difficulty swallowing.

is a viral infection that affects the central nervous system.

Rabies is an infectious disease caused by a virus that affects the central nervous system. Symptoms may include fever, headache, confusion, excessive salivation, muscle spasms, and paralysis. In severe cases, death may occur.

is a type of cancer treatment used to treat cancer.

Radiotherapy is a type of cancer treatment used to destroy cancer cells and shrink tumors. It uses high-energy radiation to target cancer cells and stop them from growing and dividing. It can also be used to reduce the size of a tumor before surgery or to relieve symptoms caused by the tumor.

are common.

Rashes in babies and children are a common occurrence. They can range from mild to severe and can cause itching, redness and soreness of the skin. In some cases, rashes can be accompanied by fever, vomiting, or a change in behavior.

phenomenon

Raynaud's phenomenon is a disorder that affects blood circulation, usually in the fingers and toes. The main symptom is a change in color of the skin, from white to blue to red, in response to cold temperatures or stress. Other symptoms include tingling, numbness, and pain in the affected areas.

is a form of arthritis that is triggered by an infection in one part of the body.

Reactive arthritis is a type of inflammatory arthritis that is caused by an infection in another part of the body. It is characterized by joint pain, swelling, and stiffness, as well as inflammation of the eyes, mouth, and urethra. It can also cause fatigue and fever.

diagnosis: Rectal bleeding, see Bleeding from the bottom (rectal bleeding)
symptoms: Rectal bleeding is the medical term for blood passing from the rectum, which may be a sign of a gastrointestinal issue. Symptoms of rectal bleeding may include bright red blood on toilet paper or in the toilet bowl, pain in the anal area, or a feeling of pressure in the rectum.

Rectal cancer, also known as bowel cancer, is a type of cancer that affects the lower part of the colon and rectum. Symptoms may include blood in the stool, rectal pain or pressure, changes in bowel habits, or anemia. Other symptoms may include fatigue, weight loss, or anemia. Treatment options may include surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation therapy.

revealed a large, firm mass in the lower rectum

A rectal examination showed a large, hard lump in the lower rectum. This lump was not able to be moved and was causing discomfort.

is low

The patient is experiencing a low red blood cell count, which can cause symptoms such as fatigue, pale skin, weakness, dizziness, and shortness of breath.

, itchy, watery

A red eye is a common symptom of an eye infection. It is usually accompanied by itchiness and wateriness. The eye may also feel gritty or scratchy, and the individual may experience sensitivity to light.

Reflux in babies is a condition in which the contents of the stomach, including stomach acid, flow back up into the esophagus. Symptoms of reflux in babies can include frequent spitting up, vomiting, coughing, irritability, difficulty sleeping, and difficulty eating.

is an umbrella term used to describe the pain felt in muscles, nerves and tendons caused by repetitive movement and overuse

Repetitive strain injury (RSI) is an umbrella term used to describe a type of injury caused by overusing muscles, nerves, and tendons due to repetitive movement. It is characterized by pain in the affected area and can lead to decreased mobility and strength.

are caused by viruses, bacteria, or fungi.

Respiratory tract infections are a type of infection caused by viruses, bacteria, or fungi that affect the airways and lungs. Symptoms of RTIs include coughing, sore throat, runny nose, shortness of breath, and difficulty breathing.

is a neurological disorder that causes an overwhelming urge to move one's legs.

Restless Legs Syndrome is a neurological disorder that causes an intense urge to move the legs, accompanied by uncomfortable sensations such as tingling, burning, or itching. The symptoms are worse when lying down or sitting for long periods of time and can disrupt sleep.

Restricted growth (dwarfism) is a condition in which an individual's height is significantly below average for their age and gender. This can be caused by genetic or hormonal factors, or by a medical condition such as achondroplasia. Symptoms may include short stature, disproportionate limb lengths, and various health complications.

diagnosis: Retinal detachment, see Detached retina (retinal detachment)
symptoms: Retinal detachment is a medical condition where the retina is separated from its underlying layer of support tissue. It can cause vision loss and is a medical emergency that requires prompt treatment. Symptoms of a detached retina include floaters, flashes of light, blurred vision, and a sudden increase in vision loss.

is a rare condition that causes temporary vision loss in one eye.

Retinal migraine is a rare condition that affects vision and causes temporary vision loss in one eye. Symptoms include significant vision loss, flashes of light, blind spots, and discomfort in the affected eye. It can also cause pain around the eye or head.

Retinoblastoma is a type of eye cancer that affects children. Common symptoms include a white pupil, redness and swelling in the eye, and vision changes. Additionally, the eye may appear to be looking in a different direction than the other eye.

is a rare genetic neurological disorder that affects mostly girls.

Rett Syndrome is a rare genetic neurological disorder that primarily affects girls. Symptoms of the disorder include impaired cognitive and social development, speech and language delays, repetitive hand movements, and loss of purposeful hand use.

is a rare but serious condition that causes swelling in the liver and brain.

Reye's syndrome is a rare condition that causes swelling in the liver and brain, which can be serious and even life-threatening. Symptoms can include vomiting, confusion, seizures, and coma.

is a serious condition that affects unborn babies.

Rhesus disease is a serious medical condition that affects unborn babies, where the mother has a rhesus negative blood type and the baby has a rhesus positive blood type. It occurs when the mother's antibodies attack the baby's red blood cells, leading to anemia, jaundice, brain damage, and even death.

is an inflammatory disease that can develop after an untreated streptococcal infection.

Rheumatic fever is a serious condition that is caused by an untreated streptococcal infection. Symptoms of this condition include fever, joint pain, rash, and heart problems. It can also lead to long-term damage to the heart, lungs, and joints.

is an autoimmune disorder that causes pain, swelling, and stiffness in the joints.

Rheumatoid arthritis is an autoimmune disorder that affects the joints, causing pain, swelling, and stiffness. It is an inflammatory condition that can affect any joint in the body.

Allergic rhinitis is an allergic reaction of the nose to certain substances, such as pollen, pet dander, and dust mites. Symptoms of allergic rhinitis include sneezing, runny nose, itchy nose, congestion, and watery eyes. It can also cause headaches, fatigue, and difficulty sleeping.

are diseases that affect the bones

Rickets is a bone disorder caused by a deficiency of vitamin D, calcium, or phosphate. It causes softening of the bones and leads to bone deformities. Osteomalacia is a similar bone disorder caused by a lack of vitamin D, which results in weak bones and muscle weakness.

is an infection caused by a fungus

Ringworm is a fungal infection that causes a red, itchy, scaly rash on the skin. It is contagious and can be spread through direct contact with the infected area or through contact with infected items. Symptoms include red, itchy patches on the skin that may be scaly or crusty, and can spread to other parts of the body.

is necessary when the pulp of the tooth becomes infected or inflamed.

Root canal treatment is necessary when the pulp of the tooth is infected or inflamed, which may cause symptoms such as pain, swelling, and tenderness. The infection or inflammation can also lead to discoloration of the tooth.

is a common skin condition that causes redness and visible blood vessels in your face.

Rosacea is a skin condition that causes redness and visible blood vessels to appear in the face. It is characterized by redness, flushing, bumps, and visible blood vessels on the face. It can also cause burning or stinging sensation, and may lead to swollen skin and eye irritation.

is a common childhood illness caused by a virus

Roseola is a viral infection that commonly affects children under the age of three. Symptoms include a high fever, lasting 3-5 days, followed by a rash on the chest, abdomen, and sometimes the face, neck, and arms. Other symptoms may include fatigue, loss of appetite, and swollen lymph nodes.

Roundworm is a type of parasitic worm that can infect humans and cause an infection known as ascariasis. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea. In some cases, a person may also experience coughing, wheezing, and a fever. Roundworm can be diagnosed through a stool sample and can be treated with medications.

Rubella is a contagious viral infection characterized by a pinkish-red rash, low-grade fever, swollen lymph nodes, and sore throat. It is most common in children, but can also affect adults. Complications can occur in pregnant women, including miscarriage, stillbirth, or birth defects in the baby.

can cause pain, swelling, and infection in the mouth

Salivary gland stones can cause a range of symptoms, including pain, swelling, and infection in the mouth. The pain may be located in the area of the salivary gland and can range from mild to severe. Swelling in the area of the salivary gland can occur, as well as infection that may cause difficulty opening the mouth.

is a chronic inflammatory disease that involves the formation of granulomas in multiple organs.

Sarcoidosis is a chronic inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs and causes the formation of granulomas. Symptoms can include coughing, weight loss, night sweats, fatigue, and chest pain. In some cases, the disease can cause problems with the eyes, heart, and lungs.

is a skin condition caused by tiny mites.

Scabies is a skin condition caused by tiny mites which results in intense itching, rash, and small red bumps on the skin. It is often spread through skin-to-skin contact or contact with infected items. Symptoms usually appear within two to six weeks after contact.

is an infectious disease caused by a bacteria called Streptococcus pyogenes.

Scarlet fever is a bacterial infection caused by Streptococcus pyogenes, resulting in symptoms such as a sore throat, fever, and a rash. It can also cause swollen glands in the neck, headache, and vomiting.

dale is suffering from a mysterious illness that has been spreading rapidly.

Scarsdale is experiencing an outbreak of a mysterious illness that is spreading quickly. Symptoms include fever, coughing, and difficulty breathing. Other symptoms may include fatigue, sore throat, and body aches.

is a parasitic disease caused by a trematode (fluke) worm

Schistosomiasis (bilharzia) is a parasitic disease caused by a trematode (fluke) worm. It is contracted by contact with freshwater contaminated by the urine and faeces of infected people. Symptoms include fever, abdominal pain, diarrhoea, and a rash.

Schistosomiasis is a parasitic disease caused by a trematode (fluke) worm. It is contracted by contact with contaminated freshwater. Symptoms of the disease include fever, abdominal pain, diarrhoea, and a rash.

is a mental disorder that affects how a person thinks, feels, and behaves.

The symptoms of schizophrenia can include delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech and behavior, reduced emotional expression, and lack of motivation. People with schizophrenia may also experience social withdrawal, difficulty concentrating, and memory loss.

is a pain that radiates from the lower back down the back of one or both legs.

Sciatica is a pain that originates from the lower back and radiates down the back of one or both legs. It can cause tingling, numbness, and burning sensations. It may also be accompanied by muscle weakness.

is a chronic autoimmune disorder that affects the skin and connective tissues.

Scleroderma is a chronic autoimmune disorder that causes hardening and tightening of the skin and connective tissues. Symptoms may include thickening of the skin on the hands and face, joint pain, fatigue, and difficulty breathing.

is a condition in which the spine curves to the side.

Scoliosis is a condition in which the spine curves to the side, resulting in an abnormal curvature of the spine. Symptoms of scoliosis can include back pain, an uneven waistline, and one shoulder or hip appearing higher than the other.

is a disease caused by a lack of vitamin C

Scurvy is a disease caused by a lack of vitamin C which can lead to symptoms such as joint pain, fatigue, gum disease, skin discoloration, and bleeding from the nose and gums. If left untreated, it can eventually lead to death.

is a type of depression that is related to changes in seasons

Seasonal Affective Disorder (SAD) is a type of depression that is related to changes in the seasons, typically occurring during the winter months. Symptoms of SAD include depression, low energy, difficulty concentrating, oversleeping, and weight gain.

diagnosis: Seizures (children with fever), see Febrile seizures
symptoms: Febrile seizures are seizures caused by a fever in children, usually between the ages of 6 months and 5 years. They usually last less than 15 minutes and the child does not lose consciousness. Symptoms include jerking or shaking of the arms and legs, loss of bladder or bowel control, and staring spells.

diagnosis: Seizures (fits), see What to do if someone has a seizure (fit)
symptoms: Seizures (fits) can cause a person to experience uncontrollable muscle spasms and possible loss of consciousness. Symptoms may include stiffening of the body, jerking or twitching movements, foaming at the mouth, and loss of bladder control.

is a disorder in which a child or adolescent does not speak in certain social settings, such as school.

Selective mutism is a disorder in which a child or adolescent does not speak in certain social settings, such as school. Symptoms of selective mutism include not speaking in certain social settings, such as school, and being very quiet in those settings. Other symptoms may include avoiding eye contact, not responding to verbal cues, and appearing to be in a trance.

are a class of antidepressant medications.

The symptoms of Selective Serotonin Reuptake Inhibitors (SSRIs) are primarily related to depression, such as feeling sad, low energy, difficulty concentrating, and changes in sleep and appetite. Other side effects may include anxiety, agitation, restlessness, irritability, and suicidal thoughts.

is when someone deliberately harms themselves, often as a way of dealing with very difficult feelings, such as deep distress, depression, or anxiety.

Self-harm is a form of coping with difficult feelings, such as deep distress, depression, and anxiety. It involves deliberately hurting oneself in order to cope with overwhelming emotions.

diagnosis: Sense of smell (lost/changed), see Lost or changed sense of smell
symptoms:
is a symptom of COVID-19. It is reported that around 40-50% of people with COVID-19 have experienced a change in their sense of smell or anosmia. Additionally, some people have reported that their sense of taste has also changed.

Around 40-50% of people with COVID-19 have reported a loss or change in their sense of smell, known as anosmia, as well as a change in their sense of taste. These are symptoms of the virus.

is a life-threatening condition that occurs when the body's response to an infection damages its own tissues and organs.

Sepsis is a serious and potentially life-threatening condition caused by an overreaction of the body's immune system to an infection. It can lead to tissue and organ damage, and can be fatal if not treated quickly.

is an infection of the joint.

Septic arthritis is an infection of the joint causing pain, swelling, stiffness, redness, warmth, and decreased range of motion in the affected joint. It is often accompanied by fever, chills, and fatigue.

Septicaemia is a severe form of sepsis, a life-threatening infection in which bacteria or other germs spread through the bloodstream. Symptoms include fever, increased heart rate, confusion, low blood pressure, and difficulty breathing. Other symptoms may include chills, rapid breathing, and decreased urine output.

The person with a severe head injury may experience confusion, seizures, loss of consciousness, blurred vision, difficulty speaking, headaches, and vomiting. They may also have difficulty with balance, coordination, and memory.

can cause a range of different symptoms.

STIs can cause a variety of symptoms including pain, itching, discharge, and burning sensation during urination. Other symptoms may include fever, swollen glands, and fatigue. In some cases, STIs can be asymptomatic.

diagnosis: Shaking, see Tremor or shaking hands
symptoms: The symptom of tremor or shaking hands is characterized by involuntary and rhythmic movements of the hands, arms, legs, and head. It is usually accompanied by a feeling of weakness, fatigue, and unsteadiness. Other symptoms may include difficulty speaking or slurred speech, difficulty writing, and difficulty walking.

diagnosis: Shin pain (shin splints), see Shin splints
symptoms: Shin splints are a common injury that cause pain along the shin bone. Symptoms of shin splints include tenderness, soreness, and pain in the lower leg, usually occurring after exercise. The pain may range from mild to severe, and can worsen when running or jumping.

are a common overuse injury that occurs in the lower leg

Shin splints are an overuse injury that cause pain in the lower leg, typically in the front of the leg or the inside of the leg. Pain is often felt after exercise and is caused by inflammation in the muscles, tendons and bone tissue around the tibia (shin bone).

is characterized by a painful, blistering rash

Shingles is a condition caused by the reactivation of the varicella-zoster virus, the same virus that causes chickenpox. It is characterized by a painful, blistering rash that can appear anywhere on the body, typically in a single stripe around either the left or right side of the torso. It can also cause itching, burning, or tingling sensations, as well as headaches, fever, chills, and fatigue.

is an eye condition where you can see close objects clearly, but distant objects appear blurred

Short-sightedness (myopia) is an eye condition where distant objects appear blurred, while close objects are seen clearly. This condition is caused by a refractive error in the eye, where the eye fails to properly focus light. Symptoms include difficulty seeing objects at a distance, eyestrain, headaches, and squinting.

, chest pain, and a feeling of lightheadedness

The individual is experiencing shortness of breath, chest pain, and a feeling of lightheadedness. These symptoms may be indicative of a medical condition and should be evaluated by a doctor.

syndrome is a condition that causes pain in the shoulder.

Shoulder impingement syndrome is a condition that causes pain and discomfort in the shoulder, typically when the arm is raised or extended. It is caused by the tendons or bursa of the shoulder becoming irritated and inflamed from the bones of the shoulder rubbing together. Symptoms include pain, weakness, and difficulty moving the shoulder.

is a common complaint.

Shoulder pain is a frequent complaint that can range from mild to severe. It can be caused by injury, overuse, or a medical condition. Symptoms may include dull or sharp pain, stiffness, swelling, and decreased range of motion.

is a set of symptoms that affect occupants in a particular building.

Sick Building Syndrome is a condition in which occupants of a particular building experience symptoms such as headaches, eye, nose, and throat irritation, dizziness, nausea, and fatigue. These symptoms are caused by poor air quality in the building and are often exacerbated by inadequate ventilation.

is an inherited blood disorder.

Sickle cell disease is a genetic disorder that affects the red blood cells, causing them to become sickle-shaped and unable to carry oxygen efficiently throughout the body. This can lead to anemia, pain, and other complications.

is an incurable lung disease caused by breathing in tiny bits of silica dust.

Silicosis is an incurable lung disease caused by exposure to silica dust. Symptoms of silicosis include shortness of breath, chronic cough, chest pain, and fatigue. Other symptoms may include fever, weight loss, and clubbing of the fingers and toes.

diagnosis: Sinus cancer, see Nasal and sinus cancer
symptoms:
Sinus cancer, also known as nasal and sinus cancer, is a type of cancer that affects the sinuses and nasal cavity. Symptoms may include a persistent nasal obstruction or congestion, facial pain and pressure, headaches, nasal discharge, and loss of smell. Other symptoms can include vision changes, difficulty speaking, and swelling or lumps on the face. 

Sinus cancer, or nasal and sinus cancer, can cause a variety of symptoms including a persistent nasal obstruction or congestion, facial pain and pressure, headaches, nasal discharge, loss of smell, vision changes, difficulty speaking, and swelling or lumps on the face.

is a common condition in which the cavities around the nasal passages become swollen and inflamed.

Sinusitis is an inflammation of the cavities around the nasal passages which can cause symptoms such as facial pain and pressure, nasal congestion, and a runny nose. It can also cause headaches, bad breath, and a reduced sense of smell or taste.

Sinusitis is an inflammation of the sinuses that can cause a stuffy or runny nose, facial pain and pressure, and difficulty breathing through the nose. It may also cause a sore throat, bad breath, coughing, and fever. It is typically caused by a viral or bacterial infection.

is an autoimmune disorder that affects the glands responsible for producing tears and saliva.

Sjögren's syndrome is an autoimmune disorder that causes dry eyes and mouth due to the glands responsible for producing tears and saliva not working properly. Symptoms include dry eyes, dry mouth, fatigue, joint pain, and dry skin.

diagnosis: Skin cancer (melanoma), see Melanoma skin cancer
symptoms: Melanoma skin cancer is a type of skin cancer which develops from the pigment-containing cells known as melanocytes. It is the most dangerous type of skin cancer and can spread to other parts of the body. Symptoms of melanoma skin cancer include a new mole or a change in an existing mole, such as an increase in size, a change in color, itching or bleeding.

Non-melanoma skin cancer is a type of skin cancer that appears on the epidermis, which is the outer layer of the skin. It can appear as scaly patches, open sores, or growths, and can be either red or brown in color. Symptoms may include a new mole on the skin, changes in the size, shape, or color of an existing mole, or an area of skin that looks inflamed or itchy.

A skin cyst is a closed sac under the skin filled with a cheese-like or oily material. It is usually painless, but may be tender, and can vary in size from pea-sized to several centimeters. Cysts may occur anywhere on the body, but are commonly found on the face, neck, and trunk.

Skin picking disorder is a mental health condition in which a person compulsively picks at their skin, often to the point of causing damage. Symptoms include recurrent skin picking, resulting in skin lesions, and emotional distress or impairment in functioning. It is often accompanied by feelings of shame and guilt, and can lead to significant social, occupational and psychological difficulties.

are small, soft, flesh-coloured growths on the skin.

Skin tags are benign growths that appear on the skin and are usually small, soft, and flesh-coloured. They are typically found on the neck, armpits, around the groin, or under the breasts.

is a viral infection which is most common in children.

Slapped cheek syndrome is a viral infection that primarily affects children, causing a distinctive red rash on the face that can spread to the body and limbs. It is accompanied by flu-like symptoms, such as fever, sore throat, fatigue and aching muscles.

is a condition that affects the quality of your sleep
