Sleep apnoea is a condition that causes interrupted breathing during sleep. Symptoms of this condition include snoring, daytime sleepiness, waking up gasping for air, and morning headaches. It can also lead to long-term health problems such as high blood pressure, heart attack, and stroke.

is a condition in which a person feels conscious but unable to move.

Sleep paralysis is a condition in which a person is conscious but unable to move or speak. They may also experience hallucinations and difficulty breathing. Other symptoms may include an intense feeling of pressure on the chest, feeling as if one is being watched, and fear.

is a sleep disorder in which people talk, walk, eat, or perform other activities while asleep

Sleepwalking is a sleep disorder in which people perform activities such as talking, walking, eating, or other activities while asleep without being aware of what they are doing. It is usually associated with an altered state of consciousness, impaired memory, and confusion upon waking.

A slipped disc is a medical condition caused by a displacement of a vertebra in the spine, which can cause back pain, numbness, and tingling in the legs. It can also cause weakness and difficulty moving the legs.

ation is a surgical procedure in which a healthy small intestine from a donor is transplanted into a person whose small intestine no longer functions.

The symptoms of needing a small bowel transplantation are an inability to absorb nutrients from food, chronic diarrhea, and dehydration. Other symptoms can include intestinal infections, abdominal pain, and weight loss.

A smear test, or cervical screening, is a test used to detect abnormal cells in the cervix. It is used to detect early signs of cancer or other diseases in the cervix. Symptoms of cervical screening may include bleeding between periods, pain during sex, or an unusual discharge from the vagina.

can be embarrassing and can lead to social anxiety.

Smelly feet can be a source of embarrassment and can cause people to feel anxious in social situations. The smell is usually caused by sweat and bacteria, and can be particularly bad in warm and moist environments.

, cloudy urine, and fever

The individual is experiencing smelly urine, cloudy urine, and a fever. These symptoms could indicate a urinary tract infection, and should be checked out by a doctor.

diagnosis: Smoking (treatments to stop), see Stop smoking treatments
symptoms: Smoking can lead to serious health problems. To help people stop smoking, there are a variety of treatments available, including medication, counseling, and support groups. These treatments can help reduce the physical and psychological dependence on nicotine and make quitting easier.

Snake bites are puncture wounds that can cause pain, swelling, redness, and bleeding. In severe cases, they can cause tissue death, infection, and even organ failure. Symptoms of a snake bite may include dizziness, nausea, vomiting, and difficulty breathing.

, tiredness, and difficulty concentrating

The person is experiencing snoring, tiredness, and difficulty concentrating, which could indicate a sleep disorder. They may be suffering from sleep apnea, which is a condition that causes pauses in breathing while sleeping. These pauses can cause fatigue, snoring, and difficulty concentrating during the day.

Social anxiety (social phobia) is an intense fear of social situations and being judged by others. It can cause physical symptoms such as trembling, sweating, blushing, and an increased heart rate. People with social anxiety may feel embarrassed, anxious, and scared in social situations, and may avoid them altogether. They may also worry excessively about the potential consequences of social situations.

are a type of cancer that can arise in any part of the body

Soft tissue sarcomas are a type of cancer that can occur in any part of the body and affect tissue such as muscle, fat, blood vessels, and deep skin tissues. Symptoms of soft tissue sarcomas may include a lump or swelling, pain, or a change in the size or shape of the affected area. Other symptoms may include fatigue, difficulty breathing, and changes in skin color.

Soiling is when a child involuntarily poos their pants. It is most common in children aged between 3 and 5 years old. They may not be aware that it is happening, and may not be able to control it. Soiling can cause embarrassment and distress for the child.

diagnosis: Solar keratoses, see Actinic keratoses (solar keratoses)
symptoms: Actinic keratoses (solar keratoses) are growths on the skin caused by long-term sun exposure. They typically appear as rough, scaly patches that range in color from light pink to dark brown. They can be itchy, tender, and may even bleed. They are most commonly found on areas of the skin that are frequently exposed to the sun, such as the face, hands, arms, and scalp.

diagnosis: Sore lips, see Sore or dry lips
symptoms:
can be caused by a variety of factors, such as dehydration, sunburn, and cold weather.

The symptoms of sore or dry lips include dryness, cracking, and chapping of the lips. They may also have a burning sensation or feel tight and uncomfortable. Dehydration, sunburn, and cold weather can all contribute to the development of sore or dry lips.

, chapped lips, and redness

The symptoms described are related to dryness and irritation of the lips. These include soreness, dryness, chapping, and redness.

, fever, chills, and body aches

The symptoms described indicate a possible infection. They include a sore or white tongue, fever, chills, and body aches.

, runny nose, headache

The person has a sore throat, a runny nose, and a headache. These are typical symptoms of a common cold or the flu.

diagnosis: Sperm count (low), see Low sperm count
symptoms: Low sperm count is a condition where a man has fewer than 15 million sperm per milliliter of semen. Symptoms of low sperm count include difficulty conceiving, reduced sex drive, and decreased semen volume.

is a birth defect that affects the spine.

Spina bifida is a birth defect that affects the spinal cord and surrounding bones of the spine. It is caused by a failure of the spine to close properly during embryonic development. Symptoms of spina bifida can include physical and neurological problems such as paralysis of the legs, bladder and bowel control issues, and hydrocephalus.

is a genetic disorder that affects the control of muscle movement.

Spinal muscular atrophy is a genetic disorder that causes muscle weakness and loss of control over muscle movement. It can lead to difficulty walking, speaking, swallowing, and breathing.

results showed a decrease in FEV1 and FVC with a decreased FEV1/FVC ratio

The patient's spirometry results indicated a decrease in both Forced Expiratory Volume in one second (FEV1) and Forced Vital Capacity (FVC). Additionally, the FEV1/FVC ratio was reduced, suggesting obstruction in the airways.

The most common symptom of spleen problems is abdominal pain or discomfort in the upper-left side of the abdomen. Other symptoms may include feeling full quickly after eating, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, and fever. In some cases, spleen removal may be necessary to treat spleen problems.

is a condition in which one vertebra in the spine slips out of its normal position onto the vertebra below it.

Spondylolisthesis is a condition in which one vertebra in the spine slips out of its normal position onto the vertebra below it, causing pain, stiffness, and a decreased range of motion in the spine. It can also cause nerve compression, leading to numbness, tingling, and weakness in the legs.

are injuries that can cause pain, swelling, and difficulty moving the affected area.

Sprains and strains are injuries that affect the muscles, tendons, and ligaments. Symptoms include pain, swelling, and difficulty moving the affected area. In some cases, bruising and tenderness may also be present.

diagnosis: Squamous cell carcinoma, see Skin cancer (non-melanoma)
symptoms: Squamous cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that affects the cells of the outer layer of the skin. It is usually caused by prolonged exposure to ultraviolet light and can result in lesions, sores, and hard, scaly patches on the skin. It can also cause changes in skin color, and can spread to other parts of the body.

ing and difficulty seeing at night

Squinting is a symptom of difficulty seeing, and difficulty seeing at night is a symptom of an eye condition. These two symptoms together could indicate a vision problem that needs to be addressed by an eye doctor.

is a speech disorder in which the normal flow of speech is disrupted by repetitions, prolongations, pauses and blocks

Stammering is a speech disorder that causes disruptions in the normal flow of speech, such as repeating words and phrases, prolonging sounds, and pausing and blocking when trying to speak.

Staph infection is a bacterial infection caused by Staphylococcus aureus. Symptoms can include redness, swelling, pain, and drainage of pus. In more severe cases, fever, chills, and fatigue may also occur.

are a type of drug used to reduce cholesterol levels in the body.

Statins are used to lower cholesterol levels in the body, which can reduce the risk of heart disease and stroke. They work by blocking the body's production of cholesterol, and by reducing the amount of cholesterol absorbed from food. Common side effects include nausea, muscle aches and headaches.

diagnosis: Stem cell and bone marrow transplants
symptoms:
are used to treat leukemia, a cancer of the blood and bone marrow.

Leukemia is a cancer of the blood and bone marrow that is treated with stem cell and bone marrow transplants. These transplants involve replacing unhealthy cells with healthy cells to help the body fight off the cancer.

diagnosis: Stent insertion, see Coronary angioplasty and stent insertion
symptoms: Stent insertion is a procedure used in coronary angioplasty to open narrowed or blocked arteries. It involves the placement of a stent, a tiny mesh tube, in the affected artery to improve blood flow and reduce the risk of further blockages. Symptoms of blocked arteries can include chest pain, shortness of breath, and fatigue.

Topical corticosteroids are steroid creams used to treat skin conditions such as eczema, psoriasis, and dermatitis. They can reduce inflammation, redness, itching, and swelling. They can also help to soften and heal the skin. Side effects can include irritation, burning, and thinning of the skin.

are used to treat asthma.

Steroid inhalers are a type of medication used to treat asthma symptoms. They are inhaled directly into the lungs and can help reduce inflammation in the airways, reduce the frequency and severity of asthma attacks, and improve breathing.

are used to treat a variety of conditions, including joint pain and inflammation.

Steroid injections are used to reduce joint pain and inflammation caused by a variety of conditions. They are injected directly into the affected area to reduce swelling and discomfort.

diagnosis: Steroid misuse, see Anabolic steroid misuse
symptoms: Anabolic steroid misuse is the use of anabolic steroids without a prescription or in a way that is not intended by a doctor. Symptoms of misuse include an increase in aggressive behavior, mood swings, and depression. It can also lead to physical changes such as increased muscle mass, deepening of the voice, and increased facial hair.

are medications that are used to treat nasal congestion

Steroid nasal sprays are medications used to treat nasal congestion. Symptoms of nasal congestion include nasal blockage, nasal discharge, and difficulty breathing through the nose. These medications work by reducing inflammation in the nasal passages, allowing for easier breathing.

can help reduce swelling, pain and stiffness in joints

Steroid tablets can be used to treat joint-related conditions, such as inflammation, pain, and stiffness. They reduce swelling, reduce pain, and improve joint mobility.

can cause a variety of side effects, including:

Steroid use can lead to a variety of side effects, such as increased blood pressure, increased risk of infection, weight gain, mood swings, and increased risk of developing certain types of cancer. It can also lead to infertility, damage to the liver, and decreased bone density.

is a rare, serious disorder of your skin and mucous membranes.

Stevens-Johnson Syndrome is a rare and serious disorder that affects the skin and mucous membranes. Symptoms may include a red or purple skin rash that spreads and forms blisters, fever, sore throat, burning eyes, and mouth ulcers. Additionally, the skin may blister, peel, and become painful.

is the death of a baby in the womb before the 20th week of pregnancy.

Stillbirth is the death of a baby in the womb before it has reached 20 weeks gestation. Symptoms include the absence of fetal movement and a lack of a fetal heartbeat. Other signs can include a lack of amniotic fluid and/or a lack of fetal growth.

diagnosis: Sting or bite (insect), see Insect bites and stings
symptoms: Insect bites and stings can cause a variety of symptoms, including pain, swelling, itching, and redness. In some cases, an allergic reaction may occur, which can cause more severe symptoms such as hives, difficulty breathing, and swelling of the face and throat.

, feeling of nausea, dizziness

The patient is experiencing stomach ache, feeling of nausea, and dizziness.

diagnosis: Stomach bug, see Diarrhoea and vomiting
symptoms: A stomach bug is a type of infection which can cause symptoms such as diarrhoea and vomiting. These symptoms may also be accompanied by nausea, abdominal pain, fever, and loss of appetite.

symptoms can include:

Stomach cancer can cause a variety of symptoms, including abdominal pain, weight loss, nausea, vomiting, and blood in the stool. It can also cause fatigue, loss of appetite, and difficulty swallowing.

is characterized by a burning sensation in the stomach area and pain in the upper abdomen.

Stomach ulcer is a medical condition that causes a burning sensation in the stomach area and pain in the upper abdomen. It is usually accompanied by other symptoms such as nausea, loss of appetite, and weight loss.

can help you quit smoking, but it is important to remember that there is no one-size-fits-all approach to quitting.

Stop smoking treatments can provide a useful aid in helping people to quit smoking, however, there is no single method that works for everyone. It is important to find the right approach that works best for an individual in order to successfully quit smoking.

, frequent headaches, and fatigue

The symptoms described in the text are irregular periods, frequent headaches, and fatigue. These symptoms could indicate a variety of underlying medical conditions.

infection can cause a sore throat, fever, and swollen lymph nodes in the neck.

Strep A infection can cause a sore throat, fever, and swollen lymph nodes in the neck, which are common signs and symptoms of the infection.

are caused by rapid stretching of the skin

Stretch marks are visible lines on the skin that appear when the skin is stretched too quickly. They are usually pink or purple in color, and can be seen on areas of the body where the skin has been stretched, such as the abdomen, thighs, hips, breasts, and upper arms. These marks can also be itchy or painful.

A stroke is a medical condition in which a blockage or rupture in the brain's blood vessels causes a disruption in the supply of oxygen and nutrients to the brain. Symptoms of stroke can include sudden numbness or weakness in the face, arm or leg, confusion, difficulty speaking or understanding speech, difficulty seeing in one or both eyes, difficulty walking, dizziness, and a severe headache.

Stuttering, or Stammering, is a speech disorder characterized by repetition of sounds, syllables, or words, prolongation of sounds, and interruptions in speech known as blocks. It is typically accompanied by struggle behavior, secondary behaviors, and/or avoidance of certain speaking situations.

is an infection of the eyelid caused by bacteria

A stye is an infection of the eyelid that is caused by bacteria. Symptoms include redness, swelling, tenderness, and pain around the affected area. In some cases, a yellowish-white bump may appear on the eyelid.

Subarachnoid haemorrhage is a type of stroke caused by bleeding into the space between the brain and the tissue that covers the brain. Symptoms include severe headache, vomiting, decreased consciousness, stiff neck, and seizures. Other symptoms may include confusion, drowsiness, and nausea.

Subdural haematoma is a type of head injury that occurs when a blood vessel in the brain ruptures and bleeds into the space between the brain and the skull. Symptoms of subdural haematoma include headache, confusion, blurred vision, nausea, vomiting, seizures, and weakness or paralysis on one side of the body. In severe cases, unconsciousness, coma, and death can occur.

is a symptom of many medical conditions.

Sudden confusion, also known as delirium, is a symptom that can indicate a variety of underlying medical conditions. It can manifest as disorientation, difficulty with concentration, and changes in behavior.

is the sudden, unexplained death of an infant younger than 1 year old.

Sudden Infant Death Syndrome (SIDS) is a term used to describe the sudden and unexplained death of a baby under one year of age. It is most common in babies between two and four months old. Symptoms include sudden death without warning or obvious cause.

diagnosis: Suicidal thoughts, see Help for suicidal thoughts
symptoms: The text describes someone experiencing suicidal thoughts. Symptoms include feeling hopeless, feeling overwhelming sadness and guilt, feeling trapped, and having difficulty sleeping. The person may also experience suicidal ideations or plans, and may engage in self-destructive behaviors. It is important to seek help if someone is having suicidal thoughts.

is a result of overexposure to ultraviolet radiation from the sun

Sunburn is a skin condition caused by overexposure to ultraviolet radiation from the sun. Symptoms include redness, swelling, pain, and blisters on the skin. Skin may also become itchy, dry, and tender to the touch. In severe cases, sunburn may cause fever and nausea.

Superficial thrombophlebitis is a condition in which a blood clot forms in a vein just beneath the surface of the skin. Symptoms include pain, tenderness, redness, and swelling in the affected area. Other symptoms may include warmth, itching, and a hard cord-like feeling along the affected vein.

is a condition that causes an abnormally fast heart rate.

Supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) is a condition that affects the heart rate, causing it to beat abnormally fast. Symptoms include palpitations, chest pain, dizziness, and shortness of breath.

diagnosis: Surgery (having an operation), see Having an operation (surgery)
symptoms: Having an operation (surgery) is a medical procedure that involves cutting into the body to repair or remove damaged or diseased tissue. It is typically done under general anesthesia and can involve a variety of techniques, such as incisions, sutures, and the use of medical instruments. Surgery can be used to treat a variety of ailments, from broken bones to cancer.

diagnosis: Swallowing pills, see Problems swallowing pills
symptoms: The patient is having difficulty swallowing pills, which is causing disruption in their daily life. They may be experiencing gagging, coughing, or choking when trying to swallow pills. They may also be having trouble getting the pill past the throat.

Dysphagia is a condition in which a person has difficulty swallowing. Symptoms may include the sensation of food sticking in the throat, pain or discomfort when swallowing, and coughing or choking when eating or drinking. Other symptoms may include regurgitation of food, trouble breathing while eating or drinking, and weight loss.

diagnosis: Sweat rash, see Heat rash (prickly heat)
symptoms: Heat rash, also known as sweat rash or prickly heat, is a skin irritation caused by excessive sweating. Symptoms include small bumps or blisters on the skin that can be itchy and uncomfortable.

Excessive sweating (hyperhidrosis) is a condition characterized by excessive sweating beyond what is necessary to maintain normal body temperature. It can affect the whole body or just certain areas, such as the palms, soles, and face. Symptoms include sweating even when the body does not need to cool itself, sweating that is not related to heat or exercise, and sweating that affects daily activities.
The patient is experiencing excessive sweating and heat rash (prickly heat). The heat rash may be accompanied by itching, redness, and small bumps on the skin.

diagnosis: Sweating at night, see Night sweats
symptoms: Night sweats are a symptom of excessive sweating during sleep. It is often accompanied by feelings of heat and discomfort. It can be caused by various medical conditions, such as infections, hormonal imbalances, and certain medications.
The patient is experiencing oedema, which is swelling of the ankles, feet and legs. This can be caused by fluid retention and is usually accompanied by pain or discomfort.
The person is experiencing oedema, which is swelling caused by excess fluid trapped in the body's tissue. The symptom is present in the arms and hands.

in the neck, armpits, and groin

The symptoms of swollen glands in the neck, armpits, and groin indicate an infection or an immune system issue. Swollen glands are usually tender and may be accompanied by a fever.

is a sexually transmitted infection that can cause serious health problems if it is not treated.

Syphilis is a sexually transmitted infection that can lead to serious health issues if left untreated. Symptoms can include sores, rashes, fever, and swollen lymph nodes. If left untreated, it can lead to organ damage, blindness, paralysis, and even death.

Tailbone pain is a common issue that can cause achy, dull, or sharp pain in the area of the coccyx. It can be caused by sitting for long periods of time, childbirth, or trauma to the area. It can also be a symptom of an underlying medical condition such as an infection or tumor.

Tapeworms are worms that live in the intestines of humans and can cause a variety of symptoms. These can include abdominal pain, loss of appetite, weight loss, and diarrhea. Tapeworms can also cause nutritional deficiencies due to the fact that they absorb nutrients from the host. In extreme cases, the worms can cause anemia, seizures, and even death.

is an inherited disorder that causes progressive destruction of the nervous system

Tay-Sachs disease is a genetic disorder that results in the progressive destruction of the nervous system. Symptoms of the disorder include a decrease in muscle tone, vision and hearing loss, seizures, and an inability to swallow or speak. Over time, the disease leads to mental and physical disability, and eventually death.

Tuberculosis (TB) is an infectious disease caused by bacteria that usually affects the lungs. Common symptoms include a persistent cough with blood-tinged sputum, night sweats, fever, weight loss, and fatigue. TB can be spread through the air when people who have the disease cough, sneeze, or speak.

Tuberculosis (TB) is a contagious infection caused by bacteria that primarily affects the lungs. Symptoms of TB include a persistent cough with bloody sputum, night sweats, fever, weight loss, and fatigue. TB is spread through the air when an infected person coughs, sneezes, or talks.

is a condition in which you grind, gnash or clench your teeth.

Teeth grinding (bruxism) is a condition in which a person grinds, gnashes, or clenches their teeth involuntarily. This can cause pain, headaches, and damage to the teeth and jaw.

strips can cause sensitivity in the teeth

Teeth whitening strips can lead to increased sensitivity in the teeth, causing discomfort and pain when consuming hot or cold foods and beverages. Sensitivity can also manifest as pain when brushing or flossing the teeth.

is a disorder of the arteries that supply blood to the scalp and head.

Temporal arteritis is a disorder that affects the arteries that supply blood to the scalp and head, causing inflammation, pain, and tenderness in the affected area. It can also lead to headaches, vision loss, and jaw pain.

is characterized by pain in the jaw joint and muscles that control jaw movement

Temporomandibular disorder (TMD) is a condition characterized by pain in the jaw joint and muscles that control jaw movement. Symptoms of TMD include difficulty opening and closing the mouth, difficulty chewing, and jaw pain when talking or yawning. Other symptoms may include headaches, neck pain, and earache.

is an inflammation of the tendon that can be caused by repetitive movement or strain

Tendonitis is a condition that is characterized by inflammation of a tendon, which is a band of tough fibrous tissue that connects muscle to bone. It is commonly caused by repetitive movements or strain, and can result in pain, tenderness, stiffness, and swelling in the affected area.

is a painful condition that occurs when tendons in your elbow are overworked

Tennis Elbow is a condition caused by overuse of the elbow joint, resulting in pain and tenderness in the area. It is usually caused by repetitive motions, such as those used in playing tennis, that strain the tendons in the elbow. Common symptoms include pain and tenderness when moving the elbow, difficulty gripping objects, and a weak grip.

is a non-invasive treatment that uses low-voltage electrical current to stimulate the nerves for pain relief.

TENS is a non-invasive treatment that uses low-voltage electrical current to provide relief from pain. It stimulates the nerves to reduce discomfort and improve mobility. It is a safe and effective way to manage pain.

, also known as stress headaches, are recurring headaches that cause mild to moderate pain.

Tension headaches, also known as stress headaches, are a common type of headache that cause mild to moderate pain. They usually occur in the form of a recurring headache, with the pain often felt as a pressure-like sensation around the head and neck.

The symptoms of testicle lumps and swellings include a noticeable lump or swelling in one or both testicles, pain or discomfort in the testicles, a feeling of heaviness in the scrotum, and a dull ache in the lower abdomen or groin area.

is a symptom of a variety of conditions

Testicle pain is a symptom which can indicate a number of underlying conditions. It can range from a dull ache to a sharp stabbing sensation and can be caused by physical injury, infection, or a medical condition. It is important to seek medical attention if the pain is severe or persists for an extended period of time.

can cause a number of symptoms, the most common being a lump or enlargement in a testicle.

Testicular cancer can cause a variety of symptoms, the most common of which is a lump or enlargement in one of the testicles. Other symptoms may include a feeling of heaviness in the scrotum, a dull ache in the lower abdomen or groin, and a sudden collection of fluid in the scrotum.

is an infection caused by the bacterium Clostridium tetani

Tetanus is a serious infection caused by the bacterium Clostridium tetani. Symptoms include muscle spasms, difficulty swallowing, stiffness in the jaw, fever, and sweating. It can also cause seizures and can be fatal if left untreated.

is a blood disorder that affects the production of haemoglobin

Thalassaemia is a genetic blood disorder that affects the production of haemoglobin, which is the protein in red blood cells that carries oxygen throughout the body. Symptoms of thalassaemia can include pale skin, fatigue, shortness of breath, dark urine, and an enlarged spleen.

can affect men between the ages of 40 and 55.

The 'male menopause' is a condition that affects men between the ages of 40 and 55, causing a variety of symptoms such as fatigue, difficulty sleeping, decreased libido, and irritability.

Excessive thirst is a symptom of an underlying medical condition where a person experiences an increased desire to drink fluids. It can be accompanied by other symptoms such as dry mouth, increased urination, and weight loss.

diagnosis: Thoracic outlet syndrome, see Cervical rib
symptoms: Thoracic Outlet Syndrome is a group of disorders caused by compression of the nerves, arteries, and/or veins in the thoracic outlet (the space between the collarbone and the first rib). Symptoms include pain, numbness, tingling, and/or weakness in the neck, shoulder, arm, and/or hand. Cervical rib syndrome is a type of Thoracic Outlet Syndrome caused by a cervical rib (extra rib) that compresses the nerves and/or blood vessels in the thoracic outlet. Symptoms include pain, tingling, numbness, and/or weakness in the neck, shoulder, arm, and/or hand.

are parasites that live in the intestine

Threadworms are parasites that cause an infection in the intestine. Symptoms of infection include itching and irritation around the anus, disturbed sleep, and stomach pain. Other symptoms may include loss of appetite, nausea, and general tiredness.

A sore throat is a condition in which the throat is sore and irritated, and may be accompanied by pain, especially when swallowing. It is also commonly accompanied by swollen lymph nodes, hoarseness, and a fever. Other symptoms may include a cough, runny nose, and headache.

is a condition in which the blood has an increased tendency to form clots.

Thrombophilia is a condition where the blood has a higher likelihood of forming clots. Symptoms may include recurrent deep vein thrombosis, pulmonary embolism, recurrent miscarriages, and unexplained stroke.

is a fungal infection caused by the yeast Candida albicans.

Thrush is a fungal infection caused by the yeast Candida albicans, which affects both men and women. Symptoms of thrush can include itching, burning, and pain in the affected area. White patches may also appear on the skin or inside the mouth.
The person is experiencing pain in their thumb. The pain may be localized or spread throughout the thumb. It could be sharp, dull or aching and may be accompanied by stiffness or swelling.

is a cancer that begins in the cells of the thyroid gland

Thyroid cancer is a type of cancer that starts in the cells of the thyroid gland. Symptoms of thyroid cancer may include a lump in the neck, hoarseness, difficulty speaking or swallowing, and pain in the neck or throat. Other symptoms may include fatigue, weight gain, and an increase in sweating.

is an inflammation of the thyroid gland.

Thyroiditis is an inflammation of the thyroid gland which can cause pain, swelling, difficulty swallowing, and difficulty breathing. Other symptoms include fatigue, weakness, hoarseness, a rapid or irregular heartbeat, and weight loss or gain.

Transient ischaemic attack (TIA) is a type of stroke that causes temporary symptoms such as sudden weakness or numbness in the face, arm or leg, confusion, difficulty speaking or understanding speech, vision problems, dizziness or loss of balance or coordination. Symptoms usually last for a few minutes or hours and go away completely.

is a viral infection of the central nervous system.

TBE is a viral infection that affects the central nervous system and can cause symptoms such as fever, headache, nausea, and weakness. It can also cause more serious complications such as meningitis, encephalitis, and seizures. Left untreated, it can be fatal.

are sudden, rapid, recurrent, non-rhythmic, involuntary movements or vocalizations.

Tics are sudden, uncontrollable movements or vocalizations that occur rapidly and repeatedly in a non-rhythmic pattern. They are involuntary and happen without warning.

Tight foreskin (phimosis) is a condition where the foreskin is too tight to be pulled back over the head of the penis. It can cause difficulty in urinating and may lead to infection, inflammation and pain. It can also cause discomfort during sexual intercourse.

is a condition that causes a ringing or buzzing in the ears.

Tinnitus is a condition that causes a ringing or buzzing sound in the ears. It is not a disease, but a symptom of an underlying condition. It can range from a mild nuisance to a debilitating condition. It can be experienced as a single sound or a combination of sounds, including ringing, buzzing, hissing, or humming.

, swelling, redness, and warmth

The patient is experiencing toe pain, swelling, redness, and warmth, which could be indicative of an infection or injury.

diagnosis: Tongue (sore or white), see Sore or white tongue
symptoms:
A sore or white tongue can be a symptom of several medical issues. It may have a white coating, be swollen, have red spots or bumps, be tender to the touch, or have a bad taste in the mouth. It can also be accompanied by other symptoms such as a fever, mouth sores, and difficulty swallowing. 

A sore or white tongue is often a symptom of an underlying medical issue, such as an infection or an allergic reaction. It may appear swollen, have a white coating, red spots or bumps, be tender to the touch, or have a bad taste in the mouth. It may also be accompanied by other symptoms such as a fever, mouth sores, or difficulty swallowing.

Tongue cancer is a type of mouth cancer that affects the tongue. Symptoms of tongue cancer include a sore on the tongue that does not heal, pain or numbness in the tongue, a lump on the tongue, difficulty swallowing, and changes in the way the tongue looks or feels.

is a condition where the thin piece of skin that connects the bottom of the tongue to the floor of the mouth is too short, thick or tight

Tongue-tie is a condition in which the thin piece of skin connecting the tongue to the floor of the mouth is too short, thick, or tight, resulting in limited mobility of the tongue. This can make it difficult to speak, eat, and swallow properly.

is a common condition that causes swelling of the tonsils, located at the back of the throat.

Tonsillitis is an inflammation of the tonsils, which are located in the back of the throat. Symptoms include swelling, sore throat, difficulty swallowing, bad breath and fever.

diagnosis: Tooth (chipped or broken), see Chipped, broken or cracked tooth
symptoms:
A chipped, broken or cracked tooth can cause pain and sensitivity to hot, cold or sweet foods and drinks. It can also cause pain when biting or chewing. In some cases, a cracked tooth can also cause swelling and tenderness of the gums.

A chipped, broken or cracked tooth can cause pain, sensitivity to hot, cold or sweet foods and drinks, pain when biting or chewing, as well as swelling and tenderness of the gums in some cases.

is a common problem that can cause pain and discomfort.

Tooth decay is a dental issue that causes pain and discomfort. It is characterized by the breakdown of the enamel and dentin of the tooth, leading to cavities, abscesses, and other issues.

diagnosis: Tooth knocked out, see Knocked-out tooth
symptoms: A knocked-out tooth is a dental emergency in which a tooth becomes completely dislodged from its socket. It can be accompanied by bleeding, pain, and swelling. The patient may also feel dizzy or faint. Treatment should be sought immediately to try and save the tooth.

is a common problem

Toothache is a common problem that is characterized by pain and discomfort in the teeth and/or gums. It can range from mild to severe and can be caused by a variety of factors, such as cavities, gum disease, and infection. Common symptoms include throbbing pain, sensitivity to hot and cold, swelling of the gums, bad breath, and difficulty chewing.

are the most common treatment for contact dermatitis.

Contact dermatitis is a condition that causes skin irritation and inflammation due to contact with an allergen or irritant. The most common symptoms of contact dermatitis include redness, itching, swelling, and burning. Topical corticosteroids are often used to treat contact dermatitis, as they help reduce inflammation, redness, and itching.

diagnosis: Total iron-binding capacity (TIBC) and transferrin test
symptoms: The Total Iron-Binding Capacity (TIBC) and Transferrin Test are used to diagnose iron deficiency anemia, which is a condition where the body does not have enough healthy red blood cells due to a lack of iron. The TIBC test measures the amount of transferrin, which is a protein that transports iron in the body, while the Transferrin Test measures the amount of transferrin that is saturated with iron. Symptoms of iron deficiency anemia include fatigue, pallor, and shortness of breath.

is a common blood test

A total protein test measures the total amount of protein in a person's blood. It is used to help diagnose and monitor conditions such as kidney and liver disease, malnutrition, and other metabolic disorders. It can also help determine if a person has an infection or inflammation.

Tourette's syndrome is a neurological disorder characterized by repetitive, involuntary movements and vocalizations called tics. Symptoms may include eye blinking, facial grimacing, shoulder shrugging, and head and arm jerking. Affected individuals may also make involuntary sounds such as grunting, throat-clearing, or barking.

is a severe, life-threatening illness

Toxic shock syndrome is a serious and potentially fatal illness that is caused by a bacterial toxin. Symptoms can include fever, low blood pressure, confusion, rash, vomiting, diarrhea, muscle aches, and redness of the eyes, mouth, and throat. It can lead to shock, organ failure, and death if left untreated.

is a parasitic infection caused by roundworms, which is spread to humans through contact with contaminated soil, or accidental ingestion of roundworm eggs.

Toxocariasis is an infection caused by roundworms that can be spread to humans through contact with contaminated soil or accidentally ingesting roundworm eggs. Symptoms can include fatigue, abdominal pain, coughing, wheezing, rash, joint pain, and fever.

is caused by a parasite found in cat feces.

Toxoplasmosis is an infection caused by the parasite Toxoplasma gondii, which is commonly found in cat feces. Symptoms may include fever, fatigue, headache, muscle pain, swollen lymph nodes, sore throat, and rash. In some cases, the infection can cause serious complications like blindness, mental disability, and even death.

is a surgical procedure to create an opening in the trachea, or windpipe.

Tracheostomy is a surgical procedure that involves creating an opening in the trachea, or windpipe. This opening allows for direct access to the airway, allowing for easier breathing and the insertion of a breathing tube. This can help with breathing difficulties, such as those caused by sleep apnea, COPD, and other respiratory issues.

Transient ischaemic attack (TIA) is a type of stroke that results in a temporary lack of blood flow to the brain. Symptoms include sudden vision loss, confusion, difficulty speaking, numbness or weakness in the face, arms, or legs, and dizziness or loss of balance. TIA is often referred to as a mini-stroke and can last from a few minutes to a few hours.

is a surgical procedure to treat benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH).

TURP is used to treat benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH), a condition which is characterized by an enlarged prostate that can cause difficulty urinating, frequent urination, weak urine stream, and a feeling of incomplete bladder emptying.

can help protect you from serious diseases that you may come in contact with while traveling

Travel vaccinations can help protect travelers from contracting serious illnesses while abroad, such as hepatitis A, typhoid, yellow fever, and rabies. Vaccines are available to help prevent these diseases and should be considered before any international trip.

, sweating, racing heart

The individual is experiencing trembling or shaking in their hands, excessive sweating, and a racing heart. These are symptoms of anxiety or a panic attack.

diagnosis: Tremor, see Tremor or shaking hands
symptoms: Tremor is a symptom characterized by involuntary, rhythmic shaking of the hands, arms, legs, head, or trunk. It can be caused by a variety of underlying conditions, such as Parkinson's disease, multiple sclerosis, essential tremor, and anxiety. Symptoms can vary in intensity, frequency, and duration.

is a common sexually transmitted infection (STI) caused by a parasite.

Trichomoniasis is an STI caused by a parasite which can cause symptoms such as itching, burning, pain, and/or a foul-smelling discharge from the genitals. It can also cause pain during urination and sex.

is an impulse control disorder characterized by the repeated urge to pull out one’s hair.

Trichotillomania is an impulse control disorder where people have an urge to pull out their own hair. This can cause significant hair loss and bald patches. Other symptoms include feelings of tension before pulling, and a sense of relief or satisfaction after pulling.

(TN) is a chronic pain disorder that affects the trigeminal nerve.

Trigeminal neuralgia is a chronic pain disorder that affects the trigeminal nerve and causes intense, stabbing, sudden pain in the face, usually on one side. Symptoms may include sharp, shooting pain, a burning sensation, or a stabbing pain that radiates from the jaw to the forehead.

is a condition that causes the fingers or thumb to click or snap when bent and straightened

Trigger finger is a condition that affects the fingers or thumbs, causing them to click or snap when bent and straightened. Symptoms include difficulty straightening the finger or thumb, a clicking or popping sensation when the finger is moved, and pain and tenderness in the affected finger or thumb.

is a rare metabolic disorder characterised by a defect in the normal production of the enzyme flavin-containing monooxygenase 3 (FMO3).

Trimethylaminuria is a rare metabolic disorder caused by a defect in the enzyme FMO3. Symptoms of the disorder include an unpleasant body odour, which has been described as fish-like, and difficulty in controlling body odour with normal hygiene practices.

is a bacterial infection that usually affects the lungs

Tuberculosis (TB) is a contagious bacterial infection that primarily affects the lungs. Symptoms of TB can include a persistent cough, chest pain, coughing up blood, fatigue, weight loss, and fever.

is often diagnosed in childhood and can cause physical and neurological symptoms

Tuberous sclerosis is a genetic disorder that causes physical and neurological symptoms, most commonly seen in children. It can cause benign tumors to grow in the brain, skin, heart, lungs, and kidneys, as well as lead to developmental delays, seizures, and autism.

The person is experiencing a stomach ache, which is causing a sharp, cramping pain in their abdomen. The pain may be localized to one area, or it may be more widespread. Other symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, and loss of appetite.

diagnosis: Tummy bug, see Diarrhoea and vomiting
symptoms: The person is suffering from a stomach bug, which is causing them to have diarrhoea and vomiting.

is a genetic disorder that affects a girl's development

Turner Syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects female development. It is caused by the complete or partial absence of the X chromosome in a female’s cells. Symptoms of Turner Syndrome can include short stature, webbed neck, low hairline, and infertility. Other physical symptoms can include heart defects, kidney problems, and hearing loss.

, dizziness, and a feeling of being unwell

The symptoms described in the text are twitching eyes and muscles, dizziness, and a feeling of being unwell. These symptoms could be indicative of a medical condition and should be discussed with a doctor.

is a chronic condition in which the pancreas produces little or no insulin.

Type 1 diabetes is a chronic condition in which the pancreas does not produce enough insulin. Symptoms of this condition include increased thirst, frequent urination, fatigue, blurred vision, weight loss and slow wound healing.

is a chronic condition that affects the way your body metabolizes sugar (glucose).

Type 2 diabetes is a medical condition in which the body does not properly process glucose, leading to high levels of sugar in the bloodstream. This can lead to a range of symptoms including increased thirst, frequent urination, fatigue, blurred vision, and weight gain. Long-term complications can include nerve damage, heart disease, stroke, and kidney damage.

is a bacterial infection.

Symptoms of typhoid fever include high fever, headache, abdominal pain, loss of appetite, constipation, and a rash. In some cases, patients may experience confusion and delirium.

is an infectious disease that is caused by a bacteria called Rickettsia.

Typhus is an infectious disease caused by the bacteria Rickettsia. Symptoms of typhus include high fever, headache, chills, rash, and muscle aches. Complications can include organ failure, central nervous system involvement, and bleeding.

is a chronic inflammatory bowel disease

Ulcerative colitis is an inflammatory bowel disease that causes chronic inflammation in the digestive tract. Symptoms include abdominal pain and cramping, bloody diarrhea, fatigue, and weight loss.

showed a large mass in the right lobe of the liver

An ultrasound scan revealed a large mass in the right lobe of the liver, indicating a possible tumor. The size of the mass was not specified, however it is located in the right lobe of the liver.

An umbilical hernia repair is a surgical procedure to fix a bulge or protrusion near the umbilicus (belly button). Symptoms include a lump or bulge near the umbilicus, pain or discomfort in the area, and/or nausea and vomiting.

Underactive thyroid (hypothyroidism) is a condition that occurs when the thyroid gland does not produce enough thyroid hormones. Symptoms can include fatigue, weight gain, depression, dry skin, constipation, and feeling cold.

, or cryptorchidism, is a condition in which one or both of the testicles, or testes, have not moved down into the scrotum

Cryptorchidism is a condition in which one or both testicles have not moved down into the scrotum, resulting in undescended testicles. It is a common birth defect in males and can cause infertility in adulthood if left untreated.

, fatigue, and feeling weak

The symptoms described in the text are indicating that the individual is experiencing unintentional weight loss, fatigue and feeling weak. These are all signs of an underlying medical condition and should be further investigated by a medical professional.

diagnosis: Upper back pain, see Back pain
symptoms: Upper back pain is a condition characterized by pain in the upper back area, between the neck and lower back. It can be a dull ache or a sharp pain, and can be constant or come and go. It can also be accompanied by muscle tightness or spasms.

Non-gonococcal urethritis (NGU) is a type of urethritis, an inflammation of the urethra caused by an infection. Symptoms of NGU include burning pain during urination, discharge from the urethra, and an urge to urinate more frequently. It is important to seek medical attention if these symptoms are present.

ization is a medical procedure used to collect a urine sample from the bladder.

Urinary catheterization is a medical procedure during which a catheter is inserted through the urethra into the bladder in order to collect a urine sample. It may cause discomfort, pain, burning sensation, and/or bleeding. Other possible symptoms include a frequent urge to urinate, difficulty urinating, and cloudy or bloody urine.

is the sudden and involuntary loss of urine.

Urinary incontinence is an involuntary loss of urine, either in small or large amounts, that occurs suddenly and without warning. It is a common condition that can affect both men and women. Symptoms may include leakage of urine when coughing, sneezing, laughing, or exercising, frequent urges to urinate, and difficulty holding urine in.

are a common cause of burning when urinating

A UTI is an infection of the urinary tract which can cause pain and burning sensations when urinating. Other symptoms may include an increased urge to urinate, cloudy or bloody urine, and a strong odor to the urine.

The patient is experiencing smelly urine, which may indicate an underlying medical condition. It could be a sign of a bladder or urinary tract infection, kidney stones, or a sexually transmitted infection. Other causes could include dehydration, certain foods, and medications.

is a test which measures the level of albumin in the urine.

The Urine Albumin to Creatinine Ratio (ACR) test is used to measure the amount of albumin in the urine. It is used to detect early signs of kidney damage or dysfunction, such as proteinuria, which can be an indication of a serious medical condition.

Uterine cancer is a type of cancer that affects the uterus and can cause abnormal vaginal bleeding, pain during intercourse, and pelvic pain. It can also cause pain in the lower back, pain in the pelvic area, and frequent urination. Uterine cancer is usually treated with surgery, radiation, or chemotherapy.

is a condition where the uvea, or middle layer of the eye, becomes inflamed

Uveitis is an eye condition that causes inflammation of the uvea, or the middle layer of the eye. Symptoms of uveitis include pain, redness, blurred vision, and sensitivity to light. In severe cases, a person may experience floaters, which are spots that appear to move across the field of vision.

symptoms may include unusual vaginal bleeding, such as bleeding between menstrual periods, after intercourse, or after menopause.

Vaginal cancer symptoms can include abnormal vaginal bleeding such as bleeding between menstrual periods, after intercourse, or after menopause. Other symptoms may include pain during intercourse, pelvic pain, and a lump or mass in the vagina.

is most often a normal and regular occurrence.

Vaginal discharge is usually a normal and healthy bodily function, and can be a sign of reproductive health. It can be clear or milky white, and may have a mild odor. It can vary in amount and thickness throughout the menstrual cycle.

, pain during intercourse, and frequent urinary tract infections

The symptoms are: vaginal dryness, pain during intercourse, and frequent urinary tract infections. These symptoms can cause discomfort and can make intercourse difficult or painful. They can also lead to recurrent urinary tract infections, which can be uncomfortable and even painful.

Vulvodynia is a condition that causes persistent, unexplained pain in the vulva (the external female genitalia). Symptoms may include burning, stinging, soreness, itching, or rawness in the area. The pain may be present all the time or may come and go.

is a condition in which the vaginal muscles involuntarily contract when penetration is attempted

Vaginismus is a condition that causes the muscles around the vagina to involuntarily contract and spasm when penetration is attempted. This can cause a great deal of pain and discomfort and can make penetration of any kind impossible.

is an inflammation of the vagina that can result in discharge, itching, and pain.

Vaginitis is a condition that causes inflammation of the vagina, resulting in symptoms such as discharge, itching, and pain. It can be caused by infections, allergies, or other irritants.

is a type of eczema that affects people with varicose veins.

Varicose eczema is a skin condition characterized by itching, dryness, and inflammation of the skin in areas with varicose veins. It may also cause redness, swelling, and cracking of the skin. In severe cases, it can lead to ulceration and infection.

are swollen, twisted veins that you can see just under the skin.

Varicose veins are a medical condition that causes the veins on the skin's surface to become swollen, twisted and enlarged. They are most commonly found in the legs and feet and can cause aching, discomfort and in some cases, skin ulcers.

is a decline in thinking skills caused by conditions that block or reduce blood flow to the brain, such as strokes or hardening of the arteries

Vascular dementia is a type of dementia caused by blockages or reductions in blood flow to the brain, resulting in a decline in thinking skills. It is often associated with stroke and hardening of the arteries. Symptoms can include confusion, difficulty with problem-solving, memory loss, and changes in personality.

is an inflammation of the blood vessels

Vasculitis is a condition in which the blood vessels become inflamed and can cause symptoms such as fever, fatigue, joint pain, skin rash, and organ damage. The most common type of vasculitis is Wegener's Granulomatosis, which can cause swelling, redness, and pain in the affected area. Other forms of vasculitis can affect different organs, such as the kidneys, lungs, or brain.

diagnosis: Vegetative state, see Disorders of consciousness
symptoms: A Vegetative State is a disorder of consciousness in which a person appears to be awake but shows no signs of awareness. They may open their eyes and move spontaneously, but they do not respond to external stimuli and do not initiate purposeful behaviors. They may also exhibit reflex behaviors, such as yawning and swallowing.

A venous leg ulcer is a shallow wound that occurs on the lower leg as a result of poor circulation. Symptoms include aching, itching, swelling, and discoloration of the skin around the affected area. It is often accompanied by pain or burning sensation and can be slow to heal. There may also be an unpleasant odor.

is a feeling of dizziness and a sensation that you, or the environment around you, is spinning or moving.

Vertigo is a feeling of dizziness and disorientation, as if the person or their surroundings are spinning or moving. It can also cause nausea, vomiting, and difficulty with balance.

diagnosis: Vestibular neuritis, see Labyrinthitis and vestibular neuritis
symptoms: Vestibular neuritis (also known as labyrinthitis) is a vestibular disorder caused by inflammation of the vestibular nerve. Symptoms include vertigo, nausea, vomiting, and difficulty walking. Other symptoms may include hearing loss, tinnitus, and fullness in the ear. It is usually treated with rest and medications to reduce nausea and vertigo.

diagnosis: Vestibular schwannoma, see Acoustic neuroma (vestibular schwannoma)
symptoms: Vestibular schwannoma, also known as Acoustic neuroma, is a benign tumor of the nerve that connects the inner ear to the brain. Symptoms of this condition include sudden hearing loss, ringing in the ears (tinnitus), vertigo, balance problems, and facial numbness or weakness.

diagnosis: Vitamin B12 or folate deficiency anaemia
symptoms: Vitamin B12 or folate deficiency anaemia is a type of anaemia caused by a lack of either vitamin B12 or folate. Symptoms of this condition include fatigue, weakness, pale skin, shortness of breath, rapid heart rate, and a sore tongue. In some cases, it can also lead to neurological symptoms such as confusion, memory loss, and difficulty concentrating.

are essential for good health.

Vitamins and minerals are necessary for maintaining overall health. They help the body to grow and develop properly, as well as providing energy and protection from illnesses. Not getting enough vitamins and minerals can lead to a variety of health problems.

is a skin condition where patches of skin lose their pigment.

Vitiligo is a skin condition characterized by the loss of skin pigment, resulting in the appearance of white patches on the skin. These patches may be present on any part of the body, including the face, hands, and arms. The cause of vitiligo is unknown, and there is no cure.

, fatigue, dizziness

The Norovirus, commonly referred to as the "vomiting bug", is a highly contagious virus that causes stomach pain, nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea. It can also cause a low-grade fever, chills, and headaches. Symptoms usually last 12-60 hours and can be severe, leading to dehydration.

The symptoms of Diarrhoea and vomiting include vomiting and frequent watery bowel movements. There may also be abdominal pain and cramps, nausea, and loss of appetite. Other symptoms include fatigue, fever, and dehydration.

is a bleeding disorder

Von Willebrand disease is a bleeding disorder that affects the body's ability to form blood clots and control bleeding. Symptoms may include excessive bleeding, prolonged bleeding from cuts and bruises, prolonged or heavy menstrual periods, and nosebleeds. Other symptoms may include blood in the urine or stool, easy bruising, and joint pain.

can cause a wide range of symptoms.

Vulval cancer can cause itching, burning, and pain in the vulval area, as well as changes in the skin such as lumps, discoloration, and thickening. It can also cause bleeding and discharge.

is a chronic pain syndrome which affects the vulval area.

Vulvodynia is a chronic pain syndrome which affects the vulval area, causing persistent pain and discomfort. Symptoms can range from a burning sensation to severe pain, itching, or stinging. It can last for months or years, and can be aggravated by things such as sitting, exercise, or sexual intercourse.

are caused by the human papillomavirus (HPV).

Warts and verrucas are growths on the skin caused by certain strains of the human papillomavirus (HPV). They often appear on the hands and feet and may be raised, flat, or cauliflower-like in texture. Warts and verrucas can be painful and can spread from person to person.

, runny nose, sneezing, and itchy throat

The person is experiencing common allergy symptoms including watery eyes, a runny nose, sneezing, and an itchy throat.

diagnosis: Weight loss (unexpected), see Unintentional weight loss
symptoms: The patient has experienced unexpected weight loss and has not been able to explain the cause. The weight loss has been unintentional.

diagnosis: Weight loss (unintentional), see Unintentional weight loss
symptoms: Unintentional weight loss is when an individual loses weight without trying. It can be a sign of an underlying medical condition and can be accompanied by a decrease in appetite, fatigue, and an increase in activity levels. Unexplained or significant weight loss should be discussed with a doctor.

is a major operation that has many risks

Weight loss surgery is an invasive procedure with potential risks such as infection, blood clots, and breathing problems. It can also cause nutritional deficiencies, gallstones, and other long-term health issues.

Weil's disease is a type of leptospirosis, an infection caused by a spiral-shaped bacteria called Leptospira. Symptoms of Weil's disease include fever, headache, muscle pain, chills, red eyes, jaundice, and rash. In severe cases, it can cause kidney failure, meningitis, liver failure, and respiratory distress.

is a mosquito-borne illness

West Nile virus is a mosquito-borne illness that can cause fever, headache, body aches, joint pain, vomiting, diarrhea, and rash. It can also result in more serious complications such as neurological issues, including encephalitis and meningitis. Symptoms of West Nile virus include fever, headache, body aches, joint pain, vomiting, diarrhea, and rash. In more serious cases, neurological issues such as encephalitis and meningitis can also occur.

A knee replacement, also known as knee arthroplasty, is a surgical procedure to replace the damaged parts of the knee joint with artificial parts. It is a common procedure for those with knee joint damage caused by arthritis, trauma, or other conditions. Symptoms of a knee replacement include knee pain, stiffness, swelling, instability, and decreased mobility.

An ileostomy is a surgical procedure in which a stoma (an artificial opening) is created in the ileum (the lower part of the small intestine) and brought out through the abdominal wall. It is used to divert waste away from the small intestine, allowing the colon to heal or rest. The waste is collected in an external pouch, which is emptied several times a day.

An ileostomy is a surgical procedure in which an artificial opening is created in the ileum (lower part of the small intestine) and brought out through the abdominal wall. The waste is diverted away from the small intestine and collected in an external pouch, which needs to be emptied several times a day.

diagnosis: What to do if someone has a seizure (fit)
symptoms: If someone has a seizure, it is important to stay calm and keep them safe. Move any dangerous objects away from them and protect their head from injury. It is important to time the seizure and call for medical help if it lasts longer than five minutes. Do not put anything in their mouth or restrain them during the seizure.

is a neck injury caused by a sudden movement of the head, either backward, forward or sideways.

Whiplash is an injury to the neck caused by a forceful and rapid movement of the head in any direction. Symptoms include neck pain and stiffness, headaches, dizziness, blurred vision, and difficulty concentrating.

diagnosis: White blood cell count (low), see Low white blood cell count
symptoms: Low white blood cell count is a condition in which the number of white blood cells in the blood is lower than normal. Symptoms may include fever, fatigue, and increased susceptibility to infection.

diagnosis: Whitlow finger, see Herpetic whitlow (whitlow finger)
symptoms: Herpetic whitlow, also known as whitlow finger, is a viral infection that affects the fingers and toes. Symptoms of the infection include redness and swelling of the affected area, pain, itching, and the formation of small blisters. The blisters may then burst and ooze fluid.

is a contagious respiratory disease

Whooping cough is a highly contagious respiratory disease that is characterized by severe coughing fits, a “whooping” sound when breathing in, and vomiting after coughing. It is most common in infants and young children, and can be spread through contact with an infected person.

Wind, or flatulence, is a common digestive symptom, which can be caused by a variety of factors such as diet, medication, or an underlying medical condition. It is characterized by the passing of gas from the digestive tract, usually accompanied by a sound and an unpleasant odor.

diagnosis: Winter vomiting bug, see Norovirus (vomiting bug)
symptoms: Norovirus, also known as the winter vomiting bug, is a highly contagious virus that causes vomiting and diarrhea. Symptoms usually begin 12 to 48 hours after exposure and can last up to 3 days. Common symptoms include nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, and stomach cramps.
